<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-US,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Honduran Road Project Inaugurated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOCON, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials formally inaugurated a
6.8-mile stretch of road built in a six-month project involving
more than 9,000 U.S. soldiers and National Guardsmen.
   The American troops, who started the project Dec. 28, built a
road linking Jocon, a village in rural Yoro province, and Puente
Grande. About 200 Honduran troops also took part in the project.
   Honduran and American Army and National Guard units have held a
series of joint operations, with the U.S. forces being rotated in
and out of the country for brief periods of duty.
   The final report at a ceremony Monday marking the conclusion of
the road-building project said the U.S. troops also assisted 11,500
Honduran civilians and 8,000 animals in health and veterinary
programs.
   Gen. Frederick Woener, chief of the U.S. Southern Command based
in Panama, attended the ceremony.
   U.S. Embassy sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
another road-building exercise is planned in the summer of 1989 to
build 5.5 miles of road between Jocon and the village of San
Lorenzo.
   At least 60 joint military exercises involving U.S. and Honduran
forces have been held in the past six years.
   The program began after the Reagan administration claimed
Nicaragua's left-wing Sandinista regime threatened other Central
American countries.
</TEXT>
