<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Suicide     06-21 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Suicide,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmer Hangs Self To Protest Opening Of Beef Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cattle farmer committed suicide to protest the
liberalization of Japan's agricultural markets just two days before
a pact to increase U.S. beef and other farm imports was signed,
police said today.
   Ikko Abe, 57, a farmer in Iwate prefecture (state) of northern
Japan, died after hanging himself on Saturday, but details of his
death were not released until today, said a police official who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said Abe left a note saying, ``I oppose the liberalization of
beef imports. I will protest it with my death.''
   Abe owned 50 head of cattle and 2.47 acres of rice paddies, the
official said. Iwate prefecture is the fourth largest producer of
beef in Japan.
   Word of Abe's death came shortly before the United States and
Japan signed an agreement Monday under which Japan will nearly
double its imports of U.S. beef by 1991.
   Tokyo had sought to avoid opening its market to foreign imports
in order to protect its own farmers. As a major concession, the
U.S. agreed to temporary tariffs to soften the impact. Under the
new plan, Japan will establish tariffs of 70 percent in 1991, 60
percent in 1992 and 50 percent in 1993.
</TEXT>
