<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Sendak,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maurice Sendak Teams With Robert Redford to Produce `Peter Pan'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNDANCE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Maurice Sendak says he hopes his
version of ``Peter Pan,'' the first production of a new children's
theater at Robert Redford's Sundance Institute, will not patronize
to its young audience.
   Sendak, whose wildly imaginative illustrations made his
children's book ``Where The Wild Things Are'' a classic, was
appointed artistic director to head the project under an $800,000
grant from the Eccles Foundation, Redford said Sunday at his canyon
resort.
   Other funding will come from AT&T and NBC, Redford said.
   Redford said he had long dreamed of creating a children's
theater and was encouraged by several professional writers,
directors and producers eager to work with him.
   Sendak, who has designed sets for ``The Nutcracker'' and an
opera based on ``Where The Wild Things Are,'' said his objective
was to produce honest, quality theater that children and adults can
enjoy.
   ``Good children's theater does not reduce or patronize,'' he
said. ``There is an unruly and tiresome 4-year-old in me.''
   Redford said the first production of ``Peter Pan'' is planned
for 1990.
