<2ND_LINE>AM-Elderly Shooting,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed, Another Wounded in Hostage-Taking at Senior Citizens
Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 64-year-old man who said he was upset about
drug trafficking was charged Monday with murder after two elderly
neighbors in his senior citizens apartment building were shot and a
third was held hostage for several hours, police said.
   Nathaniel Mayo was accused of shooting two of his neighbors in
the head and leaving them for dead, police said.
   Assistant Police Chief Isaac Fullwood said the two women were
found in a third-floor hallway at about 9:30 a.m. A 65-year-old
woman was pronounced dead at the scene and a 64-year-old woman was
hospitalized in critical condition at The Washington Hospital
Center, Fullwood said.
   Another resident, Neva Williams, 75, was held hostage in
Williams' fourth floor apartment as officers evacuated dozens of
other residents from the 123-unit complex, police said.
   Mayo summoned WJLA-TV reporter Del Walters to the scene, and
Walters, who arrived about 3:30 p.m., eventually persuaded Mayo to
give himself up, officials said.
   Walters said Mayo claimed to have met him last week at the
District Building where he threatened to do ``something drastic''
if measures were not taken to stop drug trafficking in his
neighborhood. Walters said he only vaguely remembered the
conversation.
   Mayo told police Monday night that he has terminal cancer and
``nothing to lose.''
   According to police, Mayo lived in a third-floor apartment
adjacent to the apartments of the two women who were shot.
Neighbors said the dead woman frequently did Mayo's grocery
shopping.
   Police did not release the names of the two shooting victims by
late Monday, but residents of the building identified the dead
woman as Carrie Walls. The injured woman was identified by
residents as Emma Waldo.
</TEXT>
