<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Leach     06-21 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Leach,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wilford Leach, Director of `Drood' and `Pirates of Penzance' Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilford Leach, the Tony Award-winning director
of ``The Mystery of Edwin Drood'' and ``The Pirates of Penzance,''
and the principal director for the New York Shakespeare Festival,
has died of cancer. He was 59.
   Leach died Saturday at home, said Joseph Papp, who runs the
festival and who worked with Leach for more than 10 years.
   ``Wilford was my right hand and my left hand, too, because he
was close to my heart,'' Papp said. ``He really gave me such a
tremendous feeling of loyalty and understood the problems of
running a theater.''
   Leach came to the festival in 1977 as an associate director for
its Central Park production of ``Henry V.'' He stayed to direct
such other outdoor productions as ``All's Well That Ends Well,''
``Othello,'' ``The Taming of the Shrew'' and ``Twelfth Night.''
   ``The Pirates of Penzance'' in 1980 and ``The Mystery of Edwin
Drood'' in 1985 were first performed in Central Park and later
moved to Broadway for long runs. Leach won Tonys as best director
of a musical for both shows.
   Leach was a graduate of the College of William and Mary and
earned a doctorate in dramatic literature at the University of
Illinois. From 1958 until 1981, he was a professor of theater and
film at Sarah Lawrence College.
   Survivors include his mother, Louise and a sister, Doris.
</TEXT>
