<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Nidecker,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Special Aide To Nixon and Ford Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John E. Nidecker, a former special
assistant to former Presidents Richard Nixon and Gerald Ford, died
Monday of cancer at a hospital in this suburb of Washington.
   Nidecker, 75, died at Shady Grove Adventist Hospital.
   He became Nixon's deputy special assistant for congressional
affairs in 1969 and remained on the White House staff after Nixon
resigned in 1974 to work for the Ford administration until 1975.
   During an investigation of Korean influence peddling in
Washington in 1976, it was disclosed that Nidecker had received
$10,000 and other gifts from Korean officials in 1974. He turned
the gifts over to the appropriate authorities and he was not
accused of any wrongdoing.
   Nidecker became a lay brother of the Episcopal Church in 1975
and served as an assistant to the rector of a Damascus, Va. church
and was on the staff of a McLean, Va. church when he retired in
1984.
   The Philadelphia native was educated at the Marine Corps
Institute and LaSalle Extension University and served in the Marine
Corps from 1936-1940.
   He is survived by his wife Jeanne, sons Arnold and Stephen,
brother Arnold and three grandchildren.
</TEXT>
