<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Notebook     06-21 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Notebook,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flag Flap, Whiling Away The Time Without A Deck, Walking
Summiteers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan stood in front of the Rising Sun
banner of Japan to salute the signing of a new U.S.-Japanese
agreement on science and technology _ but not without a flap about
whose flag went where.
   As spectators and journalists gathered in a hotel ballroom to
view Monday's signing ceremony at the seven-nation economic summit,
the American flag stood at the right of the bandstand and the
Japanese on the left.
   About 20 minutes before the ceremony was to start, two Japanese
came out from backstage, picked up the flags, base and all, and
swapped them.
   That was where matters stood for several minutes. Then two
Americans came out, picked up the flags, and put them back where
they were to begin with.
   After Japanese and American aides conferred in an aisle, the
flags were left as the Americans had put them.
   A U.S. official, speaking on condition he not be identified,
explained the goings-on this way:
   The White House maintained that for protocol reasons the
American flag should be on the right at the ceremony, for which
Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita came to the hotel where
Reagan is staying.
   The Japanese, however, took the position that the flag of Japan
should be on the right side, because that was where Takeshita was
to sit as the two leaders signed the treaty. In any event, the two
flags and the two leaders ended up where they were scheduled to be
_ with Takeshita seated on the Stars and Stripes side and Reagan on
the Rising Sun side.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   As the seven summit leaders dined in the splendid dining room at
Hart Hall on the University of Toronto campus, the pool of
reporters, photographers and cameramen accompanying President
Reagan ate box lunches in a gymnasium.
   During their approximately three-hour wait for the trip back to
the president's hotel, they wrote, read, worked crossword puzzles,
pitched pennies and competed in making and flying paper airplanes.
   They didn't play cards. Nobody had brought a deck.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Study in contrasts: As the summit leaders' dinner broke up, a
lengthy motorcade formed in a circular drive, lights blazed at the
entrance of Hart Hall and, as the president stepped out, motorcyles
roared into action for the trip to his hotel a mile or so away.
   As the motorcade prepared to leave, two groups of people were
seen walking down a darkened sidewalk alongside the drive. At the
center of the first group was Helmut Kohl, the chancellor of West
Germany. At the center of the second was Francois Mitterrand, the
president of France.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Toronto summit, expected to be President Reagan's last trip
outside the United States as president, will be his 25th since he
took office in January 1981.
   His first trip abroad as president was to Ottawa on March 10 and
11, 1981, to meet with the then prime minister of Canada, Pierre
Elliott Trudeau. He has been to 28 countries in North and South
America, Central America, Europe and Asia.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
