<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-IRA     06-21 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-IRA,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Conclude Arrested Irishman Not IRA Member</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have concluded that an Irishman arrested
over the weekend before the start of the seven-nation economic
summit is not a member of the Irish Republican Army terror group.
   Michael Derek Collins was arrested Saturday for overstaying a
one-month visa issued to him last year. Police in Ireland said
Collins was a junior operative in the outlawed IRA during the 1970s.
   But police here said Collins is only being held pending an
immigration hearing and that no criminal charges are being brought
against him.
   Police Inspector Bob Guay said summit security forces are paying
strict attention to possible activities by the IRA because of the
presence here of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   But he denied the group is posing a specific threat to Mrs.
Thatcher during her stay. ``We have to be ever-mindful of all
terrorist groups in the world,'' he said.
</TEXT>
