<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Heat     06-21 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heat,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>How Hot Can It Get? How Does 134 Degrees Sound?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stifling temperatures are adding to the
drought-induced misery in parts of America, but even the 104-degree
record set in Lincoln, Neb., is 30 degrees short of the national
all-time high.
   Record highs recorded in the Midwest and Plains this week
include Sunday's 104 degrees at Lincoln, breaking a record of 103
for the date set in 1974; 95 degrees in Alpena, Mich., topping the
92-degree mark of 1964; and 103 in Sioux City, Iowa, beating the
99-degree record set in 1933 and 1953.
   The highest official reading in the United States was set July
10, 1913, in Death Valley, Calif., when the thermometer reached 134
degrees Fahrenheit.
   Death Valley has the perfect conditions for setting heat
records: low elevation in an already warm area, clear skies and
subsiding air on the lee side of mountains, geographer David H.
Hickcox says in ``Weatherwise'' magazine.
   Even so, it seldom reaches the sweltering heights of the 130s,
rarely exceeding 127 degrees, Hickcox reports. But it is steadily
hot, with the daily high falling below 105 only once during June of
1987, for example.
   While Death Valley gets the attention, however, high temperature
records of more than 100 degrees have been set in every state at
one time or another.
   Even seemingly frigid Alaska has managed the century mark,
recording 100 degrees at Fort Yukon on June 27, 1915.
   That ties Hawaii, where the 100-degree record was set at Pahala
on April 27, 1931.
   Alaska and Hawaii, with their records of 100 degrees, tie for
the lowest such record.
   Here is a rundown of the record high temperatures that have been
set in each state, as reported by the National Climatic Data Center:
   Alabama: 112, Sept. 5, 1925, Centerville.
   Alaska: 100, June 27, 1915, Fort Yukon.
   Arizona: 127: July 7, 1905, Parker.
   Arkansas: 120, Aug. 10, 1936, Ozark.
   California: 134, July 10, 1913, Greenland Ranch.
   Colorado: 118, July 11, 1888, Bennett.
   Connecticut: 105, July 22, 1926, Waterbury.
   Delaware: 110, July 21, 1930, Millsboro.
   Florida: 109, June 29, 1931, Monticello.
   Georgia: 113, May 27, 1978, Greenville.
   Hawaii: 100, April 27, 1931, Pahala.
   Idaho: 118, July 28, 1934, Orofino.
   Illinois: 117, July 14, 1954, E. St. Louis.
   Indiana: 116, July 14, 1936, Collegeville.
   Iowa: 118, July 20, 1934, Keokuk.
   Kansas: 121, July 24, 1936, Alton.
   Kentucky: 114, July 28, 1930, Greensburg.
   Louisiana: 114, Aug. 10, 1936, Plain Dealing.
   Maine: 105, July 10, 1911, North Bridgton.
   Maryland: 109, July 10, 1936, Cumberland and Frederick.
   Massachusetts: 107, Aug. 2, 1975, New Bedford and Chester.
   Michigan: 112, July 13, 1936, Mio.
   Minnesota: 114, July 6, 1936, Moorhead.
   Mississippi: 115, July 29, 1930, Holly Springs.
   Missouri: 118, July 14, 1954, Warsaw and Union.
   Montana: 117, July 5, 1937, Medicine Lake.
   Nebraska: 118, July 24, 1936, Minden.
   Nevada: 122, June 23, 1954, Overton.
   New Hampshire: 106, July 4, 1911, Nashua.
   New Jersey: 110, July 10, 1936, Runyon.
   New Mexico: 116, July 14, 1934, Orogrande.
   New York: 108, July 22, 1926, Troy.
   North Carolina: 119, Aug. 21, 1983, Fayetteville.
   North Dakota: 121, July 6, 1936, Steele.
   Ohio: 113: July 21, 1934, Gallipolis.
   Oklahoma: 120, July 26, 1943, Tishomingo.
   Oregon: 119, Aug. 10, 1898, Pendleton.
   Pennsylvania: 111, July 10, 1936, Phoenixville.
   Rhode Island: 104, Aug. 2, 1975, Providence.
