<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EquityLoans     06-21 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Equity Loans,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Bill To Impose Consumer Protections</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: St Germain, no period, is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial institutions offering home equity
loans would have to provide consumers with detailed descriptions of
the terms before requiring any non-refundable fees, under
House-approved legislation now headed for the Senate.
   House Banking Committee Chairman Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.,
said the bill, approved on a House voice vote Monday, would put
``an end to carnival-type advertising that lures homeowners into
deals they can't afford.''
   The legislation would prohibit misleading advertising and place
a series of new consumer protections on the loans, which have
increased in popularity because of tax advantages under the income
tax overhaul enacted in 1986.
   The legislation also includes requirements that lenders base
variable rates on publicly available indexes outside of their own
control, and it prohibits them from requiring speeded-up payments
unless the customer is at fault.
   The bill was sent to the Senate, which has already approved
similar legislation as part of broader banking legislation. The two
chambers must agree on identical bills before the legislation goes
to the president.
   An industry spokeswoman said bankers hoped to win changes in the
bill before final passage.
   ``We support the concept of the bill ... and we look forward to
working with Congress to pass a bill that fully balances the needs
of consumers and creditors,'' said Mary-Liz Meany of the American
Bankers Association, who said her group considered the legislation
too complex.
   Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the consumer
subcommittee of the House Banking Committee, said the measure is
needed because people are rushing to use home equity loans because
of their continued tax-deductibility.
   They might be ``the fastest growing craze since the Hula Hoop,''
he said.
   Surveys of banks and other lenders indicate home equity credit
lines have grown steadily over the past two years and are expected
to grow another 40 percent this year, Ms. Meany said.
   In 1985, the public owed $20 billion in home equity loans out of
$150 billion in all second mortgages. By the end of 1987, there
were $64 billion in equity loans out of about $200 billion in
second mortgages, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
