<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Finances     06-21 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Finances,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaign Remains Well Below Pre-Convention Spending Limit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' presidential campaign notched a
healthy fund-raising month in May, and more importantly, remained
far enough below the primary season spending cap to allow Dukakis
to campaign across the country before the Democratic convention
next month.
   Financial disclosure forms released by the Dukakis campaign
Monday indicated that the campaign raised $2,259,359 in
contributions in May and also received a $953,121 in federal
matching funds.
   The campaign ended the month with $2 million on hand, according
to forms filed with the Federal Election Commission.
   The strong May fund-raising effort brought to $8.57 million the
amount the campaign has raised through contributions this calendar
year, according to the FEC filing. It received an additional $7.75
million in matching funds during that period.
   The FEC forms indicated that as of May 31 Dukakis had spent
$19.4 million against the $27.6 million spending cap for the
primary season, leaving him with a comfortable cushion that allows
for the scheduling of several campaign trips before next month's
Democratic National Convention.
   He spent three days in the South last week and has trips to the
Midwest and West planned before the Atlanta convention.
   ``Careful budgeting has given us the finances so that right up
until the convention the governor can go to different regions of
the country and continue the campaign in an active and vibrant
way,'' said Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan. ``Careful budgeting has
paid off.''
   Dukakis' Republican counterpart, Vice President George Bush, has
had to dramatically cut campaign travel because he has spent nearly
to the limit.
   Robert A. Farmer, campaign treasurer for Dukakis, said total
fund-raising, including that of last year, had reached $19.2
million.
   In a statement, he said Dukakis has received contributions from
90,000 individuals from all 50 states, with an average donation of
$175. The maximum individual donation allowed by law is $1,000.
   Farmer, the man behind the Dukakis campaign's record-setting
fund-raising, is planning to help national and state Democratic
party organizations raise money for the general election, when the
burden of campaign financing shifts from individual candidates to
party groups.
   ``This year, the Democrats are going to create a financially
level playing field with the Republicans,'' Farmer said.
   At a fund-raiser earlier this month that netted $500,000, Farmer
said the Dukakis camaign had reached its limit for primary
fund-raising and was concentrating on raising $2.6 million for a
legal fund.
   The latest financial disclosure form, released by the Dukakis
campaign headquarters in Boston, indicated that the campaign had
$2,027,924 on hand as of May 31. It had $1.4 million on hand at the
beginning of the month.
   The campaign spent more than $2.8 million in May.
   The Dukakis campaign, which has not taken out any loans,
reported that it had outstanding bills totaling $669,100 and was
owed $224,474.
   A listing of state-by-state expenses related to primary
elections showed that the campaign spent $153,678 in California
last month, by far the largest single-state expenditure in May.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, clinched the delegate
majority needed for the nomination with a June 7 sweep of primaries
in California and three other states.
   During the first five months of this year, the campaign's
greatest allocation in a single state was the $1 million spent in
Texas. Dukakis won the March 8 primary there.
</TEXT>
