<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     06-21 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Urges Farm Foreclosure Moratorium</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Will stand for PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEBSTER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson visited a farm near here and criticized Reagan
administration farm policies that he said have left farmers more
vulnerable to the drought.
   Jackson examined the stunted corn crop at the farm of Dale and
Nancy Snesrud and called for a moratorium on farm foreclosures. He
said debt-ridden farmers hit hard by the drought could now fall
victim to land speculators.
   ``What we must do is declare a moratorium on foreclosures,''
Jackson said. ``There is nothing we can do about an act of God. But
we must stop an act of the devil.''
   Jackson blamed administration policies in part for driving
650,000 farmers out of business in the past eight years. He said
those farmers who have survived have no financial cushion to carry
them through the drought.
   ``If we can come up with creative ways to bail out Chrysler and
Continental Bank, we can bail out family farmers and ranchers,''
said Jackson. ``It's a matter of who our country comes to the aid
of.''
   To avoid drought-related livestock losses and curb the expected
increase in meat prices later this year, Jackson said the
government should free surplus grain for feed to make up for
expected low crop yields.
   Snesrud, who raises livestock, corn and soybeans on 230 acres,
said his crops will be severely damaged unless there's a good
rainfall in the next 10 to 14 days.
   Jackson said urban consumers will share the burden of the
drought when the grocery prices increase during the fall and
winter, with the brunt of the blow taken by people on fixed
incomes, he said.
   ``We have to take action before the impact takes place,'' said
Jackson, who led a brief prayer for rain. ``What is happening in
the field has an impact on the entire country.''
   The candidate also spoke Monday in Minneapolis to the 24th
annual convocation of the Opportunities Industrialization Centers
of America, a non-profit organization of vocational schools that
serves the needy.
   ``It's dark and we've got to hold on until morning comes,''
Jackson said. ``You never have a right to do less than your best.''
   He urged the crowd to ask presidential candidates, ``Where do I
fit in your budget?''
   Jackson touted his own budget plan, which would include more
spending on social programs and freezing the military budget.
   The Democratic presidential hopeful was spending today in
California, but had no campaign appearances planned. He scheduled a
meeting with rival Michael Dukakis, aides said.
</TEXT>
