<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Duarte     06-21 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Duarte,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duarte to Resume Presidency, Son Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
will return from next month from Washington, where he is being
treated for terminal liver cancer, and continue in office, his son
says.
   Alejandro Duarte told a news conference Monday that his
62-year-old father will return between July 5 and July 8 and
immediately resume his duties.
   ``His intellectual capacity is not affected by the treatment; in
fact it is admirable,'' said the younger Duarte.
   ``My father is a fighter,'' he said, emphasizing that doctors
say a cancer patient's will and morale are a big factor in the
prognosis.
   The younger Duarte said chemotherapy could extend his father's
life well into next year. He said that according to statistics, the
president could reasonably expect to live between six and 18 months.
   Duarte's five-year term ends June 1, 1989.
   He said his father ``will have to organize his work
differently'' but that chemotherapy would not prevent him from
carrying out his work.
   Duarte has spent the last three weeks in Walter Reed Army
Medical Center in Washington. He underwent surgery earlier this
month to remove most of his stomach, also affected by cancer.
   Duarte plans to return to Walter Reed in August, but his later
treatment would be in El Salvador, his son said.
   At home, the president faces a persistent 8-year-old leftist
guerrilla insurgency and divisions within his Christian Democratic
Party.
   The party is sharply split over who will be its presidential
candidate in March 1989 elections. The rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance handed the Christian Democrats a stunning
defeat in municipal and legislative elections held in March and is
considered likely to win the presidency.
   Vice President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount is the acting
president in Duarte's absence.
</TEXT>
