<DOCNO> AP880621-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0300EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Gainers     06-21 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Gainers,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Midwest Misery Could Benefit Northwest Farmers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Northwest farmers stand to benefit
from the drought that's laying waste to crops in the Midwest, but
they could easily become victims of the weather themselves,
agricultural experts say.
   Sparse rainfall and record heat have left the nation's heartland
parched, and some states anticipate losing 40 percent of this
year's farm revenue. But Oregon and Washington state farmers were
blessed with late spring rains and cooler temperatures that boosted
some crops but damaged others, such as cherries.
   Washington State Grange Master Ray Hill is one who stands to
both benefit and lose because of the drought.
   Hill, a wheat grower and cattle rancher, said he will make more
money this year on wheat, which is selling at nearly $1 a bushel
more than last year due to the anticipated shortfall from the
drought.
   But he probably will lose money on his cattle because Midwest
farmers are sending to market steers they are unable to feed from
parched fields. Beef prices, which were peaking, could become
depressed as the Midwest stock comes on the market, he said.
   As for wheat, ``the picture is brighter than it has been in a
long time,'' he said.
   ``It is definitely having a (beneficial) impact on our prices,''
said Thomas Mick, the Washington Wheat Commission's administrator.
``We hate to reap benefit off somebody else's misfortune, but the
futures prices of wheat are rising dramatically (because of the
drought), and our wheat prices are based on those.''
   Last year farmers received about $2.60 per bushel. They are now
looking at $3.35 to $3.50 a bushel, Mick said. It is possible price
rises will continue through the August harvest of Washington's and
Oregon's predominantly soft white variety of wheat, used for
noodles and pasta.
   Midwest farmers grow a hard red variety that's used primarily in
bread.
   Mick and Hill said Washington state growers still face potential
crop losses because of weather. If recent hot, dry weather
continues it could stress the crop, but nothing like the Midwest
drought.
   ``We've been lucky for the last three harvests,'' said Mick.
``We barely made a crop, then received extremely timely rains.
Going into April, we were in a drought situation ourselves. The
rains in April, May and June saved the crops.''
   Because of various government land set-aside programs, the total
Washington state wheat acreage is at its lowest in two decades, but
the total yield for the state is expected to be average or just
below average, Mick said.
   Barley and corn growers also should benefit, Mick said, because
barley prices are closely related to corn prices and the Midwest
corn crop has been severely hurt by the drought.
   Although the prices paid for wheat are expected to rise,
consumers should barely feel the increase, Mick said.
   Mick said a $1 hike in the price of a bushel of wheat represents
an increase of about 1{ cents in the price of a loaf of bread, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
