<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out In Vacant Building Near Reagan's Hotel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with fire being brought under control,
security official saying it was not connected to the summit meeting</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An eight-story building only 150 yards from the
hotel where President Reagan is staying for the economic summit
caught fire early Tuesday, but the blaze was brought under control
within an hour of the initial alarm, officials said.
   The fire, which broke out in vacant building, sent burning
cinders showering hundreds of yards down Bay Street, in the heart
of Toronto's financial district.
   The building was located only 1{ blocks from the Royal York,
where Reagan is staying. The fire was four blocks from the
Metropolitan Toronto Convention Center, the site of the
seven-nation economic summit. Dozens of TV crews, both local and
foreign, ran the four blocks to film the blaze.
   Officials at the site said the fire was under control within an
hour of the initial alarm.
   Sgt. Rick Morris of the summit security force said there was no
connection between the fire and the summit meeting.
   Fire officials said they had asked for the arson squad to
investigate whether the fire had been deliberately set.
