<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Scotus-AlaDeseg     06-21 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Ala Deseg,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court's Ruling Unravels Years of Litigation in Desgregation
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After more than seven years of dispute,
a lawsuit seeking to desegregate Alabama's universities is back
where it began and is headed for a new trial as a result of a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling.
   The court, without comment, refused on Monday to alter a ruling
that a federal judge who found ``vestiges of segregation'' in the
state's schools should not have presided over the case.
   Officials from both sides of the lawsuit are working toward
reaching a settlement, said Gov. Guy Hunt's legal adviser, Mark
Montiel.
   Montiel declined to discuss specifics that might help or impede
a settlement.
   ``It's going to take a cooperative effort to resolve it,'' he
said. ``It's just a matter of sitting down and working toward that
goal.''
   Auburn University officials would not comment on pending
litigation.
   In 1983, the Reagan administration sued the state's higher
education system, alleging racial discrimination. The lawsuit was
filed after two years of efforts to settle the case among the
college presidents and state school officials failed.
   U.S. District Judge U.W. Clemon, the first black federal trial
judge in Alabama, ruled after a 22-day trial in 1985 that
authorities would have to take steps to racially integrate such
state-run schools as Auburn, the University of Alabama and Troy
State. Clemon described Auburn as the state's most segregated
university, an opinion now void.
   But the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last Oct. 6
that Clemon should have disqualified himself because as a former
state legislator, he ``actively participated in the very events and
shaped the very facts that are at issue in this suit.''
   Clemon once served as chairman of the state Senate Rules
Committee. In that role, the appeals court said, he ``played a
critical role in the confirmation of those individuals nominated
for positions on the board of trustees of the defendant
institutions.''
   The appeals court, however, rejected arguments that Clemon
should have disqualified himself because of his past civil rights
activity and because his children may some day attend some of the
schools involved.
   ``To disqualify minority judges from major civil rights
litigation solely because of their minority status is
intolerable,'' the appellate court said.
   The appellate ruling sent the case back for a new trial before
U.S. District Judge Sam Pointer Jr. of Birmingham.
   The appeal acted on Monday was filed by Alabama State University
and Alabama A&M University, two predominantly black schools.
Officials at both schools say their integration attempts have been
thwarted by official state policies, and individuals.
   The 11th Circuit ruled that the two schools could not bring suit
against the state that created the institutions.
</TEXT>
