<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RobertsCrew     06-21 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Roberts Crew,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crew Of Ship That Hit Iranian Mine Returns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crew members of the USS Samuel B. Roberts
hit the shore for a monthlong vacation after arriving home to
balloons and flowers for the first time since the Navy frigate hit
a mine in the Persian Gulf in April.
   The 140 sailors were greeted Monday night by more than 350
whooping wives, girlfriends and other relatives as they arrived
here at T.F. Green State Airport after the long flight from Dubai
in the gulf.
   ``It's great to be back! I'm going to a Cubs game,'' one sailor
shouted.
   On April 14, while on escort duty in the gulf, the
guided-missile vessel hit a mine that tore a 22- to 25-foot hole in
its bottom, flooded its engine room and set a fire that took five
hours to control.
   The blast injured 10 crew members, two critically. All have
since recovered, Navy officials said.
   In retaliation for the mine, which Navy officials said was laid
by Iran, the United States destroyed two Iranian offshore platforms
and sank or crippled six Iranian ships.
   Vice Admiral Joseph S. Donnell III, commander of the Atlantic
fleet's surface forces, praised the crew Monday, calling them
``clearly national heroes.''
   ``The ship would have sunk had it not been for the crew, there's
no question about that,'' Donnell said.
   The crew had to deploy small propellers driven by electric
motors to get out of the mine field, control a fire that was
feeding on engine fuel, shore up buckling bulkheads next to the
flooded engine room, and weld new plates and heavy wire to cracks
to hold the ship together.
   ``We did a job that we're supposed to do,'' said Richard
Raymond, 26, an operations specialist from Spotswood, N.J.
   But some said the ordeal was as harrowing as their family and
friends had imagined.
   ``The fires were really getting out of control, and the
flooding,'' said Scot Joseph, 20, a ship's cook from New Bedford,
Mass. ``We weren't sure if we were going to stay afloat.''
   ``We felt right until they pumped the water out in the drydock
(two days after hitting the mine) that we were at risk,'' said Lt.
Cmdr. John Eckelberry, the ship's executive officer.
   About 30 crew members were chosen to stay with the frigate when
it returns Sunday to the United States.
   The ship is expected to arrive at its home port of Newport about
40 days later, Navy officials said. In October, it will be sent to
the Bath Iron Works in Portland, Maine, for repairs that could take
a year, Donnell said.
   The crew will be on leave until the Roberts arrives in Newport,
and then will be assigned to stay with the ship while it is being
repaired, said Donnell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
