<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Korea-Divorce,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Divorce Rate Soars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divorces in South Korea soared by 33
percent last year, with infidelity being cited as the most common
reason for dissolved marriages, court figures show.
   The Supreme Court reported that 54,762 couples divorced in 1987
compared to 41,240 divorces the year before.
   South Korea's rising divorce rate appears to reflect the decline
of traditional values and the impact of Western lifestyles as well
as growing prosperity and the pressures of modern, urban life.
   Court officials said infidelity was cited in 47.3 percent of the
divorces, followed by desertion in 22.4 cases, mistreatment in 12.2
percent.
   Mistreatment of a spouse's parents was cited as the reason in
5.5 percent of divorce cases. Some elderly people live with their
married children, causing domestic tension.
</TEXT>
