<HEAD>Malpractice Insurance Cost Cutting Maternal Care, HHS Chief Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's health chief says the
availability of maternal care in rural and inner-city areas is
being especially hurt by the soaring cost of medical malpractice
insurance.
   ``With family physicians often the only ones to serve an area,
numerous counties or entire regions of some states report that they
have just one or two physicians to deliver babies,'' Health and
Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen said on Monday.
   Bowen's remarks to an Institute of Medicine symposium were based
largely on an HHS task force report on medical malpractice
insurance issued last August.
   Bowen told the opening session of the symposium the American
Academy of Family Physicians reported last year that 18.6 percent
of its members have dropped their obstetrical practice due to the
cost of liability insurance or an inability to get malpractice
insurance.
   The independent Institute of Medicine is studying the effect of
malpractice insurance issues on the delivery of maternal and child
health care.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Recall Ordered for Scuba Dry Suits Using Single Air Control Valve</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has ordered the recall of scuba
diving dry suits using air control valves made by Diving Unlimited
International because malfunctioning valves may cause serious
injury or death.
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission said Monday that owners
of dry suits with AC (air control) valves made by the San
Diego-based Diving Unlimited International Inc. ``should
immediately stop using the dry suits.''
   The commission said there have been 16 incidents associated with
malfunctioning of the valve, which deflates or inflates the dry
suits to equalize air pressure while divers ascend or descend in
water.
   The commission said that unlike air control systems which use
two separate valves, DUI's one-valve system may cause ``air to fill
the dry suit, resulting in the diver rising rapidly to the surface
or failing to provide sufficient air to maintain buoyancy.''
   DUI says owners of suits with the company's valve should return
their suits to the company and the valve will be replaced at no
charge.
   DUI can be contacted at 800-327-8439, the commission at
800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
