<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     06-21 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Post Poll Puts Dukakis Well Ahead Of Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush has slightly improved
his standing but still trails Democratic presidential contender
Michael Dukakis by double digits, a new poll published today by The
Washington Post indicates.
   The latest poll suggests Dukakis leads Bush 51 percent to 39
percent. In a similar survey on May 25, the Massachusetts governor
was ahead of the vice president by just a bit more _ 53 to 40
percent.
   The Post poll suggests that Bush is significantly better known
than Dukakis. Ten percent of the voters said they know a great deal
about Dukakis, compared to 29 percent for Bush.
   The survey suggested that only half the supporters of both
candidates described themselves as ``strong'' supporters of the
candidate of their choice, with the remainder saying their
preference is ``not strong.''
   The telephone survey of 1,012 adults was conducted from
Wednesday to Sunday. Of those, 782 were registered voters.
   For results based on the entire sample, the margin of error was
plus or minus 3 percentage points. It was 4 percentage points for
registered voters.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Drought Hurting Bush's Chances?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican congressman says drought
conditions in the Midwest could cripple Vice President George
Bush's chances of winning election as president.
   ``There's no question that a drought fairly early on hurts the
party in power,'' Rep. Steve Gunderson, R-Wis., said Monday.
   ``Fairly or unfairly, we (Republicans) have been accused over
the last eight to 10 years of moving out the bad farm managers,''
he said.
   Gunderson said the Reagan administration must help farmers
withstand the drought because ``I don't think you can justify
putting farmers out of business because of circumstances beyond
their control, such as the weather.''
   He said the drought could make Bush choose former rival Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole as his running mate because of Dole's support in the
farm community.
