<HEAD>Democrats Ponder Rules Violation By Maine Delegation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic officials are being asked to decide
whether members of Maine's delegation should be seated at the
national party convention even though the state party ignored a key
rule in selecting delegates.
   ``They may not meet the letter of the ... rule, but they meet
the spirit of the rule,'' said Estelle A. Lavoie, a Portland,
Maine, attorney told a national party hearing officer on Monday.
   Hearing officer John Nolan said he would make a report to the
convention's rules committee before its meeting here on Thursday.
If Maine is judged in violation of the rules, it could lose its
four seats for Democratic National Committee members at the
convention.
   The state convention in May selected 23 delegates, giving 11 to
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, nine to Jesse Jackson and 3 to
an uncommitted group.
   Under national rules, the uncommitted group would not have won
any delegates, since they had only 13 percent of the state
convention delegates _ below the 15 percent national minimum. But
the Maine rules specifically rejected any minimum threshold for
winning national delegates.
