<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Poll     06-21 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Poll,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Majority of Mexicans Support Governing Party Candidate, Polls Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-six percent of Mexican voters favor
governing party candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari in the July 6
presidential election, according to a Gallup poll touted as the
most ambitious ever in Mexico.
   Leftist coalition candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas trailed at 23
percent, and conservative National Action Party candidate Manuel
Clouthier was preferred by 19 percent of voters, according to
survey, which was published Monday night by the government news
agency Notimex.
   Two other presidential hopefuls, Rosario Ibarra de Piedra of the
radical Revolutionary Workers' Party and Gumersindo Magana of the
conservative Mexican Democratic Party, each received 1 percent of
voter support in the poll.
   As the candidate of the Institutional Revolutionary Party,
Salinas de Gortari is virtually certain of victory over four
opposition candidates. The party, known by its Spanish initials
PRI, has not lost a presidential, gubernatorial or senate election
since it was founded in 1929.
   Another poll published by the Mexico City newspaper El Universal
found near-identical vote totals for the leading candidates. That
survey, conducted in 44 of Mexico's most important cities, gave
Salinas de Gortari the support of 56.2 percent of voters. Cardenas
placed second at 21.6 percent.
   The nationwide Gallup survey was billed as the ``most ambitious
ever realized'' in Mexico. It was conducted between May 12 and June
1 for ECO, Inc., a Los Angeles-based affiliate of the private
Televisa television network, which is closely aligned with the
government.
   A total of 2,960 registered voters were asked to answer 70
questions indicating their voting preferences, opinions on the
leadership and personal qualities of the candidates, and background
information on their incomes and professions.
   The news agency did not provide a margin of error.
   Salinas de Gortari also polled first in personal and leadership
characteristics, such as familiarity with Mexico's problems,
leadership, honesty, and ``love for Mexico.''
   Among those who voted in 1982 for then-candidate Miguel de La
Madrid, the current president, 77 percent said they plan to vote
for Salinas de Gortari.
   Jorge de la Vega, president of the party's national executive
committee, predicted Monday that the party would obtain the votes
of 20 million of Mexico's 38 million registered voters in July.
</TEXT>
