<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MetMove     06-21 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Met Move,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Metropolitan Opera Plans Part-Time Move to Brooklyn's Majestic
Theater</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Metropolitan Opera is planning a part-time
move to the Brooklyn Academy of Music's Majestic Theater as part of
an experiment scheduled to start with the 1991 season.
   The newly restored Majestic will provide the backdrop for new
and small-scale works and for innovative productions that may not
be suitable for performances at the Metropolitan Opera House in
Lincoln Center, said Bruce Crawford, the Met's general manager.
   The arrangement is based on an agreement in principle, and no
contracts have been signed, The New York Times reported today. The
productions are to be jointly presented by the Met and BAM.
   The Majestic has presented vaudeville, movies and plays, and was
restored last year in a post-modernistic style for Peter Brook's
production of ``The Mahabharata.''
   The theater seats 900, compared with 4,000 at the Met in Lincoln
Center. Some of the Brooklyn productions may be staged in the
academy's 2,000-seat Opera House, rather than in the Majestic.
   Harvey Lichtenstein, president of the academy, said more than $2
million has been budgeted for the 1991 season.
   The move would mark a return of sorts for the Met. Even before
the current BAM building opened in 1907, the Met offered Tuesday
night performances in Brooklyn during its regular season. The
visits stopped during the Depression, after the 1936-37 season.
</TEXT>
