<DOCNO> AP880621-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0446EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland     06-21 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Bishops Urges Political, Economic Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's influential Roman Catholic
bishops say Communist authorities will plunge Poland deeper into
poverty unless they allow the political freedoms necessary to make
promised economic reforms work.
   In their first statement since last month's labor unrest, the
bishops called for greater freedom of association and reinstatement
of the free trade unions the government denied citizens 6{ years
ago.
   The statement Monday came as the banned Solidarity independent
labor federation accused the government of dramatically inflating
the reported 56 percent turnout in nationwide regional and local
elections held Sunday.
   Since a nearly three-week strike wave that ended May 10, the
government has said it wants to accelerate its economic reform
program and may legalize certain independent associations.
   The bishops' communique, issued after a weekend conference in
the northeastern city of Bialystok, criticized the pace of the
government's program of political and economic reforms.
   ``Numerous announcements are not accompanied by equally
energetic actions,'' it says.
   The recent strikes stemmed mainly from economic causes: the
``impoverishing of society'' and the ``remarkable increase'' in the
cost of living for families, the communique says.
   Prices have risen by at least 40 percent so far this year.
   Opposition spokesmen say the government should recognize
Solidarity and begin negotiations with the opposition on solving
Poland's economic problems.
   ``The bishops share basic concern over the state of the country
and society's basic rights,'' they said in their statement.
   The church says more than 90 percent of Poland's 37 million
people are Roman Catholics.
   ``Critical judgment of the situation ... should lead to
courageous and far-sighted changes which are commonly believed
necessary in the economic, social and political spheres,'' the
bishops said.
   Referring to the authorities' announced plans to make it easier
to form private associations, the bishops said, ``This may
contribute to the rise of creative activity in the society.''
   But they said the changes must ``create freedom of associating
accessible for all,'' regardless of political viewpoint, and
eliminate administrative and political interference in associations.
   ``Even far-reaching changes in this field will not replace the
need of trade union pluralism, which, according to the social
teaching of the church, belongs to the basic rights of working
people,'' the statement adds.
   Trade union pluralism is one of the basic demands of Solidarity,
which has remained active though it was banned after a December
1981 military crackdown.
   About 50 Solidarity local organizations have sought registration
in the courts over the past year, but all have been denied it on
the grounds officially recognized unions already exist at the
plants.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said poor economic conditions
discouraged some people from attending Sunday's voting but argued
that the elections were a breakthrough because some candidates
actively campaigned for the first time and some races were
contested between people of different parties.
</TEXT>
