<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-21 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen today, and
share prices declined on the Tokyo Stock Exchange following an
overnight drop in New York.
   After opening at 126.39 yen, up 0.30 yen from Monday's close,
the dollar hit a high of 126.43 yen before closing at 126.33 yen.
It closed Monday at 126.09 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues slid 213.46 points, or 0.75 percent, to finish the
day at 27,925.57 points.
   ``The market is a bit mixed following the summit, trying to find
a trend,'' said King Ogino, a foreign exchange dealer with Goldman
Sachs. He was referring to a Toronto summit of seven leading
industrial nations, including the United States.
   ``Fear of U.S. inflation could depress the dollar and stock
markets,'' he said. ``The yen is still a safety currency, and
that's why people are hedging.''
   On the stock exchange, investors ``generally stayed on the
sidelines, although steel issues gained across the board,'' said
Hitomi Sakano of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
``Electronics, precision instruments, finances and real estates
fell back.''
   Dealers attributed the Nikkei's loss to a 20-point overnight
drop on Wall Street.
   The stock exchange suffered its first decline in six days on
Monday when the Nikkei average plummeted 203.43 points.
   ``Investors are not active so far this week following heated
trading last week,'' said a broker at a major securities firm,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said investors had found few new incentives and had engaged
in occasional profit-taking. ``That's pushing share prices down,''
he said.
   The index closed at a record high 28,342.46 points on Friday.
</TEXT>
