<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Explosion     06-21 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Explosion,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Soldiers Killed Training With Plastic Explosives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHILLIWACK, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six soldiers learning
explosives handling were killed and three injured at a Canadian
Forces base when enough plastic explosives to level a small house
detonated prematurely.
   The five men and a woman, all military engineering students,
were preparing to blast a five-yard-deep crater on Monday when the
more than 60 pounds of plastic explosives detonated, military
authorities said.
   Three other second-year officer training cadets were injured in
the blast, which occured on the third day of a four-day training
session.
   ``We do not know at this time what was the cause of the
explosion and that will be a matter for summary and formal
investigations over the next long period,'' said Lt. Col. Graham
Meharg, administrator of Canadian Forces Base Chilliwack.
   Further explosives training was suspended pending a military
investigation.
   The tragedy cast a pall over the 2,000-soldier base near this
city of 40,000 in a quiet farming valley about 60 miles east of
Vancouver.
   Some survivors were in shock and Meharg would not allow those
who were not to speak to reporters.
   The training unit, which was also learning to blow up concrete
and trees, consisted of 29 students, seven instructors and five
support staff.
   ``They were on their third day . . . (and) did know what they
were doing with explosives,'' said Meharg.
</TEXT>
