<DOCNO> AP880621-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0615EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Japan-Beef-Reax     06-21 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Beef-Reax,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Cattlemen, Citrus Producers Welcome Lift on Import
Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By READ MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas cattlemen and Florida citrus growers were
enthusiastic about Japan's decision to liberalize import
restrictions and double the amount of beef and oranges it buys from
the United States.
   ``It's going to be a morale booster for us and it's going to
help our markets some,'' Charles E. Ball, executive vice president
of the Texas Cattle Feeders Association in Amarillo, said Monday.
   ``This has been a psychological thing for our people: the fact
that we import so much from Japan while they've had barriers on our
beef and citrus over there,'' Ball said.
   The agreement, announced Monday in Tokyo by U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter, calls on Japan to nearly double its
beef imports by 1991. It also provides for doubling of Japan's
imports of oranges from the United States.
   ``It's clearly beneficial ... a positive step forward for the
Florida industry,'' said Robert Behr, director of economic research
for the Florida Department of Citrus in Orlando, Fla.
   Japan is Florida's largest export market for fresh grapefruit,
and Florida growers hope the agreement will boost sales of other
citrus products.
   ``We have the potential for similar growth in orange and orange
juice that we have had with grapefruit,'' said Lee Bouldin,
international marketing director for the citrus department.
   The U.S. Agriculture Department said total American citrus sales
to Japan could increase from $50 million to $150 a million a year
when the quotas are lifted. The agreement could double U.S. exports
of beef and oranges to more than $1 billion annually, Yeutter said.
   Under the agreement, Japan will be allowed to set beef tariffs
of 70 percent in 1991, 60 percent in 1992 and 50 percent in 1993 to
allow Japanese farmers time to adjust.
   Japan agreed to expand market access for fresh oranges by 22,000
tons annually, to 192,000 tons in 1990.
   Some Texas cattlemen said they doubt that they'll see an
immediate financial gain as a result of the agreement.
   ``The import quota as I understand it was very small anyway, and
doubling something that was small to begin with is going to have a
pretty minor impact, but it's a step in the right direction,'' said
San Angelo rancher Skipper Duncan, who raises feeder cattle.
   In Japan, some farmers have reacted angrily to the agreement,
and one cattle farmer committed suicide to protest the
liberalization of the country's agricultural markets.
   Ikko Abe, 57, a farmer in Iwate prefecture of northern Japan,
died after hanging himself on Saturday, but details of his death
were not released until today, said a police official who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   He said Abe left a note saying, ``I oppose the liberalization of
beef imports. I will protest it with my death.''
   Abe owned 50 head of cattle and 2.47 acres of rice paddies, the
official said. Iwate prefecture is the fourth largest producer of
beef in Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
