<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-21 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summer Comes On Hot Over Much of The Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Summer got off to a scorching start today as a heat wave
blistered dozens of cities in the central and eastern United States.
   Summer officially began just before midnight Monday, following a
sweltering day of record-setting temperatures in nearly 40 cities.
   The mercury hit 110 degrees at Bullhead City and Phoenix, Ariz.,
Hill City, Kan., and Laughlin, Nev., setting a record high for the
date.
   A cold front brought some relief to parts of the north-central
United States with readings in the 50s and 60s over much of the
Great Lakes region and the upper Mississippi Valley.
   A few showers and thunderstorms lingered along the cold front,
while other storms were widely scattered through western portions
of the nation and east of the Mississippi River. The sky was clear
across the southern and central Plains and the lower and
mid-Mississippi Valley.
   A thunderstorm in Fernley, Nev., spawned a tornado that damaged
several roofs, ripped down power lines and uprooted several trees
Monday night.
   Today's forecast was for mostly sunny skies and hot temperatures
for much of the nation; showers and thunderstorms scattered from
the Gulf Coast region across the southern Atlantic coast states and
over the Rockies and the Great Basin; and a few severe
thunderstorms possible from eastern North Dakota through Minnesota
into Wisconsin.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 90s across much of the
nation; in the 60s and 70s along the Pacific coast; in the 80s over
the Rockies, the Appalachians, the Great Lakes, the central Gulf
Coast and the south Atlantic coast states; reaching 100 to 110
degrees in the deserts Southwest; readings over 100 degrees from
the central Plains into northern Illinois.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 50
degrees at Quillayute, Wash., to 93 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 73 fair; Boston 75 hazy; Buffalo 67 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 70 fair; Cincinnati 73 cloudy; Cleveland 75 fair;
Detroit 72 fair; Miami 81 cloudy; New York 73 hazy; Philadelphia 76
hazy; Pittsburgh 74 hazy; Portland, Maine 74 hazy; Washington 74
hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 90 cloudy; Chicago 77 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
78 fair; Denver 71 fair; Des Moines 82 fair; Indianapolis 77 fair;
Kansas City 80 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 73 fair; Nashville 73
hazy; New Orleans 72 fair; St. Louis 81 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 74 fair; Anchorage 51 fair; Las Vegas 86
fair; Los Angeles 60 fair; Phoenix 93 fair; Salt Lake City 79 fair;
San Diego 63 fair; San Francisco NOT lable; Seattle 58 cloudy.
   _Canada: Toronto 61 fair.
</TEXT>
