<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-NuclearTest     06-21 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Nuclear Test,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Said To Detonate Nuclear Bomb in South Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France has detonated another
nuclear weapon in the South Pacific as part of its series of
underground tests in the region, the foreign minister said today.
   The minister, Russell Marshall, condemned France's continued
testing of nuclear weapons in the region.
   Marshall, also minister for disarmament and arms control, was
responding to a report from New Zealand government scientists that
France had conducted a small underground nuclear test at Mururoa
Atoll on Friday.
   They said it was the third blast there this year and the 98th in
the series started in 1976, when France abandoned atmospheric
testing.
   New Zealand monitored the blast at Raratonga, in the Cook
Islands, about 1,800 miles northeast of its coast.
   The weapon carried an explosive yield of five kilotons, the
equivalent of 5,000 tons of dynamite, said government seismologist
Murray Lowry.
   ``This explosion is smaller than most, but even so weapons of
this size would cause enormous destruction. It is totally
reprehensible,'' Marshall said.
   He added, ``The fact that we detected this explosion is further
evidence that the means of verifying a ban on testing are at hand.''
   New Zealand has called for a comprehensive ban on such nuclear
tests.
   The nation joins its South Pacific neighbor, Australia, in
vigorously opposing French nuclear testing in the region.
   France refuses to comment on reports of its testing.
</TEXT>
