<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0619EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HomelessRestaurant     06-21 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless Restaurant,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Full-Service Restaurant For The Homeless Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 25 homeless people gathered for a hot meal
at the opening of 458 Cafe, where patrons are asked for their order
instead of told to wait in a soup line.
   The cafe, housed in an art deco-style building, serves as a
full-service restaurant for the homeless. Volunteer waiters take
orders from seated patrons who are offered a choice of meals.
   The clientele Monday was not demanding _ many simply shrugged
when asked to choose from the menu of beef burgundy or
chicken-and-rice casserole, salad, green beans or corn, and
chocolate cheesecake or peaches.
   Oscar Shears can't remember the last time he sat down at a table
and heard someone ask, ``May I take your order, please?'' He said
lingering over hot food and fresh coffee is an unaccustomed
pleasure.
   ``It's been awhile _ I ain't had no money,'' Shears said. He
still doesn't have any money, but he enjoyed a meal of beef
burgundy, corn and green beans with ham hocks.
   ``The atmosphere here is a whole lot different (from a soup
kitchen),'' said Shears, who lives in a shelter. ``It kind of makes
you feel like a person again.''
   Jim Zerdecki, who usually stays in shelters, agreed.
   ``When a lot of people go through a soup line they feel more
like animals being fed out of a trough,'' he said. ``This makes
people feel more like they're somebody, maybe somebody special.''
   The Rev. A.B. Short, who helped launch the 28-seat diner, said
he wants more from his concept than a few dozen filled stomachs.
   ``Food is not really what we're serving here,'' Short said.
``What we're serving is friendship, hospitality, brotherhood and
sisterhood.
   ``Something almost mystical happens when people sit down
together and share a meal,'' Short said. ``Walls break down.''
   Short conceived the idea for the restaurant two years ago after
a passing comment from Bobby Freeman, who chairs the Atlanta
Community Food Bank's board of directors.
   Short envisions a multipurpose stop for the homeless, including
legal services, weekly visits by a mobile medical clinic, and
alcohol and narcotics support groups.
   The building, a former drive-in liquor store, was purchased for
$60,000 with federal grants.
   The restaurant is operated by the Community of Hospitality, a
non-profit religious group that grew out of Short's activities. The
food is provided by the food bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
