<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0701EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-21 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Holds Steady In Calm Trading; Gold Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was holding steady in calm European
trading late this morning despite a small increase in short-term
West German interest rates earlier in the session.
   Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said the Deutsche Bundesbank's decision to raise the
rate on securities repurchase agreements to 3.5 percent from 3.25
percent had been expected and didn't have any immediate impact on
the currency market.
   Higher West German interest rates make West German investments
more attractive, which could depress demand for the dollar.
   ``The market is relatively tranquil,'' said one senior trader
with a foreign bank in Milan. ``Activity has essentially halted to
see whether there's going to be any reaction to the movements in
interest rates.''
   He added that the rate hike already had been discounted by the
market.
   The market also was in a ``wait-and-see mood'' over the Toronto
economic summit of the seven major industrialized countries.
   Although the summit, which ends today, wasn't expected to
produce any major developments for the currency markets, traders
were on their guard for any statements that could affect the dollar.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.24 yen to a closing 126.33. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 126.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday:
   _ 1.7569 West German marks, up from 1.7543
   _ 1.4605 Swiss francs, up from 1.4580
   _ 5.9280 French francs, up from 5.9173
   _ 1.9767 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9730
   _ 1,304.50 Italian lire, up from 1,302.00
   _ 1.2065 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2094
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7867 to buy one pound, fractionally more expensive than $1.7865
on Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $451.40 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $453.90. At mid-morning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $451.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $451.80, down from $452.50 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.55 to close at a bid of
$452.75.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $7.19 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $7.26.
</TEXT>
