<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JailbreakKilling     06-21 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jailbreak Killing,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspects In Slaying Of Deputy Surrender</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK GROVE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men accused of killing a sheriff's
deputy during a jailbreak surrendered because they knew their
chances of survival were slim, said a sheriff who participated in
the three-state manhunt for them.
   Frank Bancroft, suspected of being the triggerman during a
weekend jailbreak that freed brothers Sonny and Frank Caston, gave
up without a fight after he was spotted Monday in a stolen boat,
said Dale Rinicker, sheriff of East Carroll Parish.
   Shortly after Bancroft surrendered, the Castons also gave up at
the East Carroll Parish sheriff's office, Rinicker said.
   ``They just didn't want to get shot or killed,'' he said. ``And
they knew that's what it was coming to.''
   Bancroft, 19, of West Carroll was booked on charges of
first-degree murder in the death of radio operator Jeff Gathings,
23. Gathings was on duty alone at the West Carroll sheriff's office
in Oak Grove when an intruder shot him with a 12-gauge shotgun
early Sunday.
   Sonny Caston, 20, and Frank Caston, 21, both from Lake
Providence, were freed by the killer. They also face first-degree
murder charges, Rinicker said.
   All three were being held without bond at Oak Grove, a northeast
Louisiana town.
   Bancroft had served time in the West Carroll jail on a theft
conviction and was released five days before the killing, said West
Carroll Sheriff Gary Bennett. The Castons were jailed on burglary
and arson charges and are suspected of planning the escape with
Bancroft before his release, Bennett said.
   Bancroft was captured after the owner of a boat stolen Sunday
night from its Lake Providence dock spotted the boat Monday and
approached it in another vessel, Rinicker said.
   Bancroft identified himself to the boat owner, said he was
wanted and that he was ready to give up, the sheriff said. When
Rinicker and other law enforcement officials arrived, Bancroft was
waiting, his hands in the air.
</TEXT>
