<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Singleton     06-21 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Singleton,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighbors Wants To Know Where Rapist Is</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted rapist Lawrence Singleton hasn't
been seen at the Florida address he listed with state officials,
but neighbors say they will live in fear until he is found and sent
packing.
   ``I find it hard to believe that none of the police departments
can tell where he is. This is totally incredible,'' said Lester
Heitlinger, among 50 residents of the neighborhood who met at a
recreation center Monday night.
   Two weeks ago, Singleton listed his brother's home in the
residential Forest Hills neighborhood as his address to comply with
a state law on incoming felons, but he hasn't shown up there and
his brother refuses to say where he really lives.
   Singleton was convicted of raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker,
chopping her arms off with an ax and leaving her for dead in a
ditch southeast of San Francisco in 1978.
   Singleton, a 60-year-old former merchant seaman who grew up in
Tampa, spent eight years of a 14-year sentence in a California
prison. After his release on probation, Singleton was chased from
town to town by Californians unwilling to allow him to live among
them. He finally completed a yearlong probation on the grounds of
San Quentin prison and is now a free man.
   Hillsborough County sheriff's Col. Cal Henderson told residents
that Singleton registered with authorities upon his arrival in
Florida. He is not, however, required to notify officials every
time he moves within the state.
   ``We get 30 ex-convicts coming into the county every month, and
we can't keep up with all of them,'' Henderson said. ``We have too
many current violators to try and keep up with past offenders.''
   That didn't calm frustrated residents, many of whom suggested
violence as a means of forcing Singleton out of their neighborhood.
   One woman, who refused to give her name, proposed throwing rocks
at the address of his brother, Walter Singleton.
   ``Walter Singleton has not been convicted of anything,''
Henderson warned. ``He's locked in his house, and he's afraid to
leave.''
</TEXT>
