<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0754EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     06-21 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Demonstrate For Unification, Poll Shows Rising Anti-US
Sentiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IMJINGAK, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students
marched at the border today to demand reunification of North and
South Korea and the withdrawal of American troops.
   About 350 students from Seoul's Konkuk University held their
peaceful protest in front of steel barriers and barbed wire that
block a bridge leading to the border with communist North Korea.
   ``Drive out Yankees who hinder unification!'' students shouted
as they marched near the bridge after a ceremony at which they
prayed for reunification of the peninsula.
   In Seoul, a survey indicated that anti-U.S. sentiment was
growing among South Koreans and went beyond radical student
protesters.
   According to the survey, 16 percent of 2,000 eligible voters
questioned said they dislike the United States, compared to 3
percent in 1984.
   As the students protested today, an American soldier guarded the
bridge, and about 20 South Korean policemen and soldiers in
plainclothes patrolled nearby.
   The bridge is the only civilian access linking the Koreas. U.S.
forces help control the southern side of the Demilitarized Zone
across from Imjingak and roads to the truce site of Panmunjom,
which straddles the border.
   The students demanded withdrawal of about 42,000 U.S. troops
stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact to help deter
North Korean attacks. The protesters contend the United States
enforces partition of the peninsula.
   They also denounced the blocking June 10 of a planned march to
the North Korean border. Fierce street clashes broke out that day
when riot police fired tear gas to block thousands of students
trying to march to Panmunjom for talks with North Korean students.
   During today's border rally, student leaders called for dialogue
with North Korean students to help form a unified Korean team for
the Summer Olympics, opening Sept. 17 in Seoul.
   In the poll, at least 37 percent of those surveyed said they
like the United States, down from 70 percent four years ago.
   To Heung-yul, a researcher at Hyundai Research Institute in
Seoul, released the survey in a seminar.
   The survey said anti-U.S. feelings were rapidly spreading,
partly in response to a steady anti-U.S. campaign by radical
students.
   He also attributed the growing anti-U.S. trend to Washington's
policies, including pressure to open the South Korean market wider,
especially to American products.
   Of 3,700 college students surveyed, the researcher reported that
85 percent held the United States responsible for partition of the
Korean Peninsula.
   The United States and the Soviet Union divided the peninsula in
1945 to end Japanese occupation at the end of World War II. The
communist nation was established in the North in 1948, and a
pro-Western republic was created in the South.
   North Korea invaded the South in 1950, starting the Korean War.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
