<DOCNO> AP880621-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0838EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Rabin     06-21 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Rabin,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Says Civilians Must Help Defend Settlements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said
today that all Israelis _ not just the army _ should defend
settlements in the occupied territories.
   Rabin, in an interview with The Assoiciated Press, also said he
was right to encourage civilians to open fire on Arabs armed with
gasoline bombs.
   The defense minister said he would explain his views to
President Reagan and American officials during his visit to
Washington next week. The date of his departure has not been
disclosed for security reasons.
   ``We have to try together, the military and the civilians, to
take all the measures (needed) to put down the violence,'' Rabin
said.
   The United States has repeatedly expressed concern over Israeli
tactics to quell 6{ months of Arab unrest in the occupied
territories.
   American officials have recently criticized Rabin's statements
encouraging civilians to carry weapons and use them for
self-defense and against Arabs armed with firebombs.
   ``Every civilian settlement is organized for self-defense,''
Rabin said. ``We have lived with terror since the new Zionist
movement started 100 years ago. We are in a prolonged war of
independence ... and everyone has to be aware, prepared, equipped.''
   He further indicated that an Israeli farmer who was bludgeoned
and stabbed to death Sunday night should have been carrying a
weapon.
   The body of 33-year-old Eli Cohen was found Monday.
   ``I am really sorry the farmer who was attacked and viciously
killed did not have the weapon that we would have hoped he would,''
Rabin said. ``I believe the whole results would be entirely
different. He would be alive today.''
   Rabin said the level of violence in the occupied territories had
been reduced but was still unacceptable.
   ``We are determined to meet violence by force,'' he said.
   Nevertheless, Rabin said his recent meetings with Palestinians
in the territories were important to help restore calm.
   Rabin disclosed he had held four closed-door meetings with
Palestinians from the occupied territories over the last several
weeks and said 13 to 15 Arabs had attended those sessions. He
declined to reveal names, saying some of those who had met with him
had received death threats.
   He said he did not negotiate with the Palestinians. ``We just
exchanged views, sometimes conflicting views,'' he said.
   He said the Palestinians he met ``represent a wide variety of
opinions'' but he added ``none of them is formally a member of any
of the PLO organizations. With them, I would not have met.''
   Israel regards the Palestine Liberation Organization as a
terrorist group and has outlawed meetings between Israelis and PLO
members.
</TEXT>
