<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Theaters-Landmark,0124</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Theaters Sue City Over Landmark and Zoning Restrictions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major theater owners have sued the city, saying
the city's efforts to save some theaters by designating them
landmarks may actually have the opposite effect and bring the
curtain down on Broadway.
   The Shubert Organization, the Nederlander Organization, Jujamcyn
Theaters and the League of American Theaters and Producers filed
suit Monday in an attempt to overturn the landmark status of 22
theaters and a restrictive demolition procedure.
   The owners say their problems started in March 1982, when the
Helen Hayes and Morosco theaters were demolished to make room for
the Mariott Marquis Hotel. Two months later, the city instituted a
demolition permit procedure applicable only to Broadway theaters.
</TEXT>
