<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Drug Sweep,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>200 Arrested, 36 Cars Seized in Drug Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orange County's first ``zero
tolerance'' drug sweep resulted in the arrests of 200 suspected
drug dealers and buyers and the seizure of dozens of cars worth
more than $250,000, authorities said.
   Among the eight juveniles and 192 adults arrested in the weekend
sweep were a doctor making a marijuana purchase from his new sports
car and a 16-year-old girl buying cocaine and driving a luxury
foreign car purchased by her father, police Chief Clyde Cronkhite
said Monday.
   Officials said 36 cars were seized, some of them containing only
a small amount of drugs, under the ``zero tolerance'' program which
allows vehicles containing drugs to be confiscated.
   ``If you're going to go out and buy drugs, especially in Santa
Ana, you better bring bus fare,'' U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner said
at news conference.
</TEXT>
