<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Explosives     06-21 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Explosives,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Reportedly Arrested on Israel-Bound Ferry With Explosives in
Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested an Arab who drove a car
containing weapons and explosives aboard an Israeli-bound ferry,
the ship's owner said today.
   Ilias Trochidis said the explosives were found just before the
Paloma was due to leave Athens' port of Piraeus on Monday.
Trochidis said there were 400 passengers and 100 crew members on
the ferry.
   ``Port authority personnel and security men found the stuff
hidden in the car's wheel wells during a security check of around
200 cars in the hold,'' Trochidis said in a telephone interview
from Piraeus.
   ``The guy was asleep in his cabin when they were found. He said
he'd just bought the car and didn't know anything about the
explosives,'' he said.
   Piraeus police officials declined comment. Spokesmen at the
ministry of public order were not immediately available for comment.
   The Cypriot-registered vessel was headed for the southern Greek
island of Rhodes, then Limassol in Cyprus and the Israeli port of
Haifa.
   About 100 of the 400 passengers aboard the ferry were traveling
to Haifa, an official from Trochidis' company, Afroessa Lines, said.
   ``We had Israelis, a few Americans, quite a number of British,
some Greeks, Greek Cypriots and Scandinavians aboard,'' the
official said, requesting anonymity.
   Port authority officials, security personnel and Israeli
security officers routinely check passengers and vehicles leaving
from Piraeus for Israel.
   ``They took out explosives from the wheel wells and knocked a
hole in the underside of the car...I could see gun barrels,''
Trochidis said.
   The Paloma sailed for Rhodes on Monday night, four hours later
than scheduled, he said.
   It was the second terrorism-linked arrest in Greece this month.
On June 1, a Palestinian identified as Mohammed Rashid was picked
up at Athens Airport after a tip from the American Embassy.
   The United States has asked for Rashid's extradition for alleged
involvement in a 1982 bombing aboard Pan Am jumbo over Honolulu
that killed one person and injured 15.
   Rashid also is suspected of being connected with a 1986 blast
aboard a TWA jetliner over Greece killed four people.
</TEXT>
