<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbandonedChildren     06-21 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abandoned Children,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Search For Woman Who Abandoned Five Children At Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five children are in temporary foster care today
while police search for the woman who abandoned them in a hospital
emergency room, saying she'd pick them up later.
   The children, 9-year-old twin boys and girls age 5, 4 and 2, had
medical exams at Cook County Hospital before they were placed in
foster care Monday, said Dave Schneidman, spokesman for the
Illinois Department of Children and Family Services.
   The woman, identified as Brenda Shed, told the children ``that
she was going to find a place for them to live and would be back
for them Thursday,'' said police officer Joseph Tabor, who is
assigned to Cook County Hospital.
   Ms. Shed, her children and a friend were evicted Thursday from
their two-bedroom apartment because she was three months behind in
her rent, said building owner Kirk Toliver. He said the woman moved
into the building six months ago from the Cabrini Green public
housing project.
   Schneidman said a woman came in to the emergency room Monday
morning and spoke with either a security guard or a bystander.
   ``She said, `I'll pick these children up Thursday,' and then she
just walked off,'' he said.
   Schneidman said the woman left her name with someone at the
hospital and gave an address at Cabrini Green. Police investigators
found no one at the address, said Sgt. Al Davis.
   Schneidman said it was too early to say whether the department
would seek custody of the children.
   ``We'd seek permanent custody .... only as a last step,'' said
Schneidman. ``We don't want to get ahead of ourselves yet. ...
Maybe she just thought she'd found a unique baby-stting service.''
</TEXT>
