<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iraq-Mujahedeen     06-21 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-Mujahedeen,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels: 8,000 Khomeini Troops Killed In Three Days Of Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BADRAH, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian rebels claimed today they killed or
wounded 8,000 of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's soldiers in three
days of fighting. The rebels captured the border town of Mehran in
the battle.
   A spokesman for the Iraqi-based National Liberation Army told
The Associated Press in Cyprus that rebel forces were still engaged
in combat today around Mehran. He gave no details.
   Rebels admitted that at least 57 of their troops were killed and
120 were badly wounded in the fighting.
   The Mehran offensive was the rebels' biggest operation. The NLA
is the main Iranian dissident movement that seeks to topple
Khomeini's government.
   The Iranian casualties claimed by the rebels could not be
independently confirmed. Reporters saw more than 1,500 Iranian
prisoners brought to Badrah on Monday.
   Mehran is about six miles east of Badrah and 90 miles from the
Iraqi capital, Baghdad.
   The rebels said in a statement issued by their headquarters in
Baghdad that their forces routed 32 battalions of Iranian regulars
and Revolutionary Guards in their offensive.
   As the 22 brigades of rebels were apparently gradually
disengaging to pull back across the border into Iraq, rebel
commanders have said they did not plan to hold Mehran, whose
civilian population fled years ago.
   A rebel communique had estimated the Iranian strength around
Mehran at 16,000 government troops and Revolutionary Guards, up
from previous estimates of 14,000.
   The rebels did not say how many fighters it had committed to the
battle for Mehran, but its assault force involved an estimated
several thousand men and women.
   Mehran, which has changed hands several times in the nearly
8-year-old Iran-Iraq war, lies a few hundred yards inside Iran.
   The biggest operation before this was Operation Shining Sun in
March, in which the rebels said 15 of its brigades routed the
Iranians' elite 77th Khorasan Division in southwest Iran, killing
or wounding 2,000 men and capturing 1,500.
   The rebels said their gunners shot down an Iranian air force
Cobra helicopter gunship Monday.
   Mehran itself was lightly held and resistance was minimal, but
fighting around positions in the foothills of the Kani Sakht
mountains to the north was reported fierce.
   The rebels began moving massive huge amounts of captured
military equipment back across the border to Badrah Monday.
</TEXT>
