<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Rebels 1stLd-Writethru a0539 06-21 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0539,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Captures Communist Rebel Leader, 40 Others, and Major
Base</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: EDITS throughout to UPDATE with capture of rebel base, ADDS
byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops captured a
communist rebel leader and 40 other guerrillas and dismantled a
major base used by insurgents to launch raids on the main island of
Luzon, military officials said today.
   Gen. Renato de Villa, the army chief of staff, presented the
captured guerrilla leader at a news conference and identified him
as Francisco Pascual, 41, a member of the central committee of the
Communist Party of the Philippines. De Villa refused to identify
the others or say where they were being held.
   He told reporters that Pascual and 40 other rebels were arrested
in raids Monday night in the northern province of Pangasinan, about
110 miles northwest of Manila.
   De Villa called the capture of the base and the guerrillas a
``crippling blow'' to the 19-year-old communist insurgency.
   He said Pascual was in charge of party activities in the central
Luzon region north of Manila and was among rebel and government
officials who supervised a two-month cease-fire that ended in
February 1987.
   Peace talks between the rebels and the government of President
Corazon Aquino broke down in January 1987, and fighting resumed
immediately after the truce expired a few weeks later.
   Brig. Gen. Orlando Antonio, a regional commander who also
attended the news conference, said troops confiscated more than
2,000 sticks of dynamite in a separate sweep in Baguio City, a
mountain resort north of Pangasinan.
   Antonio said Pascual was arrested while on his way to a rebel
hideout in Dagupan, in Pangasinan. Antonio said soldiers seized
assorted documents, a computer and radio equipment powerful enough
to transmit messages to much of central and northern Luzon at the
base.
   ``What we captured in Dagupan was actually an underground house
of the military staff,'' said Pangasinan provincial commander Col.
Romeo Odi. ``In other words, they were orchestrating their
operations from that particular communications center... And so,
with that capture, we are able to paralyze their operations.''
   Officials said the rebels planned to use the explosives to blow
up bridges and other targets in Luzon's Cagayan Valley, a rebel
stronghold.
   Pascual's arrest brings to at least five the number of central
committee members captured by the military this year. Among those
were party general secretary Rafael Baylosis and Romulo Kintanar,
chief of the communist New People's Army.
   ``With the arrest of Mr. Francisco Pascual, the (rebel)
leadership as well as the entire organization is dealt another
crippling blow by the government,'' De Villa said.
</TEXT>
