<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1005EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Drought-Streamflow 1stLd-Writethru a0552e 06-21 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Streamflow, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0552,360</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 4 grafs new material</NOTE>
<HEAD>May Streamflow Below Normal Over Half the Nation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The volume of water flowing in streams and
rivers fell well below normal over half the nation during May, the
U.S. Geological Survey reported today.
   The low streamflows reflected the drought plaguing large areas
of the country.
   The Saline River at Rye, Ark., dropped to only 10 percent of
normal flow for the month, and there was only 15 percent of normal
water in the Tombigbe River at Coatopa, Ala.
   The survey reported streamflows of only 21 percent of normal in
the Peace River at Arcadia, Fla., and the Buffalo River near St.
Joe, Ark.
   The French Broad River at Asheville, N.C., at 40 percent of
normal, also set a record low flow for the month.
   The survey reported that the combined flow of the nation's three
largest rivers _ the Mississippi, St. Lawrence and Columbia _
averaged 617 billion gallons per day during the month, 37 percent
below normal and the second lowest combined flow in 60 years. These
three rivers drain about half of the contiguous 48 states.
   Regionally, streamflows were lowest in California in May at 42
percent below average for the month. Flows were down 40 percent in
the Great Basin of Nevada and Utah; 29 percent in the Pacific
Northwest and 18 percent in the Southeast.
   Turning to underground water supplies as measured in wells,
water levels fell in the Southeast and Southwest. New lows were
recorded in Memphis, Tenn., Montgomery, Ala., and Jackson, La.
   Meanwhile, the Army Corps of Engineers reported that the low
water flows across the nation are damaging to navigation, hydro
power, natural resources and recreation.
   In the southeastern part of the country, low water resulted in a
33 percent deficiency in power generation last week, said Bob Page,
assistant secretary of the army for civil works.
   He said that generation problems are also being experienced at
plants in the Pacific Northwest, but added that he does not
anticipate any power shortages because power is being obtained from
other areas.
   Page added that because of low water, 96 percent of the beaches
at corps-operated reservoirs are unusable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
