<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1021EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Superfund-Critics     06-21 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Superfund-Critics,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Superfund</HEAD>
<HEAD>Groups Attack Superfund Toxic Waste Cleanup Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six environmental organizations and a trade
association say the Environmental Protection Agency's ``Superfund''
toxic waste cleanup program ignores the intent of Congress.
   The groups told a House subcommittee Monday that EPA has ignored
1986 amendments intended to settle the question: How clean is clean?
   Those amendments directed EPA to use ``relevant and
appropriate'' pollution standards contained in other laws, such as
the Safe Drinking Water Act, in setting cleanup goals.
   But EPA uses confusing risk assessments that leave varying
amounts of contaminants in the ground, according to a report from
the Hazardous Waste Treatment Council, a trade association, and the
Sierra Club, the National Audubon Society, the Natural Resources
Defense Council, the National Wildlife Federation, the
Environmental Defense Fund and the U.S. Public Interest Research
Group.
   Much of the report echoed findings of a study by the
congressional Office of Technology Assessment last Friday that EPA
is ignoring another provision of the amendments, that it prefer
permanent remedies in cleanups over simply containing the waste in
the ground or moving it to a landfill that might need to be cleaned
up later.
   Different residual contamination doesn't necessarily mean
cleanups fail to protect health and the environment, said J.
Winston Porter, assistant EPA administrator in charge of Superfund,
in testimony before the investigations subcommittee of the House
Energy and Commerce Committee.
   Different exposures and resources at risk might well justify
different cleanup levels, he said. Porter is in charge of three
dioxin cleanups, ``and I'll be using different action levels at all
three,'' he said.
   In its examples, the report cited lead at the Schmaltz Dump in
Harrison, Wis., and at Rose Township, Mich.
   ``We learn from the Schmaltz Dump, Wis., Record of Decision that
soil lead concentrations greater than 14 parts per million pose an
unacceptable lifetime risk from direct contact. The Rose Township,
Mich., site set a level for lead in soil that is five times higher
than at Schmaltz,'' and other sites permit an even higher
concentration, 100 ppm, the report said.
   The explanation: In Wisconsin, children under three are assumed
to eat one gram of dirt a day; in Michigan, children are assumed to
have no access to the site.
   Walter Kovalik, deputy director of the Superfund office, said
the agency was in the process of forcing its regional offices to
use common exposure assumptions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880621-0105 </DOCNO>
