<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0574,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Arab Youths Shot; Rabin Says Slain Farmer Should Have Been
Armed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with two Arab youths reported
shot today, more Rabin quotes. Picks up 10th pvs, `Rabin, in...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israelis shot and wounded two Arab youths
today, including a 10-year-old boy who was shot by a civilian
firing at a stone-throwing mob in the West Bank, hospital officials
said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said all Israelis, not just the
army, must defend the occupied territories, and he said he was
right to encourage civilians to open fire on Arabs armed with
firebombs.
   Rabin also said that a Jewish farmer found stabbed and
bludgeoned to death Monday should have carried a weapon. Police
blamed Palestinian activists for the slaying.
   The army confirmed an Israeli civilian was stoned in Nablus, in
the West Bank. It said the man told the military that he fired in
the air to disperse the attackers. Army officials said they had no
reports of injuries as a result of the shooting.
   Officials at Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus said the boy was shot
in the leg.
   The second reported injury involved a 16-year-old Arab who was
shot in the shoulder during a clash with troops in the village of
Burka near Nablus, said officials at Al Ittihad.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, quoted Burka
residents as saying the army clamped a curfew on the village and
rounded up all men over 16 at the local schoolyard.
   The army confirmed a Burka resident was injured in a clash with
troops, but it would not provide further details.
   ``We are in a prolonged war of independence ... and everyone has
to be aware, prepared, equipped,'' Rabin said today.
   He spoke a day after Eli Cohen, 33, was found dead in a field
near Moshav Shekev, a communal farm inside Israel and bordering the
West Bank.
   Cohen was the fourth Israeli to be killed during the Arab
uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, which began Dec.
8. At least 210 Palestinians have died.
   Rabin, in an interview with The Associated Press, said he was
``really sorry'' that Cohen ``did not have the weapon that we would
have hoped he would.''
   ``I believe the whole results would be entirely different. He
would be alive today,'' said Rabin, who has been criticized for
encouraging Israelis to carry weapons to defend themselves against
Arabs.
   Cohen left home Sunday evening to spray insecticide on his
vineyard and never returned, said farm spokeswoman Etti Elinsky.
His body was found nearby on Monday. Police said he was stabbed in
the back and beaten, apparently with an iron rod, and his head was
crushed.
   Twenty Arabs were detained, and security forces clamped curfews
on two nearby Arab villages.
   In a stormy meeting Monday night, commune members decided they
would no longer employ Arab laborers, the farm's security officer,
David Elinsky, told Israel radio.
   ``We decided that we will do the job ourselves, with the help of
volunteers, even though this will hurt us economically,'' Elinsky
said. He did not say how many Arabs work for the farm.
   Thousands of Arabs, many from the lands seized in the 1967
Middle East war, work in Israel's agricultural sector, which has
come to depend on the cheap source of labor.
   Earlier Monday, Elinsky had said farm residents were considering
retaliatory measures against their Arab neighbors, including
barring them from using roads leading into Israel.
   ``On second thought, we decided not to take the law into our
hands and to cooperate with the security forces,'' he said after
the meeting.
   But residents complained that the army has ignored requests to
set up patrols following acts of vandalism in the area blamed on
Arabs.
   Residents vented their anger on Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, head of
the West Bank military command, who some tried to prevent from
entering the farm.
   Mitzna told the farmers: ``The war here is a lot more complicted
and difficult ... (but) it's likely that this was a terrorist
attack and we will do everything we can.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir called the slaying a ``serious
incident.'' He said if it indeed was carried out by Palestinian
militants, Israel would respond harshly.
</TEXT>
