<HEAD>Death Penalty Sought for Man Convicted In Officers' Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors say they will push for the death
penalty again for a man convicted for a second time in the deaths
of two police officers.
   ``Let's go for it, all the way,'' said Patricia Fahey, the wife
of officer William Fahey, who was shot to death with his partner,
Richard O'Brien, during a traffic stop in 1982.
   A sentencing hearing begins today for Andrew Wilson, who was
convicted by a Circuit Court jury on Monday. Wilson's 1983
conviction in the case was overturned last year by the Illinois
Supreme Court, which ruled that a confession has been beaten out of
him.
   Wilson's brother, Jackie, was also convicted in the officers'
slaying but his conviction and life prison term also were
overturned because he didn't receive a separate trial. He is
awaiting a retrial.
   Prosecution witness Derrick Martin testified in both trials that
the Wilson brothers let him out of a car two blocks from the
shooting scene just before the officers were shot.
   During the second trial, however, Justice R. Eugene Pincham of
the Illinois Appellate Court testified that Martin had told him he
lied at the first trial.
   Martin also said Andrew Wilson told him he wanted to get some
police uniforms to help a friend escape from jail. Martin said
Wilson told him a few days later that he had killed the officers.
   The defense insisted Wilson was not in the car, even though his
eyeglasses were found at the scene.
