<HEAD>Six Reported Killed in Unrest; Curfew Imposed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 9 grafs with details of violence and curfew, ADDS
that more classes canceled. Corrects day of week in 7th graf pvs to
today sted Monday. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `About 200...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government imposed a curfew in the
capital today after at least six people were killed in street
battles between thousands of protesters and riot police.
   Government radio said in a nighttime broadcast that the
restrictions began immediately and would last until August 19. The
curfew runs from 6 p.m. to 6 a.m.
   Witnesses said thousands of students and other protesters fought
stone-throwing duels with police after authorities closed a Rangoon
university where students had staged peaceful anti-government
rallies.
   ``Five police personnel were killed, and 26 others seriously
wounded as a result of an attack by unruly mob armed with swords,
sticks and catapults,'' the broadcast said. ``A member of the mob
also was killed and several others wounded.''
   ``Since these violent acts disrupt public tranquility and cause
public disorder, the Rangoon Division Peoples Council deemed it
necessary to impose a curfew and ban public meetings and
demonstrations within the Rangoon municipal area,'' it said.
   The broadcast said the mob set fire to one police station and
the family quarters of another station. They damaged
government-owned buildings and traffic light posts, it said.
   The government Monday announced that classes at Rangoon Arts and
Science University, its affiliate colleges and the Institute of
Economics were to be suspended after an upsurge of student protests
against the 25-year-old rule of Burmese military dictato~n.
   Another government radio broadcast today announced the
suspension of classes, effective Wednesday, of two more
institutions where students have staged peaceful anti-government
rallies _ the Institute of Medicine and the Institute of Dental
Science.
   Witnesses said today's fighting began when about 1,000 students
of the arts and science university marched from campus toward
downtown Rangoon. High school students joined them.
   About 200 riot police swung batons and hurled stones to stop the
marchers about two miles south of the campus, witnesses said.
   They said the demonstrators, who had grown to 5,000 strong,
hurled stones and other objects and forced police to retreat a
block south to a military barricade.
   The protesters then dispersed in small groups.
   In the nearby Sanchaung area of the city, there were sporadic
clashes between protesters and police, who reportedly used tear gas
and firearms. It was not immediately clear if there were casualties
in those clashes.
   Throughout last week, students held anti-government rallies at
the university and put up posters that demanded the legalization of
student unions and the release of students who had been detained in
earlier protests.
   Several days of student unrest at Rangoon universities climaxed
on March 18 with anti-government riots that police and military
units rapidly crushed.
   According to diplomatic sources in Bangkok, Thailand, as many as
100 people may have died in the March 18 violence. The government
said two students were shot by riot police.
</TEXT>
