<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChicagoLibrary     06-21 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Library,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Picks Neo-Classical Design For Library</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A romantic, neoclassical design has been selected
for a new $140 million central library building in a departure from
the steel-and-glass box architecture that marks the city's skyline.
   The new library, which will be the largest municipal library in
the United States, will be named after Mayor Harold Washington, who
died last year.
   Officials on Monday announced a jury's selection of a design
submitted by the Sebus group, one of five teams of architects,
developers and builders. The project has been debated since 1976.
   The city's Library Board was expected to give its endorsement
today. The new library will cost $140 million and is scheduled for
completion in 1991.
   ``The majority felt it was the one most consistent with the
architecture in the area,'' said Norman Ross, the jury's chairman.
``It feels like a library to many people, and it relates to the
surrounding great architecture.''
   The building's classical design reflects such historic Loop
landmarks as the Art Institute and the Auditorium Building.
   The plans call for a 10-story building with a pink granite and
brick facade, multistory arched windows, an array of skylights and
a large lobby. It will include a 400-seat auditorium and skylit
gardens.
   Most of the central library's 2.3 million-book collection has
been stored in a warehouse since 1974, when it was moved from a
central library building built in 1897. The building built in 1897
replaced a library destroyed in the great Chicago fire of 1871, but
the replacement was deemed inadequate within two decades.
</TEXT>
