<DOCNO> AP880621-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Drought-Senate     06-21 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Senate,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speed Drought Aid to `Brown and Brittle' Lands, Urges Ag Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should speed aid to farmers hard hit
by drought that has caused $1.8 billion in crop damage and left ``a
brown and brittle land'' in its path, the Senate Agriculture
Committee chairman said today.
   ``You've got to be giving some help to these people, to say hang
on,'' Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., told a news conference. ``...
At what point do they sit around the kitchen table and start to
say, `I can't take it anymore.' I don't want that to happen.''
   Leahy, who headed a three-state tour of drought-stricken wheat
lands over the weekend, said the bipartisan task force of lawmakers
and administration officials that has been monitoring the drought
should sit down on Wednesday and come up with a blueprint for aid
to farmers.
   He said he had some thoughts about what the package should
contain but added that all of the task force members should have
their say before any type of drought relief legislation is unveiled.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng told lawmakers last week
that they should be ready to produce legislation but not make
anything final until after the full extent of the problem is
understood.
   Leahy said it was not too soon to start shaping an aid package.
He said the drought has not only caused $1.8 billion in crop
damage. On their foray to Montana and both Dakotas over the
weekend, he said, the lawmakers found that the blazing sun and
shortage of rainfall had left ``a moonscape'' and a ``brown and
brittle land.''
   ``What I saw was not a disaster in the making,'' Leahy said.
``What I saw was a disaster now.''
   Even if the task force reaches a consensus this week on the
shape of an aid package, it would most likely take weeks or longer
to get the bill to President Reagan's desk. Thus far, urban
lawmakers who are persistent critics of agricultural subsidies have
held their fire amid the outcry from the Farm Belt for drought aid.
   The Senate Appropriations Committee balked on Monday at a
proposal to guarantee 92 percent of federal income-support payments
to wheat, feed grains, upland cotton and rice producers whose crops
are wiped out by the drought.
   Sen. Quentin Burdick, D-N.D., proposed the measure, saying the
situation in his home state already was grim. But other panel
members said it was still too early to act and that his proposal
would have provided no aid to producers of crops not covered by
USDA programs.
   In the end, the panel did not vote on the proposal and instead
voted to attach a ``sense of Congress'' resolution calling for
drought aid in a $47.3 billion agriculture appropriation bill for
the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
