<DATELINE>HOWE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck hit the back of a chartered bus
carrying members of a Michigan drum and bugle corps early today and
36 people were injured, none critically, authorities said.
   The bus had stopped for mechanical problems and was struck when
it pulled back onto the roadway, said state police Cpl. Ron
Johnston. Fog may have contributed to the accident, he said.
   The bus was one of three returning about 60 members of the
Aurora Drum and Bugle Corps to Saginaw, Mich., from a Monday night
competition in Mishawaka. The members range in age from 14 to 21.
   Steve Stigall, a corps instructor riding on another bus, said
most of the youths were asleep when the accident occurred.
   ``All they can remember is something hitting them in the rear
and being thrown forward,'' said Stigall, of Somerset, Ky.
   Six rows of seats at the rear of the bus were crushed by the
impact, said instructor Joe Kuerzi of Louisville, Ky.
   The injured were treated at hospitals in LaGrange and Steuben
counties in northern Indiana and in Sturgis, Mich.
   Police dispatcher Cindy Culp identified the truck driver as
Larry Noble, 40, of Clinton, Iowa. His condition was not available.
