<DOCNO> AP880621-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1204EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Bhopal     06-21 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Bhopal,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Carbide Blames Indian Government For Delay In Bhopal Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEEMA SIROHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American representative of Union
Carbide Corp. today accused the Indian government of delaying a
settlement in the 1984 Bhopal gas disaster and said the company
would begin settling with individuals.
   ``We are frustrated because of the attitude of the government.
The political will is not there to settle the case,'' said the
representative, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``They talk about settling the case out of court but do not have
the authority from the top to do so,'' he said. ``We will settle
with individuals. They all have their own lawyers.''
   About 523,000 people have filed claims in the Bhopal District
Court. Union Carbide lawyers say the government attorneys have not
yet certified if the claims are true.
   Nearly 3,000 people died and 20,000 were seriously injured when
methyl isocyanate gas leaked from a Union Carbide subsidiary's
plant in Bhopal in December 1984. It was the world's worst
industrial disaster.
   The Indian government filed a $3 billion compensation suit
against the Danbury, Conn.-based multinational but the case still
is at the pre-trial stage.
   The Indian government also passed a law making it the sole legal
representative of the victims.
   When asked if the settlement with the victims would be legal in
view of the law, the Union Carbide source said: ``The case can be
settled in the United States. There is no law to prevent that.''
   However, H.K. Khan, secretary of India's Chemicals and
Petrochemicals Ministry, said Union Carbide could not settle
directly with the victims.
   The government last week requested the Bhopal court to issue an
injunction blocking Union Carbide from such a move.
   Judge M.W. Deo is to rule on the application July 29.
   Khan said the Indian government ``had to go back to court
because there was no proper offer forthcoming from Carbide'' for an
out-of-court settlement.
   He refused to discuss figures.
   Sources close to Union Carbide said in November 1987 that the
company was willing to pay $650 million in an out-of-court
settlement but the Indian government was pressing for more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
