<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Robbery,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Report Fatal Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two ex-convicts shot and killed five bank clerks
in northern China and made off with the equivalent of more than
$40,000, the official Xinhua News Agency reported Tuesday.
   One of the robbers later was killed by police, and the other was
captured following the theft early Monday, the dispatch said.
   The report did not identify them.
   Xinhua said the two men broke into a branch of the Construction
Bank of China at Shizuishan, in northern Ninxia province, at
midnight.
   They shot dead five bank clerks who were living in the bank
building and stole 160,000 yuan (about $43,243) in cash and state
bonds. Workers in China often are housed in or near their workplace.
   The two men were confronted by police while buying tickets at
the railway station. Police shot one man while the other escaped
with the money. He was captured a few hours later, Xinhua said.
   Armed bank robberies are unusual in China, where possession of
firearms is illegal.
</TEXT>
