<2ND_LINE>AM-Tunisia Statues,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Statues of Former Leader Being Dismantled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bronze statues of former
President-for-Life Habib Bourguiba have been removed, and
authorities are planning to dismantle others, it was reported
Tuesday.
   An equestrian statue of Bourguiba was removed under cover of
darkness in Tunisia's religious capital, Kairouan, last week.
   The move followed City Council's decision to rename the main
street that had been named for Bourguiba, the newspaper Tunis-Hebdo
reported.
   In the city of Gabes, 225 miles south of the capital of Tunis,
municipal authorities decided to remove two statues of Bourguiba,
the paper said. A statue of Bourguiba dominates the main street of
Tunis, still named for him.
   Many Tunisian cities have either a statue or street in honor of
the ousted leader. The newspaper Al Sabah reported that all these
reminders of Bourguiba's virtual dictatorship for 30 years would
soon disappear.
   He was ousted in November by his interior minister, Zine El
Abidine Ben Ali, after a panel of physicians pronounced Bourguiba
senile and medically unfit to carry out his duties as president.
   Bourguiba, 84, lives in a chateau 20 miles south of Tunis and is
accorded ``all the respect due to a former chief of state,''
officials said.
</TEXT>
