<DOCNO> AP880621-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1231EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Communists     06-21 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Communists,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West's Largest Communist Party Chooses Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's Communist Party, the largest in the West,
chose a new leader on Tuesday to try to halt its erosion at the
polls.
   Achille Occhetto, the No. 2 in the party, was voted its
secretary in balloting by the Central Committee and the Central
Control Commission. The vote was 278-3, with five abstentions.
Occhetto was the only candidate.
   He succeeds Alessandro Natta, who suffered a heart attack in
April and has been under increasing criticism for the party's
electoral slide. Natta, 70, resigned June 13.
   In a speech Monday night to members of his party _ Italy's
second-largest _ Occhetto, 52, defended Natta's leadership but
called for greater openness and a firmer line against the
government, led by Christian Democrat Premier Ciriaco De Mita.
   The party says it has 1.2 million members, double that claimed
by its French counterpart, the second-largest Communist Party in
the West.
   The Italian Communists have been excluded from government since
1947. But they were at the threshold of power in the mid-1970s when
led by Enrico Berlinguer, who declared the party's independence
from Moscow. In 1976, the party captured 34.4 percent of the vote.
   Natta, who took over after Berlinguer's death in 1984, pledged
to follow his policies but lacked his political charisma.
   The party entered a period of drift and in 1987 suffered its
worst election defeat in 20 years, slipping to 26.6 percent of the
vote for the Chamber of Deputies in Parliament. Last month, the
Communists won only 21.9 percent of the vote in local elections.
   Occhetto on Monday noted that the party's traditional base of
support had shrunk and pledged to ``work for a new Communist
Party.''
   The Communist leader, heavy-set with a graying walrus mustache,
was born in the northern city of Turin. He joined the Communist
youth federation in 1953, won election to Parliament in 1976 and
has been re-elected three times. He was made party vice-secretary
after the disastrous 1987 elections.
   The Rome newspaper Il Messagero said Occhetto has ``a bit of a
`yuppie' ... image,'' noting his interest in sailing and gourmet
cooking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
