<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Rabin     06-21 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Rabin,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rabin To Washington, Ready For Expected U.S. Criticism</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   p
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said
Tuesday he will tell U.S. critics of Israel that his country has to
respond forcefully to an Arab rebellion if it wants to remain an
independent state.
   Palestinian leaders of the 6{-month uprising have ``far-reaching
political goals that can endanger Israel's future and its
security,'' Rabin said in an interview with The Associated Press.
   ``If we would like to remain an independent Jewish state ... we
must be strong,'' Rabin said. ``We cannot accept the present level
of violence against us.''
   He also said all Israelis, and not just the army, had the job of
defending towns and settlements.
   ``We have to try together, the military and the civilians, to
take all the measures (needed) to put down the violence,'' he said
in his office within the walled Defense Ministry compound in Tel
Aviv. ``Everyone has to be aware, prepared, equipped.''
   The 66-year-old former Israeli prime minister and army chief of
staff is scheduled to go to the United States in the next few days
to meet with officials including President Reagan. His itinerary
was not revealed for security reasons.
   U.S. officials have expressed disapproval of some Israeli
tactics to quell Arab unrest in the occupied territories and are
expected to voice their concerns to Rabin during his visit.
   Most recently, they have questioned Rabin's statements
encouraging civilians to carry weapons and open fire on Arabs armed
with firebombs.
   But Rabin said he was right to urge civilians to shoot in
self-defense and added that if an Israeli farmer killed this week
had been carrying a gun, he would still be alive today.
   ``I am really sorry the farmer who was attacked and viciously
killed did not have the weapon that we would have hoped he would,''
Rabin said. ``I believe the results would be entirely different. He
would be alive today.''
   The body of Eli Cohen, 33, was found Monday in his vineyard
south of Jerusalem. He had been bludgeoned and stabbed to death,
and police have blamed Arab nationalists for the attack.
   ``In a way,'' Rabin said, ``we can call the last 40 years the
continuing war of independence ... and we are determined to meet
violence by force.''
   Rabin also disclosed he had met four times in recent weeks with
more than a dozen Palestinian leaders from the occupied territories
and said the sessions were fruitful simply because they kept the
channels of communication open.
   ``It was not in the format of negotiations. We just exchanged
views, sometimes conflicting views,'' Rabin said.
   He declined to identify them, saying some of those with whom he
had met had received death threats. But he said the Palestinians
``represent a wide variety of opinions.''
   He stressed that ``none of them is formally a member of any of
the PLO organizations.''
   Israel views the Palestine Liberation Organization as a
terrorist group and has outlawed meetings between Israelis and PLO
representatives.
</TEXT>
