<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Number of Japanese Births at Record Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan reported 1,346,666 births last year, a record
low partly due to the later age at which women are marrying, the
Health and Welfare Ministry said Tuesday in its annual report.
   A ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the nation's birth rate fell to a record low of 11.1 per 1,000
people in 1987.
   Japans previous lowest birth rate was in 1986, when 11.4 babies
were born per 1,000 people, the official said.
   The official said the average Japanese woman married at the age
of 26.5 years in 1986, up from 25.7 years in 1978.
   Japan recorded 751,181 deaths last year _ 6.2 deaths per 1,000 _
or 561 more than the year before, the official said. The population
in October was 121.5 million.
</TEXT>
