<HEAD>Death Toll to 15 In Ethnic Clashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three days of violent street clashes
between ethnic Indians and native Pakistanis in the southern city
of Hyderabad has left 15 people dead, officials said Tuesday.
   The riots began Saturday after the Pakistanis opened fire on the
Moslem Indians, whose families had emigrated to this country after
its partition from India in 1947.
   Officials on Monday lifted a curfew in Hyderabad, 84 miles north
of Karachi, for one hour, and five people were stabbed or shot to
death and 15 wounded.
   Army troops sealed off the city with barbed wire.
   Riots in the past two years have killed hundreds of people in
the southern province of Sind, which includes Hyderabad and
Karachi, a port city where the ethnic groups share cramped slums
and compete for jobs.
