<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Fine Against Maria DeSillers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An administrative judge has dismissed a
$1,000 state fine against Maria DeSillers for failing to register
as a charity when raising money to pay medical bills for her son's
liver transplants.
   Administrative Hearing Officer Donald Alexander said all the
money donated to Ronnie DeSillers' mother for his liver transplants
now belongs to the boy's estate. He said that means the money is
not subject to state charity laws.
   In a decision released today, Alexander emphasized that he was
not ruling on whether Mrs. DeSillers received or used the money
legitimately, but only whether she was required to register as a
charity.
   There are other court remedies available for those questioning
her use of the money, he said.
   Ronnie DeSillers, 7, died at Children's Hospital in Pittsburgh
last year while awaiting a fourth liver transplant. His plight
resulted in a highly publicized fund-raising drive that included a
$1,000 donation from President Reagan.
   According to court documents, almost $300,000 of the $527,000
that remained in Ronnie's account when he died has been spent.
About $243,500 remains in the estate.
</TEXT>
