<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Notebook,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Summit Sense of Humor Shines Through Serious Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher arrived
for this year's summit of Western leaders ready to take care of
business in a hurry.
   A Canadian official involved in running the summit says that
before Sunday's opening session, Mrs. Thatcher was looking around
the room where the world leaders were about to launch three days of
meetings over an octagonal table.
   West Germany's Hans-Dietrich Genscher, on his way to the
separate meeting with his fellow foreign ministers, poked his head
in the room and Mrs. Thatcher bantered with him briefly about his
tan and other topics.
   As Genscher waved good-bye, Mrs. Thatcher told him jokingly,
''I'll go to the table, work on the communique and have it finished
by the time the others arrive.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Authorities at the economic summit have been able to keep their
wit despite the extraordinary security that has engulfed the
meeting site and surrounding area.
   One jovial security official, searching a reporter's small but
tightly packed handbag, turned to a colleague and remarked, ``Even
if she had a bomb in here she wouldn't be able to get it out.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With the exception of Tuesday's closing news conferences, only a
fraction of the 3,000 journalists covering the economic summit have
had a chance to see, much less question, the seven world leaders.
   So reporters have tried to make the most of the brief ``photo
opportunities'' that were held as the leaders came and went.
   One of the finer exchanges of the three-day summit:
   ``Anything new on Haiti, Mr. President,'' a reporter shouted at
Ronald Reagan.
   No answer.
   ``Anything old?''
   ``Just me,'' the 77-year-old Reagan replied.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Antonia De Mita, daughter of the Italian prime minister,
captured the attention of the world media as she was whisked into a
dinner for summit spouses.
   She told reporters that she spent the day shopping in the city's
ritzy Yorkville district. But when asked what she bought, she
turned to her mother, struggling for the English word for jumpsuit.
   ``Don't say foolish things,'' Anna De Mita shot back with a
shake of her finger. Then, daughter in tow, she hurried inside for
the dinner.
</TEXT>
