<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1253EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     06-21 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Splinter Group Will Advocate Approval of Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A splinter group within the
striking Writers Guild of America announced today it would oppose
the union leadership and call for approval of the latest producers'
offer to end the 16-week-old strike.
   About 300 members of the Writers Coalition met Monday night and
voted to oppose the guild at Wednesday night membership meetings in
New York and Los Angeles, where the contract will be voted on.
   ``The feeling that came out of the meeting is that the board and
negotiating committee are very much out of touch with the (guild)
membership,'' said publicist and guild member Dick Guttman, who
attended the Writers Coalition meeting.
   The Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers offered
a $71 million contract last Thursday, but the Writers Guild said
the economic package on foreign and one-hour residuals was
unacceptable.
   Writers Guild spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden, who said union
officials were aware of the coalition meeting Monday night, today
urged members ``to wait until Wednesday night's meeting to hear the
presentation on the proposal before they give their proxies to
anyone to vote.''
   The coalition claims about 600 members within the 9,000-member
union. But its members are among the guild's most frequently
employed, and therefore the biggest contributors to its health,
welfare and pension fund, coalition leaders have said.
   It also includes several of the industry's top ``hyphenates'' _
writer-producers who hold union cards but also have become
management by starting their own production companies.
   Among those in the coalition are ``L.A. Law'' producer-writer
Steve Bochco; Stephen Cannell, who produces ``Hunter''; and John
Hughes, producer and writer of such films as ``The Great Outdoors''
and ``Planes, Trains and Automobiles.''
   The coalition has been working behind the scenes since the
beginning of the strike, but made no public pronouncements until
last week, when the union's negotiating committee and East and West
Coast boards decided to reject the producers' latest offer.
   The strike vote on Wednesday comes on the eve of the new
television production season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
