<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Strike,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 4,000 Yugoslav Workers March To Protest Low Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 4,000 striking truck and
metal workers in the northern republic of Slovenia marched Tuesday
to protest low wages, sources reported.
   The workers met with officials in the city of Maribor, about 15
miles south of the Austrian border, and demanded a 50 percent pay
increase, said the sources, who requested anonymity.
   The workers, who were from the Tam truck-manufacturing plant and
the Primat metal factory, earn an average wage of about $210 a
month, according to the Tanjug news agency, though Slovenia is
Yugoslavia's wealthiest republic.
   The government has linked wages to industrial productivity as
part of a severe austerity program designed to cut Yugoslavia's 170
percent inflation rate and its $21 billion debt.
   Last week, about 5,000 agricultural workers rallied in front of
the Parliament in the capital of Belgrade to demand better living
standards.
</TEXT>
