<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Military     06-21 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Military,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov't Announces Length of Alternative Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has sent to parliament a
bill allowing conscientious objectors to the draft to serve three
years of alternative civilian service, a spokesman said Tuesday.
   The alternative service for males exempted from military duty
will be shorter than outlined earlier this year, said government
spokesman Jerzy Urban.
   In January, the government said it was considering requiring
draftees who qualified for alternative service to perform four
years of alternative service.
   Under a bill approved by the Council of Ministers on Monday,
however, it will last three years, while students released from
military obligations will be required to serve only one to two
years, Urban said.
   A military commission that will include civilian participants
will be established to consider the requests to determine the
authenticity of the applicant's motives, Urban said.
   Current law mandates that all young men perform up to two years
of military service.
   The banned peace group Freedom and Peace has campaigned for the
establishment of alternative service since the group was formed in
1985.
   Only last week the group scored its greatest success to date
when parliament adopted a new military oath that drops any
reference to serving alongside the Soviet army.
   Urban refused to comment on the fate of 16 members of the group
which the group says are imprisoned either for refusing to serve in
the army or to take the oath.
   The Supreme Military court in Warsaw on Tuesday upheld the
2{-year sentence of Freedom and Peace supporter Rafal Budzbon, a
spokesman for the group said.
</TEXT>
