<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Fireworks     06-21 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fireworks,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Commission Warns of Fireworks Danger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tourists standing in line at the Washington
Monument flinched in surprise Tuesday as federal safety officials
blew two dressed turkeys to bits in a demonstration of the dangers
of fireworks.
   A pair of watermelons also met their end as the Consumer Product
Safety Commission used the monument grounds to conduct its annual
pre-Fourth of July event for the news media.
   ``This July 4th marks Uncle Sam's 212th birthday. What better
way to celebrate than to make sure that fireworks do not spoil the
occasion,'' commission Chairman Terrence M. Scanlon said.
   Federal and state laws ban firecrackers with more than 50
milligrams of powder _ the small, finger-type firecrackers. But
agency officials acknowledge that large illegal items, such as
cherry bombs, M-80 and M-100s can still be obtained.
   The M-100s were used to blast the thawed turkeys, blowing them
apart and scattering pieces about. The birds were used to simulate
what could happen to a human being.
   The effect on the watermelons was similar, if more colorful.
   The safety commission also announced that during the last five
months it has seized some 57 million units of illegal fireworks in
a cooperative program with the U.S. Customs Service at 15 ports of
entry.
   Problems found in the products included overloaded fireworks,
defective fuses, unstable bases, casings which blow out on the side
and improper warning labels.
   The commission said approximately 9,000 injuries involving
fireworks were treated at hospital emergency rooms last year, down
from 12,600 in 1986.
   To avoid becoming one of those statistics, Scanlon offered a
series of safety tips:
   _Always read and follow label instructions.
   _Ignite fireworks outdoors only.
   _Make sure an an adult is present whenever fireworks are used.
   _Have a bucket of water at hand in the event of a fire and for
dousing apparent duds.
   _Never try to re-light a firework that does not go off.
   _Never carry fireworks in a pocket and don't throw them.
   _Light only one at a time.
   _Do not set off fireworks in a metal or glass container.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
