<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1318EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lefebvre     06-21 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lefebvre,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Archbishop, in New Attack, Defends Planned Consecration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ECONE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traditionalist Archbishop Marcel
Lefebvre said Tuesday that cooperation with the Vatican is no
longer possible, and he reaffirmed his decision to consecrate four
bishops without papal authority.
   Lefebvre announcement last week to consecrate the bishops on
June 30 drew public warnings from Pope John Paul II and European
Roman Catholic church leaders.
   Elevating bishops without papal permission seems certain to
result in the Frenchman's excommunication from the church and its
first split since an 1870 schism over the dogma of papal
infallibility.
   In a statement, the 82-year-old Lefebvre accused the Vatican of
``continuous and cruel persecution to force our submission'' to the
reforms launched by the Second Vatican Council in 1962-65.
   The church will need years ``to find its way back to its
2,000-year-old tradition,'' the founder and leader of the
traditionalist St. Pius X fraternity in Switzerland said. The
movement will defend this tradition, which is ``the only
possibility for the renewal of the church,'' he said.
   The relationship with the Vatican ``no longer in any way points
to brotherly cooperation and a pure and simple recognition of the
fraternity,'' Lefebvre said.
   He has said the consecration of four of his followers is needed
to ensure the survival of his movement, which claims millions of
followers worldwide.
   According to the Vatican, a May 5 agreement between the pope and
Lefebvre gave the archbishop the right to consecrate one bishop on
Aug. 15. In return, Lefebvre would have promised to be faithful to
the church and the pope, and accept the teachings of the Second
Vatican Council.
   Lefebvre insisted on the June 30 date and on elevating four
bishops, effectively repudiating the accord.
   On Thursday, the Vatican published the text of a letter from the
pope to Lefebvre that urged him to renounce the ``schismatic'' act.
The presidents of the French, West German and Swiss bishops'
conferences did the same.
   Lefebvre, whose movement uses the Latin-language tridentine
mass, has spoken out for some two decades against the Second
Vatican Council.
   The council led to the celebration of Mass in local languages,
an enlargement of the role of lay people, and opening of the church
to other faiths.
   Excommunication is the last sanction left in the Vatican's
arsenal of measures against Lefebvre.
   In 1976, Pope Paul VI suspended him from his priestly functions
_ barring him from saying Mass and giving the sacraments _ but
Lefebvre ignored the order. He continued to ordain priests and
criticize the Vatican.
</TEXT>
