<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For fans of artist Al Hirschfeld, there was a
twist Tuesday on his usual game.
   A story in The New York Times on Tuesday, Hirschfeld's 85th
birthday, had a small ``6'' next to the byline, indicating there
were six ``Ninas'' in the text.
   Normally, the name of Hirschfeld's daughter, Nina, appears in
his sketches, with the number of times revealed next to the
artist's name.
   ``Nina was born on Oct. 20, 1945, and on that day I put in a
drawing, in a circus poster in the background, a little baby
reading a book called `Nina the Wonder Child,''' he said. ``And
since then it has become a national insanity.''
   On Monday, celebrities from the art and theater worlds turned
out at the Margo Feiden Galleries, where much of Hirschfeld's work
is displayed, to honor the man who has captured many of their
likenesses.
   The artist, known for his caricatures of celebrities as diverse
as Humphrey Bogart, Superman and Albert Einstein, estimates
conservatively that he has sketched more than 3,000 drawings.
   In the Times, where many of his caricatures are published,
Hirschfeld said his career began in the 1920's when a friend who
happened to be a press agent saw a caricature he had sketched on a
theater program.
   That sketch was sold to The Herald Tribune, which wanted another
one the following week. About a year later, the Times started
requesting sketches and Hirschfeld kept them coming.
   Hirschfeld said drawing feeds his ``insatiable appetite for pure
line, for distillation, for bringing things down to the simplest
form.''
</TEXT>
