<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YaleProtest     06-21 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yale Protest,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Standoff Continues Over Anti-apartheid Wall At Yale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yale alumnus accused of setting afire
shanties erected on the university campus as an anti-apartheid
protest entered an innocent plea today and requested a jury trial.
   A lawyer for Dr. Elwood Bracey, of West Palm Beach, Fla., who
didn't appear in court, entered the plea in New Haven Superior
Court.
   A date for a pretrial hearing on the charge of third-degree
arson was set for July 14. No one was injured in the incident.
   Anti-apartheid activists, meanwhile, have declared unacceptable
a proposal by the university administration under which a
40-foot-long memorial wall could be reconstructed on campus on a
limited basis if the Coalition Against Apartheid agreed to
voluntarily dismantle the structure and store it for at least the
summer.
   The wall, covered with pictures and statements in support of the
anti-apartheid movement, replaced the shanties destroyed in the
fire June 5.
   Last week, the Yale administration announced that the wall could
remain up only for four days, through noon Monday. However, when
the deadline arrived, the administration didn't try to take down
the wall, but instead proposed a compromise.
   The coalition immediately rejected the proposal.
   ``It's still the university telling us what to do,'' said
Charlotte Hitchcock, a Yale graduate student.
   The shanties and the wall were built by students and comunity
members seeking to end all Yale investment in companies doing
business in South Africa. The coalition said it would not take the
wall down until Yale fully divests itself of such stocks.
   Yale Secretary Sheila W. Wellington said Monday the burning of
the shanties and threats of arson since June 5 have made officials
conclude that the symbolic structures must be temporary, not
capable of being lived in and adequately protected.
   In addition, officials said, the shanties and wall were erected
on a granite plaza located over part of the Beinecke Rare Book and
Manuscript Library. Another fire might not only endanger human
safety, it could also pose a threat to some of the library's rare
documents, they said.
   University police have guarded continuously since it went up,
but officials said that isn't prudent use of police services.
</TEXT>
