<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     06-21 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Holds First Full Joint Debate To Discuss Blacks' Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament's three racially
segregated chambers held their first full-scale joint debate
Tuesday, discussing a bill that would expand blacks' political role
while keeping them out of Parliament.
   Most prominent black leaders have rejected the bill, which is
aimed at negotiating a power-sharing system in which the white
minority would retain political and economic control.
   The dominant white chamber of Parliament has sat previously with
the 4-year-old Asian and mixed-race chambers, but only for
ceremonial occasions and major speeches, not to debate legislation.
The only previous joint debates have been in committees, not among
the full chambers.
   On the agenda Tuesday was a controversial proposal to establish
a council that would negotiate a new constitutional system. The
government says the council also would provide a voice for blacks
in national affairs during the period of negotiations.
   The council, with a minimum membership of 36, would include
Cabinet ministers, provincial administrators, eight presidential
appointees, leaders of six semi-autonomous black homelands, and
nine blacks chosen on a regional basis by black municipal
councilors.
   The most prominent of the homeland leaders _ Chief Minister
Mangosuthu Buthelezi _ has declared that he won't participate on
the council until African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela
is released from prison.
   More militant black leaders, as well as many anti-apartheid
whites, have rejected the bill outright, saying it is an attempt by
the government to evade demands for a one-man, one-vote democracy.
At present, the 5 million whites hold political and economic power,
while the 26 million blacks have voting rights only in homeland and
municipal elections.
   Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis, speaking in
Parliament, described the bill as a legislative landmark.
   ``It is the first time in our history that legislation is being
introduced with the goal of laying a foundation for the
participation of all South Africans and communities in the
political and governing process,'' he said.
   ``Those who want to perpetuate racism will certainly say the
legislation is the last nail in the coffin of the whites,'' Heunis
said, adding that the bill would be ``mercilessly fought by
revolutionary and violent forces'' on the left.
   But he said South Africans interested in peaceful solutions will
view the bill as ``an attempt to give content to the high ideals of
liberation and freedom.''
   The Star, South Africa's largest daily newspaper, said in an
editorial Tuesday that ``no black leaders of consequence seem
disposed to take part'' in the council.
   The government ``will of course find black faces, somewhere, to
sit on the council, but they will not carry credibility,'' it said.
``The prognosis is not a happy one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880621-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1355EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AirTraffic     06-21 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Traffic,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Task Force to Study Air Traffic Congestion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international agency has set up a task force to
examine ways to relieve airport congestion and flight delays that
have reached a ``crisis situation'' in Europe, a spokesman for the
group said Tuesday.
   The task force held its first meeting May 25 in Montreal, where
it mapped out a working plan to tackle problems created by an
increase in aircraft takeoffs and landings, especially in Europe,
said International Air Transport Association spokesman David Kyd.
   Kyd said in an interview with The Associated Press that aircraft
movements in Europe had increased by 7 percent this year compared
with 1987, and that last year's level may double by the year 2002.
   ``It is now a crisis situation. Everybody's waking up to it,''
he said.
   The six-member committee will examine the traffic problem
worldwide, but is starting with Europe where the problem is most
acute, Kyd said.
   One idea the task force was studying was the possibility of
ending night curfews at airports in order to increase their
capacity, because new quiet jets can land ``almost with their
engines shut down'' and therefore create less noise, he said.
   The task force also was looking at the entire air traffic
control system, and is likely to encourage governments to hire more
air traffic controllers and raise their salaries, Kyd said.
   The task force will meet again in September in London, he said.
</TEXT>
