<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Several Arrested As Demonstrators Stage Sit-In At Summit-Lunch
Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two-dozen demonstrators were arrested
Tuesday when they staged a sit-in outside the art museum where
summit leaders, aides and spouses were to have lunch.
   For the second time in three days, protesters marched down a
major city thoroughfare, saying they wanted to serve a ``citizens
warrant'' for the arrest of the leaders of the summit nations, the
United States, Britain, Canada, France, Italy, Japan and West
Germany.
   The self-styled warrant accused the seven summit nations of
crimes against humanity, ranging from U.S. backing for the
Nicaraguan Contras to persuing economic policies which, they said,
have been responsible for the deaths of poverty stricken people in
major Western cities.
   ``They're the criminals, not us'' and ``Arrest the G-7,'' the
protesters chanted.
   One organizer, Michaele Shapcott, said, ``They're sitting in
there for the cameras saying basically, things are O.K.' but we're
saying, `Listen folks, things are not O.K.'''
   The site of the demonstration, the Art Gallery of Ontario, was
selected by summit organizers as the locale for the final lunch
among the leaders, their spouses and top aides.
   But the final summit session ran late, and the demonstration was
over by the time the summit participants arrived.
   The protesters, who numbered 75 in all, were met by police
barricades and about 100 officers in three ranks, backed by mounted
police.
   One young woman, waving a ``warrant,'' told Toronto policeman
P.E. Semple: ``These people are criminals. We would like you to go
and arrest them for us.''
   The officer, who was armed with a revolver and a nightstick,
replied, ``This is my post right here.''
   On Sunday, more than 130 people were arrested as 1,500
demonstrators defied a police ban and marched toward the
Metropolitan Toronto Convention Center, site of the 14th annual
meeting between the seven largest industrialized democracies.
</TEXT>
