<HEAD>Manigat Calls For International Isolation of Haiti</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted President Leslie
Manigat of Haiti called today for international isolation of
Haiti's new military government.
   Manigat, ousted in a military coup Monday and put on a plane to
the Dominican Republic, called the new regime ``very fragile'' and
blamed the coup on corruption in the military.
   Manigat told reporters in Santo Domingo that he has talked to
foreign governments and international organizations asking them to
reject the government named Monday by Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, the
armed forces chief.
   Manigat, a 57-year-old former political scientist, was elected
in controversial, fraud-marked voting Jan. 17. He said he hasn't
decided where his place of exile will be, but he plans to travel
this month to Europe for meetings with political leaders to rally
opposition to the new government.
   The first he knew of the Namphy coup was as he sat in his home
watching the state television Monday, Manigat said.
   Manigat said he wasn't told where he was being sent until he
landed in the Dominican Republic, which shares the island of
Hispaniola with Haiti.
   Manigat had rescinded Namphy's order retiring and transferring
military officers last week. He had placed Namphy under house
arrest, but his troops freed him late Sunday and Namphy took the
national palace and announced a new government Monday.
