<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1401EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MultipleKillings     06-21 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Postpones Simmons Trial in Death of 14 Relatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge said Tuesday he will postpone
until fall or winter the trial of R. Gene Simmons for the deaths of
14 relatives.
   The trial, which had been set for July 18, follows Simmons'
conviction for the murders of two other people in a rampage last
Christmastime. He has been sentenced to die, but the state Supreme
Court on Monday indefinitely postponed the execution, originally
scheduled June 27.
   ``I think the public has heard enough of R. Gene Simmons for a
while,'' Judge John S. Patterson said in a telephone interview from
Clarksville.
   The high court postponed the execution so that it could consider
whether the Rev. Louis J. Franz of Star City should be allowed to
represent Simmons' interests against Simmons' wishes.
   The court will consider whether the state should have a
mandatory appeal in death sentence cases, or if the court should
review a case in which the appeal is waived.
   The Supreme Court order said written legal arguments on behalf
of Simmons, the state, and Franz should be filed by Monday, with a
hearing set Tuesday.
   One of Simmons' attorneys, John C. Harris of Russellville, said
Simmons would be disappointed by the high court's ruling.
   ``He had his mind made up,'' Harris said. ``He had a court
sentence. He was perfectly willing for it to be carried out. He
didn't want this controversy to go on forever. I don't think anyone
else does except those opposed to capital punishment. I'm
disappointed for him.''
   Simmons, 47, waived his right to appeal after being sentenced to
die for fatally shooting Kathy Kendrick, 24, and James Chaffin, 33,
in Russellville on Dec. 28. He wounded four others during a
45-minute rampage. When Patterson pronounced the death sentence on
May 12, Simmons said he wanted a speedy execution. ``Let the
torture and suffering in me end,'' he said.
</TEXT>
