<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomelessRestaurant     06-21 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Restaurant,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restaurant For Homeless Open In Atlanta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sure, there's food. And waiters. And they even
take reservations. But that's not the point.
   ``Food is not really what we're serving here,'' said the Rev.
A.B. Short, one of the founders of 458 Cafe. ``What we're serving
is friendship, hospitality, brotherhood and sisterhood.''
   The 458 Cafe opened Monday as a full-service restaurant that
caters to the homeless.
   The cafe, which served 25 people Monday, is in an art deco-style
building downtown. Formerly a drive-in liquor store, it was
purchased with $60,000 in federal grants.
   The homeless sit at white tables in the bright room with pink
flowered curtains and are waited on by volunteers. Some patrons
just shrugged when asked to choose from Monday's menu of beef
burgundy or chicken and rice casserole, salad, green beans or corn
and chocolate cheesecake or peaches.
   Meals are available by reservation only. Reservations are good
for several weeks, during which the staff tries to get to know
patrons and assess their needs beyond food.
   ``We're basically looking to establish some sort of relationship
with people, see what they want to do and what's the next step for
them,'' Short said.
   He wants the restaurant to become a multipurpose resource for
the homeless. He hopes to provide weekly visits by a mobile medical
clinic, legal services and support groups for alcoholics and drug
abusers.
   The restaurant is operated by the Community of Hospitality, a
non-profit religious organization. Food is provided by a food bank.
   One of Monday's patrons said relaxing over hot food and fresh
coffee is a rare pleasure. He can't remember the last time someone
asked him ``May I take your order, please?''
   ``The atmosphere here is a whole lot different (from a soup
kitchen),'' said Oscar Shears, who lives in a shelter. ``It kind of
makes you feel like a person again.''
</TEXT>
