<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Probe-Chappell     06-21 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Probe-Chappell,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chappell Claims None in Congress Involved in Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House panel that handles the
Pentagon budget asserted Tuesday ``there is no member of Congress''
involved in the wide-ranging defense contracting investigation, but
he would not back up the statement.
   Rep. Bill Chappell Jr., D-Fla., told reporters he has not spoken
to official of the Justice Department, the FBI or anyone else
conducting the investigation. Although pressed repeatedly, he would
not cite any authority for his comment.
   News accounts have reported Chappell was under scrutiny in the
investigation. The probe is focused on possible bribery of Pentagon
officials by private consultants, who sought inside information
that would allow their clients to win competitive military
contracts.
   Chappell, chairman of the House Appropriations defense
subcommittee, called stories mentioning him ``absolute lies, just a
lot of bunk, as far as I'm concerned.''
   Asked if he thought his telephone has been tapped, Chappell
replied, ``No sir, I do not. There's no reason for it to be
tapped.''
   ``There is no member of Congress, to my knowledge, who is a
target of this investigation _ and I'm a member of Congress,''
Chappell said repeatedly. ``If there's anyone that's involved in
the kind of activities alleged, he should be brought swiftly to
justice.''
   The lawmaker said he and his subcommittee members maintain
regular contact with defense officials and contractors. ``Lots of
people in the contracting business come through our offices,'' he
said.
   Chappell acknowledged he accepts political action committee
contributions from defense contractors, adding, ``I hope they will
keep giving me contributions'' because there's nothing wrong with
receiving them.
   Chappell acknowledged discussing the investigation with longtime
acquaintance William W. Roberts, president of a company in his
district that was searched by FBI agents as part of the probe.
   Chappell said that after reading about the search of Armtec
Inc., in Palatka, Fla., he called Roberts in a light-hearted manner
to learn what happened.
   ``It wasn't a kidding matter to him,'' Chappell said. ``They had
taken all his papers and files. He's cooperating in every way with
the probe.''
   Chappell said he doesn't believe the company is under
investigation, adding that its files were searched to learn
information about individuals under investigation.
   Chappell also denied there was anything improper about his role
in forcing the Army to award a $24.3 million sole-source contract
to Litton Industries for an artillery fire control system the
service didn't want.
   The Washington Times, quoting from Defense Department documents
and sources, said Litton lobbyists used their personal relationship
with Chappell to sell the system.
   ``Congress does a lot of things the Pentagon doesn't want,'' the
congressman said, adding the Army needed the system. Chappell said
he has been trying to get the Army to take the system for a decade,
but the service has ``dragged its feet.''
   The Army preferred to wait for a more advanced system, to be
produced in the 1990s.
   John Thom, a spokesman at Litton headquarters in Beverly Hills,
Calif., said he would have no comment about the role of company
officials.
   ``We sold the Army a darned good system,'' he said.
</TEXT>
