<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EthiopianStowaways     06-21 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopian Stowaways,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Youths Granted Political Asylum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Ethiopian boys have been granted
political asylum in the United States after stowing away on a ship
to escape their country.
   The boys, ages 12 to 14, said they swam to a U.S.-registered
ship anchored in an Ethiopian port, climbed the anchor chain and
hid aboard the boat. It arrived April 30 in Jacksonville.
   Pimketu Tesfazgi, who has been providing a home for 14-year-old
Fustum Rivei Kiafi, said the boys are uncomfortable speaking to
Americans but are eager to fit in.
   ``They want to be like Americans. They want to learn. They want
to know everything. When they finish their school, they want to
work and buy cars,'' she said.
   Now that the boys have been granted asylum, the foster families
they live with can apply to become legal guardians, said Sandy
Saputo, refugee resettlement specialist for Lutheran Social
Services.
   David Angotti, officer in charge of the Jacksonville branch of
the U.S. Immigration Service, said to be granted asylum the boys
had to show there was a ``clear probability'' that they would be
subjected to persecution if forced to return to Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
