<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Homeless     06-21 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves $427 Million To Renew Homeless Aid Grants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee approved
legislation Tuesday authorizing $427 million to renew and expand a
program of aid to the homeless which was approved by Congress last
year.
   The voice-vote approval came after the Democrat-controlled
committee rejected along party lines, 30-19, a proposal by Reps.
Marge Roukema, R-N.J., and Thomas J. Ridge, R-Pa., which would have
channeled homeless aid from a categorical grant program to block
grants.
   Mrs. Roukema argued to no avail that the block grant approach
would give states and cities more leeway in putting the money to
use.
   The panel did approve, however, an amendment by Rep. Joseph J.
DioGuardi, R-N.Y., which would require recipients of homeless-aid
grants to make ``a good faith effort'' to ensure that the housing
facilities they provide are free of illegal drug use and alcohol
abuse.
   When the housing subcommittee took up the bill on June 3,
DioGuardi introduced an amendment which would have required the
recipients to certify that the facility was drug-free. He withdrew
the proposal after Democrats criticized it, but said he would work
on new language.
</TEXT>
