<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1529EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeathPenalty     06-21 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Penalty,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeal Puts Pennsylvania Death Statute In Limbo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state won't schedule executions until
the state Supreme Court rules on an issue that could invalidate
Pennsylvania's death penalty law, officials said Tuesday.
   ``It is clear to us that that issue will have to be resolved
before there is an execution in Pennsylvania,'' said Christopher A.
Lewis, the Casey administration's executive deputy general counsel.
   At issue is whether the death penalty statute provides a method
for executions. Lawyers for Roderick Frey of Lancaster, who was
scheduled to die in the electric chair June 14, argued that no
method is called for, so the law is unconstitutional.
   The court, in blocking Frey's execution, agreed to hear
arguments in September.
   Frey, convicted of arranging the 1979 contract killing of his
wife, Barbara Jean, was the subject of Gov. Robert P. Casey's first
execution warrant. A ruling in Frey's favor could overturn his
death sentence, as well as those of 83 other death row prisoners.
   ``It's a broad-based challenge. It reaches everybody on death
row in Pennsylvania,'' said Barry Steinhardt, executive director of
the American Civil Liberties Union's Pennsylvania chapter. The
ACLU's lawyers help represent Frey.
   The electric chair, at the State Correctional Institution at
Rockview, has not been used since 1962.
   A 1913 law established the state's method of execution. It also
provided that if any section of the law was deemed
unconstitutional, the entire act would be void.
   The U.S. Supreme Court later ruled the death penalty
unconstitutional because many states had what amounted to a
mandatory death sentence for first-degree murder. The court allowed
states to reinstate the death penalty in 1976.
   A new state law was enacted in 1978, but instead of restating
the method of execution, it relied on the 1913 law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
