<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0659,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb In Hindu Market Kills 24; Curfew in Amritsar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE death toll to 24. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, `Officials clamped...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful bomb believed planted by Sikh
militants exploded today in a crowded Hindu market near the Golden
Temple and killed at least 24 people, police said.
   The United News of India news agency quoted unofficial sources
as saying that more than 30 people were killed and 75 others
wounded. Police refused comment on the report.
   At least 45 people were reported injured earlier. Suresh Arora,
senior police superintendent in Amritsar, said some of them died in
hospitals. He said the dead included two Sikh policemen.
   Officials clamped an indefinite curfew on the old walled city of
Amritsar after the explosion.
   About 300 people were in the market frequented by cloth
merchants, yarn sellers and Hindu industrialists when the explosion
occurred, witnesses said.
   Angry people prevented police from coming to the spot about 200
yards from the Golden Temple, the holiest Sikh shrine.
   It was the fourth attack since Sunday blamed on Sikh militants.
At least 43 people have died in the latest violence, and most of
the victims have been Hindus.
   Late Monday, at least six people were killed in neighboring
Haryana state when gunmen believed to be Sikh extremists opened
fire at a crowd of people leaving a movie theater.
   In Amritsar, protesters pelted police vehicles with stones and
blocked them from going to the explosion site, witnesses said.
   Two policemen were injured in the scuffle, according to Arora.
   Dina Nath, one of the people injured in the blast, said the
explosive was hidden inside a motor scooter parked in the shopping
area.
   Police said they were investigating.
   Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent homeland in Punjab state for six years.
   The Press Trust of India said four Sikhs fired submachine guns
into a crowd of people leaving a movie theater in the Haryana town
of Pehowa on Monday. The militants escaped, the news agency said.
   Pehowa is about 20 miles west of the town of Kurukshetra, where
18 people were killed and 33 injured in a bomb explosion in a
market on Sunday.
   Police said they believed Sikh militants planted the bomb,
believed to have been a remote-controlled device.
   In New Delhi, at least four people were killed and 40 wounded
Monday when militants hurled a homemade grenade into an outdoor
vegetable market.
   No arrests have been reported in any of the incidents.
Authorities have ordered police to be on full alert in six north
Indian states and in New Delhi.
   At least 52 people have been killed this year in violence blamed
on Sikh militants outside of Punjab, a northern state.
   In Punjab, the militants have been blamed for the killings of
more than 1,330 people since the start of the year.
   Sikhs make up just 2 percent of India's 800 million people but
comprise a slight majority in Punjab.
   The militants claim discrimination by India's majority Hindus.
</TEXT>
