<DOCNO> AP880621-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1536EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-Congress     06-21 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Congress,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ag Chairman Urges Drought Aid for `Brown and Brittle Land'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Heat Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought aid is needed urgently in the nation's
breadbasket, which has been transformed into ``a brown and brittle
land'' as a result of $1.8 billion in crop damage, a Senate
chairman said Tuesday.
   ``This drought comes at a time when many farmers are just
climbing out of the hole after five years of farm depression,''
Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., said
``But now, with their crops burned and their livestock hungry, they
are once again threatened with bankruptcy.''
   Leahy said that a weekend inspection tour by six senators into
Montana and the Dakotas found ``a brown and brittle land.''
   ``These three states, along with Minnesota, are suffering
through the worst drought this early in the season that has
occurred in my lifetime,'' Leahy said. ``Estimated crop losses in
these states alone are running in excess of $1.8 billion, and
that's a conservative estimate that goes higher every day.''
   He said a drought task force meeting Wednesday should stay in
session until consensus has bee reached on what kind of aid package
to recommend.
   The bipartisan task force of lawmakers and administration
officials was formed last week to monitor crop damage arising from
the broiling sun and shortage of rainfall that has wrung out the
Farm Belt over the last month.
   Any hope of winning approval of drought relief depends on
keeping the issue bipartisan and avoiding friction with the
administration, Leahy said. He praised Agriculture Secretary
Richard E. Lyng for opening conservation lands to hay cutting and
cattle grazing. But Leahy said more aid would be needed.
   Lyng told lawmakers last week to be prepared to move with
drought relief legislation but urged them not to make anything
final until the seriousness of the problem was fully known. Leahy
said, however, that it was not too soon to get started with a bill.
   ``You've got to be giving some help to these people, to say hang
on,'' Leahy told reporters. ``At what point do they sit around the
kitchen table and start to say, `I can't take it anymore.' I don't
want that to happen.''
   He said many afflicted farmers ``have just come through five
years of living hell.''
   ``What I saw was not a disaster in the making,'' Leahy said.
``What I saw was a disaster now.''
   Even if the task force reaches a consensus this week on the
shape of an aid package, it most likely would take weeks or longer
to get the bill to President Reagan's desk.
   In response to a question, he scoffed at the notion that
congressional enthusiasm for the issue may be sparked largely by
election-year pressures.
   The Senate Appropriations Committee balked on Monday at a
proposal to guarantee 92 percent of federal income-support payments
to wheat, feed grains, upland cotton and rice producers whose crops
are wiped out by the drought.
   Sen. Quentin Burdick, D-N.D., proposed the measure, saying the
situation in his state already was grim. But other panel members
said it still was too early to act and that his proposal would have
provided no aid to producers of crops not covered by USDA programs.
   In the end, the panel did not vote on the proposal and instead
voted to attach a ``sense of Congress'' resolution calling for
drought aid in a $47.3 billion agriculture appropriation bill for
the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
