<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Grassley-Probe     06-21 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grassley-Probe,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Investigator Says Justice Dept. Failed to Pursue Fraud Reports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Pentagon investigator said Tuesday
the Justice Department had ``substantive evidence that there was
massive fraud'' in military weapons purchases three years ago but
failed to pursue the case.
   ``We had extensive evidence that other companies were involved''
beyond the few that were charged, Robert L. Segal said at a Capitol
Hill news conference.
   Segal's scheduled testimony to a Senate subcommittee on Oct. 1,
1985, was blocked by the Justice Department because it allegedly
would have harmed ongoing criminal cases.
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, the subcommittee chairman at the
time, has contended this week that the current Pentagon bribery
probe could have been conducted three years ago.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III, at a news conference Monday,
defended the Justice Department against Grassley's charges. ``I can
assure you that at no time has this department had to be dragged
into any indictment where the evidence is there,'' Meese said.
   Segal said that before resigning from the government in January
1985 he had worked 11 years for the Drug Enforcement Administration
for 11 years and for one year for the Defense Department, where he
served as the Pentagon's liaison with the Procurement Fraud Unit in
the Justice Department.
   Segal, now a stockbroker in suburban Springfield, Va., said his
decision to leave government work ``has nothing to do with this
case.''
   He described as himself as frustrated because he said there was
``a terrible lack of competence'' at the fraud unit. ``They
literally were not prepared to handle'' an involved case, he said.
   Asked to estimate the extent of bribery and fraud in Pentagon
procurement, Segal answered, ``I think it's common.''
   He made clear that he doesn't believe that the investigations
were blocked for political reasons, a view shared by Grassley.
   ``What happened has nothing to do with the administration,''
said Segal. ``It's not the administration we're talking about here,
it's the bureaucracy.''
   Grassley said, ``It's the bureaucracy that's at fault, it's not
the administration. This has been a problem of both Democratic and
Republican administrations.''
   Segal said he suggested in 1985 that defense officials and
consultants who passed classified documents should be charged with
espionage. While he said the charge could later be lowered,
``espionage is a leverage item'' in trying to plea-bargain with
people in an investigation.
   Segal said he saw cases involving the alleged unauthorized
taking of hundreds of pages of classified documents. But said ``no
one seemed concerned about the fact that classified information was
being sold, being bandied about.''
   In a related development Tuesday, Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., said
the congressional General Accounting Office estimates that while
the Pentagon says it spent $155 million on consultants in fiscal
1987, the actual cost was $2.8 billion.
   And that figure, high as it is, may be far too low, Pryor said.
He said the GAO estimated that consulting costs might run as high
as $18 billion a year.
   Pryor said the Pentagon ``has been using a very narrow
definition, obviously'' of how to define a consultant's contract.
</TEXT>
