<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewDreamers     06-21 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Dreamers,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Class of '98 Latest Recipients of College Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once again, Eugene Lang has rewritten
Shakespeare for a class of Harlem sixth-graders: to study,
perchance to dream.
   Seventy-seven graduates of Public School 92 entertained visions
of college Tuesday after hearing that their tuition is guaranteed
under Lang's ``I Have A Dream'' program for inner-city youths _
provided, of course, they graduate high school.
   ``It means a lot to me,'' said 12-year-old Paul Getty after
hearing the surprise announcement during graduation ceremonies in
the school auditorium. ``To get a job, you need a college
education. I feel great.''
   Feeling just as good was Lang, who helped arrange the program
which will be funded by the Marble Collegiate Church of Manhattan.
The church, through donations by its 3,500 members, has raised
$270,000.
   ``If you work for it, if you stay in school, if you graduate
high school, you will have no worries,'' Lang promised the
students. ``Your college tuition will be paid.''
   Lang founded the program seven years ago; it now provides the
promise of a college education to approximately 10,000 students in
25 cities around the country. Half the students in Lang's first
group entered college in September 1987.
   Two other Manhattan schools will be designated for the program
later this week.
   Both of those schools will be similar to P.S. 92, which sits
amid a row of burned-out and boarded-up buildings, its playground
littered with bottles and other garbage. But it's what's inside the
schools that counts, program directors say.
   ``I have never seen so much potential waiting to be tapped in
one room,'' said Gloria Caliandro of Marble Collegiate as the
students gave a standing ovation to her and husband Arthur
Caliandro, the church's senior minister.
   Virtually all the graduating boys and girls were shocked and
excited at the prospect of a fully paid college career. Dwayne
Cooper, a 12-year-old aspiring architect, vowed to study hard next
year.
   ``I think it's good to get this chance,'' he said. ``I always
wanted to go to college.''
   Agreed classmate Khaaliq Muhammad: ``It means a great chance to
be somebody. I'm very happy.''
</TEXT>
