<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Carbide     06-21 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Carbide,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Carbide Plans Negotiations With Lawyers For Disaster Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEEMA SIROHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Union Carbide Corp. representative
said Tuesday that the company would negotiate with private lawyers
for victims of the 1984 Bhopal gas disaster.
   ``We will settle with individuals. They all have their own
lawyers,'' said the representative, an American lawyer, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   About 523,000 people have filed claims in the Bhopal District
Court in the world's worst industrial disaster.
   Nearly 3,000 people died and 20,000 were seriously injured when
methyl isocyanate gas leaked from a Union Carbide subsidiary's
plant in Bhopal in December 1984.
   India filed a $3 billion compensation suit against the Danbury,
Conn.-based multinational but the case still is at pre-trial stage.
   The Indian government also passed a law making it the sole legal
representative of the victims.
   When asked if the settlement with the victims would be legal in
view of the law, the Union Carbide representative said: ``The case
can be settled in the United States. There is no law to prevent
that.''
   But H.K. Khan, secretary of India's Chemicals and Petrochemicals
ministry, said Union Carbide could not settle directly with the
victims in the United States.
   He said the company submitted itself to Indian law and is
``bound by the law.''
   The government last week requested the Bhopal court to issue an
injunction blocking Union Carbide from such a move.
   Judge M.W. Deo is to rule on the application July 29.
   The Union Carbide representative said it was waiting for the
Indian government to provide the company with the exact number of
``real victims.''
   Khan said the government lawyers will provide the list of real
victims to the court the court begins hearing individual cases.
   ``We are under no obligation to provide the list to Union
Carbide,'' he said.
   Khan said the Indian government ``had to go back to court
because there was no proper offer forthcoming from Carbide'' for an
out-of-court settlement. He refused to discuss figures.
   Sources close to Union Carbide said in November 1987 that the
company was willing to pay $650 million in an out-of-court
settlement but the Indian government was pressing for more.
</TEXT>
