<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     06-21 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disputed Region's Legislature Asks Temporary Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nagorno-Karabakh's legislature on Tuesday asked
that the southern territory be made independent until Moscow
decides whether it belongs to Soviet Armenia or Azerbaijan, reports
from the area said.
   Most of 160,000 people in Nagorno-Karabakh are ethnic Armenians,
a mainly Christian ethnic group, but it was assigned in 1923 to the
predominantly Moslem neighboring republic of Azerbaijan.
   The legislature voted Feb. 20 to request annexation to Armenia
and the Armenian legislature supported it, but Azerbaijan has
refused to give up the territory and Moscow has not said whether it
will decide the question.
   On Tuesday, the Nagorno-Karabakh legislators appealed to the
federal Supreme Soviet for temporary independence, according to
Koryun Nahabidyan, an Armenian activist in Moscow who spoke to
Nagorno-Karabakh residents familiar with the decision.
   Nahabidyan, who has led several Armenian demonstrations in
Moscow, said the legislature asked for independence until the
Supreme Soviet, the national parliament, decided whether
Nagorno-Karabakh would remain part of Azerbaijan or be given to
Armenia.
   A resident of Stepanakert, the territorial capital, said the
``whole city'' of 60,000 people gathered outside government
buildings to await the legislature's decision. The resident,
speaking by telephone on condition of anonymity, said the members
rejected a proposal to secede from Azerbaijan.
   He said the legislature appealed to residents who have been
striking since May 23 to return to their jobs, then added without
elaboration: ``People won't return to work because the session was
unclear. Some of the deputies said things people won't like.''
   Reports have said the strike has stopped nearly all commercial
activity in the region except for retailing and agriculture.
   The activist in Moscow, Nahabidyan, said the territorial
legislature asked the Supreme Soviet to disregard Friday's decision
by the Azerbaijan legislature to oppose a transfer to Armenia.
   It also asked the national Supreme Court to take over legal
action against rioters responsible for killing 32 people, most of
them Armenians, on Feb. 28 in the Azerbaijan city of Sumgait.
   Armenians have said the Supreme Court of Azerbaijan, which is
handling the case, is not being severe enough on those responsible.
   In the latest case of ethnic violence, officials reported eight
Armenians and eight Azerbaijanis injured Friday and Saturday in the
Armenian villages of Masis and Sayat Nova.
</TEXT>
