<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     06-21 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>12 Killed in Palestinian Camps Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat's guerrillas and
Syrian-backed Palestinian rivals battled in Beirut's Chatilla and
Bourj el-Barajneh refugee camps Tuesday in a bloody power struggle.
Police said 12 people were killed and 45 wounded.
   The casualties raised the toll since fighting began 12 days ago
to 46 killed and 188 wounded.
   Police said machine gun fire forced the closing of the road next
to Bourj el-Barajneh, which leads to the Beirut airport. Flight
operations were not affected, police said.
   Shell blasts echoed across Beirut as Arafat's Fatah fighters,
the main component of the Palestine Liberation Organization, and
Col. Saeed Mousa's Fatah-Uprising guerrillas pounded each other's
positions with mortar and rocket barrages.
   A Fatah spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Mousa's fighters deployed outside the camps launched two assaults
on Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh around noon. He said both attacks
were repulsed by Arafat supporters.
   Police said Mousa's gunners, deployed in Syrian-controlled
territory in mountains overlooking Beirut, hammered both camps with
155mm howitzers.
   Mousa's fighters also battered the shantytowns with 82mm and
120mm mortars from positions in Syrian-controlled neighborhoods
around the camps.
   Fatah guerrillas responded with 120mm mortar fire, police said.
   Fatah-Uprising said it foiled an attempt by Arafat's men to
storm one of their outposts on the outskirts of Bourj el-Barajneh
in the afternoon.
   Police said two mortar rounds exploded in residential
neighborhoods around Chatilla, killing four civilians and wounding
18.
   They said one 155mm artillery shell crashed into a densely
populated district near Bourj el-Barajneh, wounding three people.
   Fatah accused Mousa's gunners of shelling the camps
``indiscriminately after their repeated failure to achieve any
military victory on the ground.''
   The camps have been the scene of some of the worst violence in
Beirut since 1982, when Christian militiamen massacred hundreds of
people in Chatilla and nearby Sabra.
   The camps, shelled and besieged by Israel's invading army that
year, were later battered by Syrian-backed Shiite Moslems for more
than two years. Thousands of people were killed or wounded in those
battles.
   Now Palestinian is fighting Palestinian.
   Tuesday's fighting raged despite efforts by Libyan mediators and
other Palestinian factions to arrange a cease-fire.
   Arafat's loyalists had dislodged Mousa's guerrillas from the two
camps in earlier fighting.
   But the latter regrouped in Syrian-policed areas of west Beirut
and the city's southern slums and have launched a series of
abortive attacks to regain territory they lost in the shantytowns.
   Mousa broke away from the PLO in 1983 with other Syrian-backed
radical factions in a dipsute over Arafat's policies. They set up
their headquarters in Damascus, Syria's capital.
   Fatah and Mousa's group have been fighting in the camps despite
a reconciliation between Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad in
Damascus in April that was aimed at ending their 5-year-old feud
over who would control the Palestinian movement.
</TEXT>
