<DOCNO> AP880621-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1820EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShantyArson     06-21 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shanty Arson,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Innocent Plea Entered On Behalf Of Doctor Charged In Yale Shanty
Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An innocent plea was entered Tuesday on
behalf of a Florida doctor charged with setting fire to a symbolic
shantytown built on the Yale University campus by anti-apartheid
activists.
   Elwood Bracey, 52, an ear, nose and throat specialist from West
Palm Beach, Fla., who was graduated from Yale in 1958, was allowed
to enter the plea without being present for the arraignment.
   Bracey, charged with third-degree arson, has been free on
$50,000 bond since the fire on an alumni weekend June 5.
   Douglas Daniels, the attorney who represented Bracey in Superior
Court, requested a jury trial for his client. A pretrial hearing
was set July 14.
   Bracey was attending an alumni weekend when he allegedly set
fire to shanties that had stood on a campus plaza since 1986. He
was turned in to police by another Yale graduate who spotted the
early-morning blaze.
   Daniels would not comment on reports there had been an offer, on
Bracey's behalf, to compensate the university for the damage caused
by the fire. The blaze destroyed some large planters and charred
the granite on which the shanties stood, as well as an adjacent
wall.
   Daniels would only say that Bracey had made ``no direct
representation in that regard.''
   The shanties were built by protestors at Yale who oppose
apartheid, the policy of separation of the races in South Africa,
and are seeking to get Yale to end all investment in companies
doing business there.
</TEXT>
