<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PantherDeath     06-21 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panther Death,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rare Panther Dies After Giving Birth; Apparently Fought Another
Panther</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVERGLADES NATIONAL PARK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of seven Florida
panthers equipped with a radio collar in Everglades National Park
has been found dead, near where she bore a litter, park officials
said.
   The animal had apparently been in a fight, possibly with another
panther.
   Park researchers on a daily flight to monitor positions of the
endangered cats picked up a ``mortality signal'' from the collar
June 10. The signal is emitted from the collar when an animal is
still for an extended time.
   The panther, FP-15, was found by a ground crew the following
day, said park spokeswoman Pat Tolle.
   The cat had just given birth but none of her kittens could be
found. Her remains were brought to Miami's Metro Zoo for necropsyy,
but veterinarian Scott Citino said Monday that a cause of death
hasn't been determined.
   ``There were some bite wounds, but we're not sure what made
them,'' he said, adding that the kittens probably were killed by
the same animal.
   The bites were on the cat's foreleg were apparently inflicted by
a large animal, possibly another panther.
   The park's radio collar project, which began in 1986, was
designed to study the habits of the endangered animals. Only about
30 panthers are believed to remain in South Florida, mostly in the
park or the adjacent Big Cypress National Preserve.
</TEXT>
