<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2038EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Solidarity     06-21 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Solidarity,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ambulance Bought With Solidarity's U.S. Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ambulance the banned Solidarity trade
union bought with U.S. money was formally donated to the Polish
state health service on Tuesday.
   Roman Catholic Bishop Adam Dyczkowski, representing Solidarity,
donated the $40,000 West German-made vehicle, decorated with a
Solidarity ribbon, to a representative of the health service in the
southwestern city of Wroclaw.
   Two other ambulances that were bought by Solidarity from a $1
million U.S. government grant have arrived in the western city of
Gorzow Wielkopolski, according to Solidarity spokesman Grzegorz
Jaszuski.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa has decided to donate the entire
grant to Poland's money-starved state health system.
   Solidarity's acceptance last year of the grant has been cited by
Polish authorities to support their charge that the illegal union
is a paid agency of a foreign power.
   Tuesday's ceremony was attended by U.S. Ambassador John R. Davis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
