<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeenSuicide     06-21 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teen Suicide,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Senator Wants Stepped-Up Effort Against Teen Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state senator on Tuesday proposed
legislation that would require training for the ``gatekeepers'' who
regularly deal with teen-agers in an effort to prevent suicide.
   Sen. Nicholas Spano's plan also would require that journalism
classes train future reporters in the coverage of suicides and that
posters with hot line numbers be put up in places frequented by
teen-agers.
   Under Spano's proposals, the state's mental health commissioner
would be required to develop a suicide prevention training program
for guidance counselors, social workers, parent groups, law
enforcement personnel and ``other pertinent gatekeepers.''
   Spano, a Repubican who chairs the Senate Mental Hygiene
Committee, charged that New York state was ``losing its battle to
eliminate teen suicides.''
   Spano issued a report that noted that in 1986 there were 112
suicides in New York state of people ages 10 to 19. Researchers
have estimated that for every teen-age suicide there are probably
100 to 300 attempts, he said.
   Training in journalism classes, Spano said, ``would ensure a
better understanding by future journalists of the impact a suicide
story may have on an adolescent contemplating suicide or families
of victims.''
   The legislation that would require journalism classes to teach
about suicide reporting has no Assembly sponsor. That's usually a
sign that the measure stands little chance of becoming law.
   No quick action appears likely on any of the major portions of
Spano's package of seven bills. Only one has come out of committee
to the full Senate. That would require uniform guidelines for
hospital emergency rooms handling attempted suicides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
