<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2016EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Party     06-21 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Party,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communists Allowing Another Political Voice In Estonia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party is allowing a large group in
Estonia to make a small dent in its monopoly on political power,
but while the grassroots organization wants regional autonomy it
largely backs Kremlin policy.
   The People's Front of Estonia says its goal is to promote the
party's program of ``perestroika,'' or restructuring of Soviet
society launched by Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   While its stated goal is to support Moscow's policies, the
political group appears to be tapping rising public dissatisfaction
with the Communist Party, which the central press has accused
recently of being full of careerists with little concern for the
people.
   The People's Front is careful not to call itself a political
party, instead referring to itself in a 12-point platform published
June 7 in Sovietskaya Estonia as ``a democratic movement based on
citizen initiative.''
   Sovietskaya Estonia reported June 11 the People's Front was
formed in April and amassed 800 local affiliates throughout Estonia
with more than 40,000 members.
   Formation of such a group as the People's Front would have been
impossible before Gorbachev became the party's general secretary in
March 1985 and launched his ``glasnost'' policy, which encourages
openness on many political, social and historical issues.
   ``In 1985-1986 we learned bravely to think, in 1987 bravely to
speak and in 1988, it's time to get experience in acting bravely,''
one of the founders of the People's Front, Estonian economist Edgar
Savisaar, said in a June 7 article in Sovietskaya Estonia.
   While generally supporting Communist Party policies, the
Estonian group puts more emphasis on ``political and economic
sovereignty'' of the 15 Soviet republics, and the ``cultural
autonomy'' of the country's more than 100 ethnic groups.
   Estonia, on the Baltic Sea, has been the scene last year and
this year of several demonstrations asserting national rights.
   Extensive coverage of the People's Front's activities in
Sovietskaya Estonia, the newspaper of Estonia's Communist Party and
government, shows the organization has official backing.
   There was new evidence Tuesday the Estonian Communist Party is
taking the People's Front seriously. Vajno I. Vaelaes, named
Estonia's Communist Party chief on Thursday last week, told the
government newspaper Izvestia some of the group's proposals have
been included in a ``Republic Platform.''
   The platform is to be presented at a nationwide party conference
on Tuesday next week.
   Not all of the informal political groups formed under the banner
of glasnost have had it so easy. The Democratic Union, a group
dissidents formed May 9 as an alternative to the Communist Party,
has been harassed through arrests of group members after
demonstrations in Leningrad, Moscow and Kiev. The official press
has sharply condemned the group.
   The group says it intends to put forward candidates for
government posts and suggest legislation to local governing
councils called soviets. It says it wants to fight corruption,
stagnation and Stalinism _ all themes trumpeted recently by the
Communist Party.
   The only condition for membership is ``active and businesslike
support of the course of perestroika of the Communist Party.''
   In an assurance to the government, the group pledges to abide by
the Estonian Constitution and the republic's laws.
   The 20 million member Communist Party describes itself as ``the
leading and guiding force'' in Soviet society and holds a monopoly
on economic, cultural and political power.
   But the party's policy-making Central Committee has recommended
that the All-Union Party Conference convening in Moscow on June 28
encourage public organizations including ``public initiative
bodies.''
   ``They should use their right to initiate bills, send
representatives to the bodies of power, (and) be partners of the
state in pursuing social programs,'' according to the
recommendations.
   Sociologist Tatyana Zaslavskaya, a Gorbachev adviser, said last
month she supports the idea of ``social institutions or people's
unions'' to assist and advise the party. But she ruled out
establishment of competing parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880621-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1638EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Superfund     06-21 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Superfund,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA to Designate 215 Sites for Addition to Cleanup Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said
Tuesday it plans to designate 215 more toxic wastes sites as
eligible for money from the ``Superfund'' toxic waste dump cleanup
program.
   In addition, 14 more sites owned by federal agencies were
proposed for the National Priority List for cleanups, though they
are not eligible for Superfund money.
   The planned update of the list, the seventh since the program
began in 1982, would be the largest since June 1984, when 244 sites
were announced.
   Tuesday's proposals would bring the priority list to 1,177 sites
_ 799 formally designated and 378 awaiting designation.
   In addition, three sites have been deleted from the list because
cleanup work is complete and proposals to list 30 more are being
dropped because the agency now believes cleanups are better
performed under other laws.
   Elaine Stanley, deputy head of Superfund enforcement, said
actions are under way at most of the 30 sites, all of which are
owned by permit holders under the federal hazardous waste disposal
laws.
   Jack McGraw, deputy assistant EPA administrator in charge of
Superfund, told reporters the change might even speed cleanups
because many of the 30 are controlled by large companies who are
eager to ``go ahead and try to reduce what they call their
`liability inventory.'''
   Thirteen of the 215 proposed sites involve hazardous waste
facilities where EPA does not believe the waste law can be used,
because the owner refuses to negotiate or for some other reason.
   Generally, it takes a year to 18 months after proposal for
public comment and agency response before a site is formally added
to the priority list, although EPA sometimes begins studies of
possible remedies before the final designation. The agency says 97
percent of proposed sites wind up on the list. Proposals generally
are made once a year.
   EPA has 29,463 places in its computers as potential hazardous
waste sites and has completed investigations at 8,875. Only the
worst threats to health and the environment, according to a
complicated numerical scoring system, are proposed for the priority
list.
   The agency has said it expects about 2,500 sites on the list
eventually.
   Once on the list, the site becomes eligible for 90 percent
federal financing of the cleanup, with the balance coming from the
state, unless it is owned by a state or local agency. The federal
government will pay only half the cleanup cost of those.
   But before federal and state money is used, EPA tries to get the
polluters responsible to clean up the site. Sometimes those people
are bankrupt, cannot be found or dispute their responsiblity. EPA
can go ahead and do the work and seek reimbursement later.
   The agency says it and the states have secured $600 million to
$700 million in cleanups from responsible parties; 191 court cases
are under way seeking $258 million and EPA has been reimbursed for
$78 million in cleanup work it performed.
   Spending about $1.5 billion a year, Superfund is simultaneously
one of the nation's largest environmental programs and one of the
largest public works programs.
   McGraw said EPA tried to propose as many sites as possible to
clear the pipeline before it begins changing the scoring system
this summer to meet congressional directives.
   Those changes will, among other things, take into account
threats to health through the food chain, give greater weight to
abandoned wells and try to account for potential later emissions of
contaminants into the air.
   The Superfund program came in for renewed criticism in recent
days.
   Last Friday the congressional Office of Technology Assessment
said EPA was largely ignoring congressional orders to prefer
permanent cleanups such as incineration or waste treatment methods
over leaving the waste in the ground and was overestimating costs
of treatment.
   On Monday, a waste treatment trade group and six environmental
organizations echoed OTA's findings in testimony before a House
subcommittee. They also contended that EPA was planning to leave
widely varying waste concentrations behind when cleanups are
complete.
   ``We have a technical response to each'' criticism of specific
cleanup decisions, EPA Assistant Administrator Winston Porter told
the subcommittee. He argued there was simply not enough money for
incineration at every site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880621-0198 </DOCNO>
