<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Pope     06-21 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Pope,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Delegation Protests Pope's Upcoming Visits With Waldheim</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two representatives of major Jewish
organizations met with a Vatican envoy Tuesday to protest Pope John
Paul II's upcoming meetings in Austria with President Kurt Waldheim.
   Dr. Avi Beker of the World Jewish Congress and Leon Feldman,
representing three other Jewish groups, said at a news conference
that they pointed out Waldhiem's past in Nazi Germany's army during
a meeting with Monsignor Renzo Fratini, counselor of the Apostolic
Delegation in Jerusalem.
   Fratini confirmed the meeting and said in an interview that he
would pass along the men's concern to the Vatican, which does not
have diplomatic relations with Israel.
   ``All signs show the pope is displaying his will and going out
of his way to legitimize Waldheim ... that he is actually trying to
penetrate public opinion, in effect challenging the information
campaign conducted by Jewish groups,'' Beker said.
   ``We expressed protest, as well as a hope that perhaps the pope
will now do what he failed to do during the previous visit, and
display some criticism about Waldheim's wartime activities and his
lies about his past,'' Beker said.
   Jewish organizations have charged that Waldheim was involved in
Nazi war crimes during his service with the German army during
World War II.
   Waldheim denies any wrongdoing, but the United States has barred
his entry into the country, saying it found evidence he was
involved in deportations of Balkan civilians in World War II.
   Feldman represents the B'nai B'rith, the American Jewish
Committee and the Synagogue Council of America. Jewish
organizations also protested a year ago when the pope met Waldheim
at the Vatican.
   During John Paul's visit to Austria he will meet Waldheim on at
least three occasions between June 23-27, according to a copy of
the pope's itinerary supplied by the World Jewish Congress.
   Beker said the pope's planned prayer service at the Mauthausen
concentration camp June 24, a day after he is received by Waldheim,
was in particularly ``bad taste.''
   ``The visit to Mauthausen, which is to honor the Holocaust
victims, is actually a desecration of their memory because of these
meetings with Waldheim,'' he said.
</TEXT>
