<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Meese     06-21 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Says Drug Money Needed For Prosecution, Prisons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America is gaining in the war on
drugs but must ensure money is spent on prosecution and jails as
well as seizing illegal drugs, Attorney General Ed Meese told state
attorneys general Tuesday.
   ``The sad truth is ... as long as enough people pay enough often
enough for drugs, somebody's going to find a way to get those drugs
to them,'' Meese told about 40 attorneys general holding a four-day
meeting.
   Several anti-drug bills are pending before Congress, and Meese
said there will be a ``bipartisan executive-legislative summit''
during the next few weeks ``to fashion a bill that would have the
support of both parties and both the executive and legislative
branches.''
   On other matters, Meese again refuted allegations the Justice
Department was slack in pursuing allegations of fraud in defense
contracting.
   ``It was the prompt and effective action by the Department of
Justice working with the Department of Defense, that brought the
case to the point of investigation now,'' he said.
   The investigation is part of the Reagan administration's
``unprecedented campaign against defense procurement fraud of all
sorts,'' he said.
   Meese said the publicity concerning the recent controversy and
resignations at the Justice Department ``hasn't been helpful.'' But
he said the controversy hasn't affected the office ``one way or the
other.''
   Meese said that, in the past, the tendency has been to put
anti-drug money into intercepting drugs and education programs.
   ``That's important, but when that's done the Congress has got to
... make sure we have the resources in prosecution, on the court
and in correctional facilities so we don't have the situation that
often occurs in many of your states _ judges reluctant to impose
appropriate sentences on people because they don't think there's
enough room in the prisons.''
   Meese said recent debate over whether drugs should be legalized
is the result of frustration because progress is slow in the battle
against drugs.
   But he said recent surveys indicate use by high school students
is down and argued that legalizing drugs has never worked in any
society.
   The United States signed an international agreement last year to
join other nations in battling drugs and legalization ``would put
us at odds with all the other civilized nations of the world,''
Meese added.
   This is the worst time to change national policies on drugs, he
said, because ``for the first time we are starting to make
progress. It certainly behooves us not to change our policies.''
   Delaware Attorney General Charles Oberly wondered if Meese was
not overstating the case about progress in the battle.
   ``My feeling is we haven't really seen any decrease'' in drug
use, he said.
   Meese agreed that ``we don't want to make too much out of
statistics,'' but added: ``The important thing is to recognize
there are changes in attitudes among high school students.''
   He said stepped-up efforts are needed to extend drug education
programs to high school dropouts and the unemployed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
