<DOCNO> AP880621-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2044EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeltaTrial     06-21 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Trial,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crew Probably Didn't See Huge Thunderstorms, Pilot Testifies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deadly thunderstorm that caused the
1985 crash of a Delta Air Lines jumbo jet was visible to air
traffic controllers but not to the aircraft's flight crew, a Delta
pilot testified.
   Capt. William Melvin, chairman of a safety committee for the
Airline Pilots Association, also said the crew of Flight 191 may
have been ``set up'' by wind shear training because flight
simulators did not include conditions comparable to the storm that
caused the crash.
   ``He (the pilot) could see the clouds, he could see rain,''
Melvin testified Monday. ``But he couldn't see the cloud
development because he was too close.''
   Melvin, a Dallas-based pilot and wind shear expert who was part
of the initial crash investigation, was Delta's final witness in a
non-jury trial being heard by U.S. District Judge David O. Belew Jr.
   The L-1011 widebody crashed Aug. 2, 1985, killing 137 people and
injuring 25 others while trying to land at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport.
   Delta claims government meteorologists and air traffic
controllers failed to inform the crew of the worsening weather and
wants the government to pay all or part of the claims facing the
Atlanta-based airline. Delta and its insurance companies already
have paid more than $90 million in death, injury and damage claims,
and the final total is expected to exceed $100 million.
   Echoing testimony earlier in the trial by William Haggard, a
meteorologist, Melvin said he believed a smaller, milder rain cell
masked the high-altitude development of the severe storm from the
flight crew.
   But observers south of the storm, where air traffic controllers
were located, could clearly see the development, Melvin said.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators determined
that the crash resulted from a microburst, a severe downburst from
a thunderstorm. Their report said the microburst contained several
wind shears, or strong, abrupt shifts in wind direction.
   Melvin said the crash was the first to document the presence of
more than one wind shear in a single storm. Computerized wind shear
models used in cockpit simulator training before the Flight 191
crash contained only one wind shear, he testified.
   ``The way pilots were trained is, once you get through these
things, there wasn't any more,'' said Melvin. ``That could have set
up the pilots of Delta 191.''
   Lawyers for the government, which contends the flight crew
should have been able to avoid the crash, are expected to begin
presenting their case next week. The trial, which has been
continuing for over three months, is expected to continue for
several more months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880621-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2045EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CondoParking     06-21 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Condo Parking,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dentist's Plan To Sell Beach Parking Spaces Is Upheld</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If people are willing to shell out
$10,000 to buy a parking spot, the town of South Kingston can't
stop Raymond V. McConnell from selling the spaces.
   The state Supreme Court ruled Tuesday ruled that the town has no
jurisdiction over McConnell's plan to sell 40 condominium parking
spaces in his lot at popular Green Hill Beach.
   McConnell and his wife have owned the lot for four years and
have been collecting daily parking fees from beachgoers.
   When McConnell, a dentist from Coventry, sought to sell
permanent rights to the parking spaces, South Kingstown officials
objected, saying he would have to seek a subdivision permit from
the town zoning and planning boards.
   But Chief Justice Thomas F. Fay, in the high court's unanimous
opinion, wrote that McConnell's plan falls under the state's
condominium law, which provides that plans to convert a property
from rental to condominium ownership cannot be regulated by local
boards.
   ``The conversion of the McConnells' lot is a mere change in the
form of its ownership and not a subdivision of land,'' Fay wrote.
``Because this parking area was not subject to subdivision
requirements before its conversion, it cannot be subject to these
requirements afterward.''
   McConnell said Tuesday that while the legal fees may drive the
price up beyond $10,000, he expects no difficulty in selling the
spaces.
   ``The demand is there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880621-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Kuwait     06-21 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Kuwait,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Voice Concern Over Proposed Arms Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty senators have told the Reagan
administration they are concerned that a proposed sale of
sophisticated U.S. fighters, missiles and munitions to Kuwait may
pose a threat to Israel and would further fuel the Middle East arms
race.
   In a letter to Secretary of State George P. Shultz, the senators
questioned the reasoning behind the sale decision, asking whether
Kuwait has agreed to give more active protection to its own
shipping in the Persian Gulf.
   The letter was sent to Shultz on Friday and was made public
Tuesday.
   The arms sale package includes 40 F@A-18 Hornet fighter
aircraft, 40 Harpoon missiles, 120 Sidewinder missiles, 300
Maverick missiles, 200 Sparrow missiles, 400 laser-guided bombs and
200 cluster bombs.
   The senators said they are concerned that the combat-range of
the Hornet could be extended to permit attacks on Israel by basing
it in Saudi Arabia, Jordan or Iraq or by adding larger fuel tanks.
   ``Accordingly, we conclude that it is critically important to
have the assurances of Kuwait that these aircraft will never be
based or deployed closer to Israel than they would be at their base
in Kuwait and that they never will be based in or based to a state
bordering Israel,'' the senators said.
   They asked for assurances that Kuwait will not seek and the U.S.
government will not sell equipment to extend the range of the
planes.
   Additionally, they said they are concerned that the highly
accurate and reliable Maverick missile might ``fall into unfriendly
hands.''
   ``The Maverick has destructive capabilities that far exceed the
legitimate security requirements of Kuwait,'' the senators said and
added: ``We cannot afford to have our most sophisticated, sensitive
and efficient weapons sold without predictable and desirable
consequences.''
   The letter was signed by Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman
of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, and these other senators:
   Sens. Dennis De Concini, D-Ariz; Frank R. Lautenberg, D-N.J.;
Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn.; Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii; Paul Sarbanes,
D-Md.; Bob Packwood, R-Ore.; Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.;
Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.; Pete Wilson, R-Calif.; John Kerry,
D-Mass.
   Also, Sens Paul Simon, D-Ill.; Brock Adams, D-Wash.; Howard W.
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio; Terry Sanford, D-N.C.; Alfonse M. D'Amato,
R-N.Y.; Donald W. Riegle, D-Mich.; Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M.; Quentin
N. Burdick, D-N.D.; and Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880621-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2021EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NOW-Jackson     06-21 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NOW-Jackson,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NOW to Call for Jackson or `Non-White' Woman as Democratic No. 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Organization for Women plans
to urge likely Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis to select rival
Jesse Jackson or a ``non-white'' woman as his running mate, the
group's president said Tuesday.
   Molly Yard said it would take the selection of Jackson, who is
very sensitive to women's issues, or ``a woman from Jackson's
constituency'' to smooth relations between the women's movement and
the Democratic Party.
   ``The whole stance of the party since 1984 has been to blame us
for the defeat of Mondale and Ferraro,'' she said.
   NOW, the nation's largest women's rights organization, has been
a major influence in Democratic politics and was a factor in the
selection of Geraldine Ferraro as Walter Mondale's running mate in
the 1984 presidential race. The ticket later was defeated by the
largest margin in the history of U.S. presidential races.
   Ms. Yard said the group plans to introduce a resolution calling
on Dukakis to heed their advice on the vice presidential choice.
The NOW president did not provide a date for the resolution, but
the group is holding its national conference in Buffalo this week.
   Dukakis is currently considering potential running mates.
Jackson, runner-up to the Massachusetts governor in the delegate
race, has said he has earned the right to be offered the No. 2
spot, but Dukakis has not made any commitment.
   Yard also charged that Democratic leaders have tried to keep NOW
out of the 1988 election.
   ``They say they don't want the party captive to special
interests,'' she said. ``I don't know how they can call the
nation's largest group of voters a special interest.''
   There are 10 million more women registered to vote than men, she
said.
   The NOW president also said the Democratic Party could lose the
women's vote and the 1988 presidential election if it doesn't pay
more attention to women's issues.
   Yard warned that millions of women would vote Republican if the
GOP is perceived as caring more than the Democrats about women.
   ``Even though their platform is a disaster, they'll get votes
because they're seriously considering a woman as a vice
presidential candidate,'' Yard said of the Republicans.
   ``Everything depends on who you showcase at the convention,''
she said.
   Elizabeth Dole, the former transportation secretary, is
considered a candidate for the No. 2 spot on the GOP ticket that
will be headed by all-but-certain nominee George Bush.
   Selection of Mrs. Dole as a running mate could hand Bush the
presidency, Yard said. Mrs. Dole is the wife of Kansas Sen. Bob
Dole who battled Bush unsuccessfully for the GOP presidential
nomination.
   NOW calculates that Dukakis's apparent early lead over Bush
could disappear if he loses a significant portion of the women's
vote. National polls indicate Bush is running significantly behind
Dukakis among women while running about even among men.
   ``It's not the time for the Democrats to send signals that they
will in any way deny the importance of women's issues,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
