<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DoctorBills     06-21 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doctor Bills,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Professor Finishing Work On Medical Fees Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Harvard professor nearing completion of a
report on the relative financial value of work done by different
types of doctors said Tuesday he believes his approach ultimately
will be embraced, though not loved, by the medical profession.
   ``Within the medical community ... there is a strong perception
that the fee structure is totally out of kilter,'' William C. Hsiao
told reporters.
   However, he acknowledged that a revised fee schedule based on
the relative value scale his team is finalizing will hold out the
prospect of ``winners and losers'' in the economic arena and thus
will be controversial among doctors.
   On the other hand, he expressed confidence that the medical
community as a whole accepts the premise that something must be
done to temper doctor bills rising at about 15 percent a year.
   And because Hsiao's Harvard team worked closely with the
American Medical Association and panels of physician advisers from
the various specialities, he said he belives the plan ultimately
will be accepted by doctors as preferable to potential alternatives
over which they have no control.
   Moreover, Hsiao continued, the fact that there are likely to be
many more ``winners'' than ``losers'' among the nation's 500,000
doctors suggests another pragmatic reason to predict ultimate
acceptance of the plan.
   The 1,000-page report flowing from the 2-year, $2.5 million
study is due at the Health Care Financing Administration _ which
oversees Medicare and Medicaid _ by July 31 and is to be made
public by the end of August.
   Hsiao said he did not expect it to have an immediate impact, but
predicted Congress will start hearings on it next spring and
probably will use the document in making budget decisions for
fiscal 1990.
   The project has generated keen interest within the medical
community because it raises the specter of massive changes in the
way doctors bill their patients.
   Hsiao declined to go into details of the report, but gave one
example of what he called an ``irrational price structure existing
in the physician market.''
   The present structure gives an incentive for doctors to perform
a $300, 30-minute procedure to detect ulcers by inserting a tube
down a patients throat while a complete physicial examination
taking about 45 minutes could accomplish the same degree of
diagnostic accuracy. The catch: the doctor could charge only about
$75 for such a ``non-invasive'' examination.
   The most obvious result of the report, financed mostly with
federal money, would be changes in the amount Medicare will pay for
each of the 7,000 different medical procedures assigned a numerical
code.
   However, private insurance companies use the same code system
and Hsiao said several of them have expressed interest in using
information from the forthcoming report to do pilot studies of the
way they pay bills.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
