<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabyKidnapped     06-21 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Kidnapped,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Begs For Return of Infant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE HOBBS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sobbing mother pleaded Tuesday for the
return of her son, who she said was abducted from her hospital room
as she fed him the day after he was born.
   ``I would just like to beg to whoever took my baby to just bring
him back to us,'' Renee McClure of Lexington said during a brief
appearance at a news conference at High Point Regional Hospital.
   The child was taken Monday from his mother's arms by a woman who
said she needed to weigh the baby, the mother and officials said.
Jason Ray McClure was born to Richard and Renee McClure at 12:22
a.m. Sunday.
   He was the first Father's Day baby born at the hospital, and
television station WGHP in High Point broadcast a special segment
on him Sunday night.
   Hospital officials said guards have been added to the maternity
floor during all four scheduled daily feedings.
   ``We know the Lord would want you to do the right thing and
bring him back to us,'' the mother said. ``I beg you, please, bring
our son back to me and all will be forgiven and forgotten and God
will forgive you, I'm sure.''
   ``We love our son,'' she said.
   ``The woman that took him, I can understand if you lost a child
because almost lost Jason twice. I about miscarried him two times
and we worked real hard to get him here,'' Mrs. McClure said.
   As she was wheeled out of the news conference by her husband,
Mrs. McClure broke into tears.
   ``Everybody is trying to stick together and hold tight pretty
good,'' said McClure's brother, Randy. ``It's a big shock to
everybody.''
   Mrs. McClure did not answer questions. FBI agent Dan Wozniak
said she was ``going through a really difficult time. The most
important thing is getting this baby back.''
   He said authorities have many leads and ``many people working
around the clock.''
   During a feeding time Monday morning, a woman dressed in a white
uniform but without a hospital badge, came into Mrs. McClure's room
in the postpartum unit and said she was going to weigh the child,
hospital officials said.
   She carried Jason away.
   Five to 10 minutes later, a nursing assistant making her rounds
noticed that the baby's bassinet was empty. After the mother said
what happened, hospital officials immediately contacted the police
and all exits from the hospital were blocked.
   It is hospital policy to have nurses transport newborn babies
from the nursery to the mother in a bassinet. Hospital officials
said it would appear strange if someone carried a baby.
   ``This person was not someone known to the hospital,'' said
hospital Vice President Page Redpath.
</TEXT>
