<HEAD>Heat Contributes To Ear-Splitting Jet Noise Near O'Hare</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Drought-Heat Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Record-setting temperatures have added to the
ear-splitting noise that afflicts residents of some suburbs near
O'Hare International Airport.
   ``The hot, dry air is holding the noise closer to the ground,''
said Roddy Coker, supervisor at the Federal Aviation Administration
control tower at O'Hare. ``And in hot weather, airplanes don't
climb as fast as they do in cold weather. That's just a fact.''
   Residents in Des Plaines, Park Ridge and Bloomingdale have been
flooding the office of the O'Hare Citizen's Coalition with
complaints about jet noise, said Director Matthew Rosenberg.
   ``People are at their wits end,'' Rosenberg said Monday. ``It
was bad enough before, but it's worse now.''
   The temperature hit 97 at O'Hare on Tuesday, breaking the record
for June 21 of 95 degrees set in 1968. On Monday, the temperature
at O'Hare hit 104 _ 1 degree short of the highest temperature in
Chicago since the weather service began keeping records.
   O'Hare authorities also said that because one runway at the
airport is closed for resurfacing, more planes have been using a
runway that heads toward the suburbs.
