<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The advisers to a black teen-ager who said she
was assaulted by six white men last fall denied Tuesday a claim
that one adviser hired someone to tape his conversations with the
other two.
   Samuel McClease, who said he was hired by the Rev. Al Sharpton
to bug lawyer C. Vernon Mason, said his tapes showed that the
advisers didn't believe the story told by teen-ager, Tawana
Brawley, but that the three were using her case for personal gain.
   Mason, Sharpton and lawyer Alton Maddox asserted during a
two-hour interview Tuesday that McClease was lying and that he did
not have the ability to carry out a secret electronic surveillance.
   On the other hand, they said McClease was forced by some law
enforcement organization to plant the bugs to make Sharpton look
bad and destroy the unity of the Brawley advisers.
   They accused WCBS television, which broke the bugging story
Monday, of ``corruption and racism'' for not checking McClease's
credibility before putting him on the air.
   The three men made their allegations on WLIB radio. They would
not talk to reporters afterward.
   No tape of the purported bugging was broadcast by WCBS during
its interview with McClease. Asked whether it had such tape, the
station issued a statement that said: ``We're confident that the
tapes exist and that the story will continue to unfold.''
   Miss Brawley, 16, of Wappingers Falls, and her family have
refused to cooperate with the grand jury, which state Attorney
General Robert Abrams said has been stymied in trying to learn what
happened during the four days last November when Miss Brawley said
she was kidnapped and raped by six white men, one of whom had a
badge.
   The three advisers contend the investigation has fallen prey to
racism, and say black people cannot get justice in New York state.
The teen-ager's mother has been in a church since last week, when
she sought refuge to avoid arrest for contempt for refusing to
cooperate with the grand jury.
