<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Explosives     06-21 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Explosives,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Arrested; Explosives-Filled Car Driven Aboard Ferry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab man accused of driving a car
containing explosives aboard an Israeli-bound ferry will appear in
court Wednesday on illegal arms possession charges, the government
announced.
   A Merchant Marine Ministry statement issued Tuesday identified
the suspect as Omar Mohammed Sofrini and said he carried a West
German passport.
   It said a car allegedly driven by Sofrini aboard the ferry
Paloma in the Athens' port of Piraeus contained a revolver equipped
with a silencer, 101 bullets, 19 bottles packed with explosives and
detonators.
   Sofrini is being held in Piraeus pending his court appearance,
according to the statement.
   The explosives were discovered by port authorities and Israeli
security officials on Monday shortly before the 3,895-ton Paloma
was to set sail with 400 passengers and 100 crew members. Also on
the Cyriot-registered ship were about 200 cars, Piraeus officials
reported.
   They said the vessel departed Monday, about four hours later,
for the voyage to the islands of Rhodes and Cyprus and then to
Haifa, Israel.
   The ministry statement said Sofrini arrived in Greece June 18
after driving the car from West Germany through Austria and
Yugoslavia.
   Ilias Trochidis, owner of the ferry company Afroessa Lines, told
The Associated Press by telephone that Sofrini, about 30 years old,
was asleep in his cabin when the explosives were found.
   ``He said he'd just bought the car and didn't know anything
about the explosives,'' Trochidis said.
   An Afroessa Lines official said the Paloma ``had Israelis, a few
Americans, quite a number of British, some Greeks, Greek Cypriots
and Scandinavians aboard.'' About 100 passengers were traveling to
Haifa, the official said, but he did not know where Sofrini had
planned to disembark.
   The Paloma makes weekly journeys between Piraeus and Haifa.
Piraeus port authority officials and Israeli security agents
routinely search the vessel.
   Trochidis said the explosives were found in the car's wheel
wells.
   It was the second arrest in Greece this month of a terrorist
suspect.
   On June 1, a Palestinian identified as Mohammed Rashid was
picked up at the Athens airport by police who said they had
received information from the U.S. Embassy.
   The United States has asked for Rashid's extradition, accusing
him of involvement in a 1982 bombing aboard a Pan American World
Airways jetliner over Honolulu that killed one person and injured
15 people.
   Rashid also is suspected of being connected with a 1986
explosion on a Trans World Airlines jet over Greece that killed
four people.
</TEXT>
