<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Palestinians,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Says Authoritative PLO Statement Needed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestine Liberation Organization official's
ideas about peacefully settling disputes with Israel contain ``a
constructive tone'' and ``some positive points,'' but lack
authoritative backing from the PLO leadership, the State Department
said Tuesday.
   Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley was commenting on a paper
circulated to journalists at the Arab summit meeting earlier this
month in Algiers and attributed to Bassam Abu Sharif, PLO chief
Yasser Arafat's Tunis-based adviser.
   The summit announced financial support for the current uprising
by Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied territories, while Abu
Sharif's material talked of Israelis and Palestinians living side
by side in peace and cooperation.
   It suggested direct peace talks and an internationally
supervised referendum on the West Bank and Gaza Strip to establish
whether the PLO should represent Palestinians.
   Assistant Secretary of State Richard Murphy, told a news
conference in Saudi Arabia last weekend that the paper lacked the
``strident rhetoric'' of other Palestinian statements and
represented a ``contribution to a rational discussion'' of the
Middle East problem.
   He also noted that no Israeli ``would sit down with the PLO in
the present conditions'' of that organization's non-recognition of
Israel.
   Asked to comment, Mrs. Oakley said the big question is how
authoritative is the Algiers statement. ``Does it represent
official PLO policy?'' she asked, then added:
   ``We note the constructive tone which the article conveys in
general, as well as some positive points. If the PLO is serious
about moderating its position so as to make a practical condition
to the peace process, it can do so in an authoritative way. We have
yet to see such an authoritative statement.''
