<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-21 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Record Heat, Thunderstorms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Record heat continued Tuesday across the Plains and Midwest
today, with record highs in dozens of cities from the Dakotas to
the East Coast. Thunderstorms cropped up around the Great Lakes and
the Gulf Coast.
   Early afternoon temperatures were higher than at the same Monday
over much of the Dakotas, Nebraska, Iowa, Illinois, Indiana and
eastward to the middle Atlantic states.
   It was only the third time that Milwaukee reached 100 degrees
during the past 33 years. The temperature at Rochester, Minn.,
reached 90 degrees for the seventh time this year, and rose to 97;
in a normal year, 90 is reached only six times.
   At Rockford, Ill., the temperature reached 100 degrees for the
second day in a row, the first time that had happened since 1947.
   The Great Lakes region will receive at least some relief from
the heat during the next few days after a cold front moves slowly
south and reaches the Chicago area late Wednesday, with some
thunderstorms breaking out ahead of the front.
   Thunderstorms developed Tuesday across parts of Michigan,
Wisconsin and Minnesota.
   Thunderstorms also popped up over sections of Florida, the Gulf
coastal states and coastal Texas.
   More thunderstorms developed over sections of the central and
southern Appalachians and over parts of the Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 107 at both Hill City, Kan.,
and Tucson, Ariz. The low for the day was 42 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo., and Truckee, Calif.
   For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from northern New England across New York and the Great Lakes
region to Iowa and northern Missouri. Showers and thunderstorms
also were forecast from the southern Atlantic states and Florida
across the Gulf Coast states to southern Texas. Widely scattered
afternoon thunderstorms were forecast across sections of eastern
California to sections of the Rockies.
   Highs only in the 60s and 70s were predicted along the Pacific
Coast; in the 70s and 80s from northern Michigan across Minnesota
to North Dakota, and over the Pacific Northwest; in the 80s from
southeastern Louisiana to Florida, and over much of New England and
New York state; between 100 and 110 over Kansas, sections of
southwestern Idaho and the desert Southwest; and in the 90s to near
100 over most of the nation.
</TEXT>
