<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Debt     06-21 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Debt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Leaders Agree to Help Poorest Countries</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World leaders agreed Tuesday to do more to lift
the tremendous foreign debt burdens shouldered by the poorest
countries but made no new effort to help the giant debtors of Latin
America.
   In their final communique, the seven leaders attending the
annual economic summit of industrialized nations backed a plan
offering a variety of options, including slashing interest rates
and forgiving some loans, to ease the debt load of mostly poor
countries in sub-Saharan Africa.
   French Finance Minister Pierre Beregovoy said the fresh move
offers ``a message of hope to the poorest countries.''
   ``I think it's very important news for countries in a very
difficult position,'' he told reporters.
   But the leaders said the debt problems of the so-called
``middle-income'' countries, like Brazil and Mexico, should be
handled on a ``case-by-case'' basis, a strategy fashioned in recent
years to deal individually with these debtors.
   The leaders acknowledged that the big debtors ``continue to have
difficulties servicing their external debt and generating the
investment necessary for sustainable growth.''
   But they said, ``The market-oriented, growth-led strategy based
on the case-by-case approach remains the only viable approach for
overcoming their external debt problems.''
   Brazil and Mexico, the developing world's largest debtors, have
foreign debts totaling a combined $220 billion.
   The 44 countries that make up sub-Saharan Africa rang up debts
of about $120 billion at the end of 1987, according to the
International Monetary Fund.
   The total foreign debt of the developing world is estimated at
approximately $1 trillion.
   Allen Sinai, chief economist at the Boston Co., said the
leaders' action ``looks like really more of the same.'' ``It's a
constructive window-dressing statement on what is a totally
intractable situation,'' he said.
   ``There is no way at any summit that what in reality remains an
albatross around the world's neck can be resolved,'' he said.
   Sally Shelton-Colby, an international financial consultant in
Washington, D.C., said the she doubted the new African plan would
have ``any appreciable effect'' on the debt problem.
   ``It's a step in the right direction,'' she said, ``but I don't
think the importance of it should be exaggerated.''
   She was skeptical that the Reagan administration in its seven
remaining months in office would take advantage of the new program.
   ``I can't imagine the Reagan administration granting meaningful
debt relief to the poorest of the poor countries,'' she said.
   ``It's not a high priority,'' she said.
   The Reagan administration backed off from its previous refusal
to go along with debt concessions, enabling the summit leaders to
adopt the fresh measures.
   The plan for the poorest debtors calls for the creditor
countries to reschedule the ``official debt of these countries
within a framework of comparability,'' the leaders' statement said.
   The governments, it said, would have several options for easing
the debt burdens.
   They include reducing interest rates on shorter-term loans,
extending repayment periods at higher, market interest rates,
partially writing off loans, or a combination of these options.
   ``This approach allows official creditors to choose options
consistent with their legal or budgetary constraints,'' the
statement said.
   The United States has said it cannot legally write off loans or
grant concessionary interest rates, but can extend interest
repayment periods.
   The program would apply only to official or government debt and
not to loans incurred from commercial banks.
   Beregovoy said that to qualify for the relief package, a country
must have a very low per-capita income and be following economic
policies approved by the International Monetary Fund.
   Moreover, a country's annual debt payments must eat up 30
percent of its earnings from export sales.
   Beregovoy estimated that 30 countries, mostly in sub-Saharan
Africa but a few in Asia, would qualify.
   He estimated that roughly $10 billion to $15 billion of the
countries' total debts would fall under the program.
   The total cost to France, he said, would be about $130 million
year.
   Details of the plan are to be worked out by the end of the year
by the Paris Club, a group of 17 Western creditor countries which
renegotiates debt owed them.
   Prior to the summit, French President Francois Mitterrand and
Nigel Lawson, Britain's top financial officer, urged relief for
these countries.
   Japan's finance minister, Kiichi Miyazawa, offered a complicated
plan to help the bigger debtor countries but no action was taken on
that.
   Several officials complained of not having enough time to study
the Japanese proposal, which calls for the debtors to deposit some
of their international reserves with the International Monetary
Fund.
   The plan, while not accepted at the summit, will certainly
prompt more discussion at later meetings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
