<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp     06-21 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warplanes Attack Positions On Front; Iranian Rebels Hold Mehran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq said they launched air
attacks on each other's battlefield positions Tuesday, while
Iranian rebels fought to hang on to a shattered border town they
took over the weekend.
   The Iraq-based rebels, known as the National Liberation Army,
said they killed or wounded 8,000 Iranian soldiers in Sunday's
battle for Mehran, 100 miles east of the Iraqi capital, Baghdad.
They said several women were among 57 of their fighters who died.
   A rebel communique said women were on the front lines, where
they were deployed as mortar crews giving cover fire for advancing
troops. The communique was sent by telex to The Associated Press in
Nicosia.
   The communique said rebel forces on Tuesday held foohills north
and south of Mehran and the highway to Dehloran, 75 miles to the
south in Iran.
   Iran, which has said Iraqi forces took Mehran, said its air
force flew eight sorties against Iraqi positions around the town.
   The bombing and artillery duels killed enemy soldiers, destroyed
vehicles and set fortifications on fire, the Islamic Republic News
Agency said in a war communique monitored in Nicosia.
   Iraq and the rebels deny any Iraqi troops took part.
   The Iranian air force also made four bombing runs against Iraqi
positions in northern Sulimaniyeh province, IRNA said. The news
agency also reported fighting on the ground between Iraqi troops
and Kurds opposed to the Baghdad government fighting next to
Iranian soldiers. The two sides have been battling for mountain
peaks in the region.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said that during fighting in the
north, its ground forces shot down an Iranian F-5 Tuesday morning.
Iran had no immediate comment.
   Iraq said its air force flew 313 combat missions Tuesday and
lost no aircraft. INA said the total included 84 combat missions by
jet fighters and 229 by helicopter gunships.
   The continued high total in gunship missions indicates the two
sides are locked in heavy ground fighting, as Iraq uses helicopters
to counter Iranian force on the ground.
   The National Liberation Army's hold on Mehran since Sunday is
the longest time the rebel force has spent inside Iran since it
formed a year ago. Its previous pattern has been to inflict as much
damage as possible and withdraw. The group has said it does not
intend to keep its fighters around Mehran.
   Iran and Iraq, locked in a nearly 8-year-old war, have each
captured and lost Mehran several times.
   The Iranian casualties claimed by the rebels could not be
independently confirmed. But reporters saw more than 1,500 Iranian
prisoners brought across the border to Badrah on Monday.
   The rebels did not say how many fighters were committed to the
battle for Mehran, but the assault force involved an estimated
several thousand men and women along a 30-mile front.
   In the northern Persian Gulf, shipping executives said a U.S.
and a French warship rushed to help a small boat that put out a
distress signal late Tuesday in the same area where Iran attacked
two commercial vessels two weeks ago.
   The executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it was
later learned the boat was simply taking water in the engine room.
They identified it as the Nada and said its Greek crew of six
radioed they were abandoning the vessel in life rafts near the
Saudi Arabian oil terminal of Ras Tanura.
   The executives said they did not know which U.S. and French
warships were involved. The U.S. Navy recently has said it would
help neutral vessels, regardless of which flag they fly, if
attacked in the vicinity of a U.S. warship.
   Iran attacks neutral shipping in retaliation for Iraqi attacks
on Iranian-chartered vessels.
</TEXT>
