<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-FarmSubsidies     06-21 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Farm Subsidies,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit Fails to Make Sweeping Changes on Farm Subsidies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders at the economic summit on Tuesday
rejected President Reagan's plan to reform bloated farm subsidy
programs after European and Japanese leaders refused to make
sweeping promises on cutting the support payments.
   The farm issue proved the most divisive of the generally
harmonious three-day summit. Even Britain, the most reform-minded
of the West European nations, dismissed the Reagan plan as
``totally unrealistic.''
   The president, attending his final summit session, appeared
undaunted even though his colleagues had spurned his plea for
change.
   Reagan acknowledged that ``there are some differences of
opinion'' on the subsidies question, but added, ``I am not going to
give up on that.''
   The final communique issued Tuesday fell well short of the
signal for urgent action some U.S. officials had hoped to send to
the crucial General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) talks in
December in Montreal.
   The summit leaders effectively ignored the Reagan proposal,
which called for the elimination of all farm subsidies by the year
2000. Instead, the communique said the countries should work simply
for a reduction of the support payments to farmers.
   Many officials agree that the payments pose a problem, since
they drain national treasuries of nearly $200 billion a year,
encourage huge surpluses and harm the trade prospects of
agriculture-dependent Third World economies.
   But many also contend that drastic reform of the system would be
politically untenable.
   The communique said the leaders supported both the ``framework''
approach of trying to find an overall solution, favored by the
Americans, and also the short-term measures which Britain, France,
West Germany, Italy and Japan feel are the most that can be
achieved. Canada, the host, had sought a compromise.
   ``The mid-term review will provide a unique opportunity to send
a credible political signal to the trading world,'' said the
communique.
   ``We suport efforts to adopt a framework approach, including
short as well as long term elements which will promote the reform
process ... and relieve current strains in the agricultural
markets,'' the communique said.
   At their final meeting Tuesday morning, the seven leaders
slightly strengthened the vague language on farm subsidies. The
communique said the trade negotiators ``must'' _ as opposed to
``should'' in the draft communique composed by officials _ take
both short-term options and long-term goals.
   But the leaders, in a communique-approving session that ran an
hour over the scheduled two hours, also included another escape
clause by drawing attention to ``the diversity of our agricultural
situations.''
   Britain, for example, has few farmers, most of whom are
efficient and wealthy. West Germany and France have electorally
important lobbies of smalltime farmers who depend heavily on
subsidies.
   The communique also said subsidy cutbacks must take account of
``social concerns.''
   According to figures produced by the 24-nation Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development, Japan has the most heavily
subsidized system, offering a 75 percent subsidy for its
agriculture in 1986, up from 54 percent in 1980.
   European Economic Community subsidies totaled 49 percent in
1986, up from 36 percent in 1980, and U.S. subsidies were 35
percent, up from 15 percent.
   The EEC, to which the four European nations at the summit
belong, agreed to far-reaching measures last spring designed to
impose permanent curbs on production through automatic subsidy
cutoff when farmers exceed quotas.
   But officials note the agreement will only slow down increases
in subsidies, rather than impose an immediate freeze.
   ``It is the right of everyone to have expectations, even great
expectations, but it is not very productive to be dreaming without
reality,'' Willy de Clerq, the EEC foreign affairs commissioner,
said of the deadlock.
</TEXT>
