<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TipSheets     06-21 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tip Sheets,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Ruling May Force Disclosure Of Financial Inducements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investment tip sheets can be forced to tell
readers that they were given financial inducements by a company to
print an article touting the firm's stock, a federal appeals court
ruled Thursday.
   But the court rejected the Securities and Exchange Commission's
contention such publications must tell readers that a featured
company provided the article or paid the writer who composed it.
   Deciding whether the text of a particular article was
``substantially provided'' by the company would be an intrusion in
the editorial process that is prohibited by the First Amendment,
the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled.
   The court, however, revived a lawsuit by the SEC to force Stock
Market Magazine to tell readers if feature articles about companies
were carried as a result of other financial inducements.
   These arrangements could include a company's agreement to buy
advertising in the publication or purchase reprints of the feature
article, the court said in an opinion by Circuit Judge Laurence
Silberman.
   The SEC had sought the injunction to enforce the anti-touting
provisions of the 1933 Securities Act, which were designed to
prohibit publication of investment tips under the guise of
journalism by people with a financial interest in a stock's value.
   The case was sent back to U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson
Jr., who had thrown out the SEC's suit First Amendment grounds, to
determine if the existence of such ``quid pro quo'' financial
arrangements warranted an injuction against the monthly magazine.
   ``If they did exist, we have no doubt that an injunction could
be fashioned to require disclosure when consideration is paid in
this distinct form, without trameling fully protected speech or
interfering with editorial practices,'' Silberman wrote in an
opinion joined by Circuit Judge Douglas H. Ginsburg. Judge Carl
McGowan, the panel's third member who had concurred in the opinion,
died last December.
   ``Requiring disclosure of such payments would not interfere with
either editorial judgments concerning the content of the feature
articles or news gathering practices,'' Silberman said.
   But the court said such interference would occur if the SEC
sought to require disclosure that the article was planted by the
company either by providing a free copy of the text or paying a
free-lance journalist to write it.
   That ``would result in both the SEC and court interference with
the `crucial process' of editorial control, interference that the
Supreme Court has decried as particularly repugnant to core First
Amendment concerns,'' Silberman wrote.
   The magazine's attorney, Joseph H. Sharlitt said his client's
``First Amendment position has been vindicated.''
   But Sharlitt said the court's decision ``gives the SEC the right
to look at the financial records of the financial press and compare
that with the content of its articles and make a determination
whether there has been some sort of tie-in deal.''
   Under this decision, the SEC could enjoin publication of a
magazine on the basis of one article that was printed as a result
of a financial inducement, he said.
   Sharlitt denied the SEC's allegations that Stock Market Magazine
received financial inducements to print the articles.
   He said he was unsure whether the magazine had legal standing to
appeal the decision because the SEC had not obtained an injunction
against it.
   Richard Kirby, the SEC's assistant general counsel, said the
decision was ``significant in the respect we can clearly now
enforce the statute in certain important respects.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
