<DOCNO> AP880621-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1940EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Mitterrand     06-21 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Mitterrand,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Says U.S. Wants Summit Seven To Decide For Rest of
World</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is trying to transform the
annual summit of Western industrialized countries into a permanent
body that would try to run the world, President Francois Mitterrand
of France said Tuesday.
   Mitterrand, who clashed repeatedly with President Reagan during
the three-day meeting, said he objected to a plan for an
international seven-nation drug task force because he considered it
the latest American attempt to establish a new organization.
   ``In whose name do these seven countries decide for the rest of
the world?'' asked Mitterrand, who was re-elected last month to a
second seven-year term.
   Speaking to reporters, he criticized what he called ``the
tendency or strategy of the United States to transform this summit
into a permanent institution, leaving each time organizations which
would continue from one year to another. This I refuse.''
   Ultimately, France abstained on a paragraph of Monday's
political declaration which welcomed the U.S. proposal for a drug
task force, but without specifying what countries might be members.
   Mitterrand said his confrontations with Reagan on this and other
issues _ farm subsidies and aid to the Philippines _ ``did not
exceed reasonable bounds.''
   The dispute over whether to single out the Philippines as a
fragile democracy deserving financial support came Tuesday morning
at the summit's final session, delaying its conclusion by about an
hour.
   Mitterrand said many other countries were in much the same
position of the Philippines, which was only singled out for U.S.
strategic and political reasons.
   ``I spoke of Argentina,'' Mitterrand said, noting that there,
too, a government was threatened after replacing a dictatorship and
was suffering under an economic burden that could menace the
survival of democracy.
   Mitterrand, who will be the host of next year's summit meeting,
said French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas suggested the compromise
that was adopted, noting that countries in Africa, Asia and Latin
America deserved help to preserve democracy, but naming only the
Philippines.
   On farm subsidies, where Reagan failed to win support for their
elimination in the next decade, Mitterrand said it was not a
France-U.S. confrontation because several European countries joined
him in opposition.
   Mitterrand, the only Socialist in a group of otherwise
conservative national leaders at the summit, said he had spoken up
to note that his peers who praised effusively the unfettered free
market were also pleased that international cooperation had
``limited the effects of this false liberty'' after the October
market crash.
   ``There's a little contradiction between the hymn to free-market
doctrine and what has just happened,'' he said.
   Mitterrand, 71, has attended the last eight summits, just as
Reagan has. But while Reagan prepares to retire, Mitterrand's new
term runs until 1995.
   The French president said he had no objection to the warm praise
for Reagan offered by Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney at the
end of the summit.
   ``For someone who played a great role in contemporary history,
it's normal to salute him and wish that his retirement be happy and
long. It's a courtesy,'' Mitterrand said. ``It has nothing to do, I
suppose, with politics.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
