<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     06-21 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Writers' Group Urges End To Strike; Other Unions Picket
Guild</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prominent members of the Writers
Guild of America broke with the union leadership Tuesday and urged
approval of the latest offer from producers to settle the 16-week
scriptwriters strike.
   Meanwhile, about 40 members of various craft unions picketed
briefly in front of the Writers Guild headquarters in West
Hollywood to call for an end to the strike, which they said was
threatening their jobs.
   Dissident members of the Writers Guild told a news conference
they were not anti-union in urging members to endorse the latest
offer at meetings in New York and Los Angeles Wednesday. They said
they were just trying to save jobs.
   ``We have a responsibility to the greater (entertainment)
community to end the strike,'' said Bruce Paltrow, one of the
creators of the recently canceled ``St. Elsewhere'' series.
   ``This is a decent contract offer, a vast improvement over what
we had, and certainly more than we expected to get,'' said Peter
Hyams, who has written or directed such films as ``Outland,''
``2010,'' and ``The Presidio.''
   The guild responded with a statement of support from other
notable members, including writer-producers Michael Mann, Lawrence
Kasdan, Richard Brooks, Billy Wilder and Norman Lear.
   ``We are opposed to any action that would divide and weaken the
guild at this difficult time,'' the statement said.
   Guild Executive Director Brian Walton said the dissidents'
attack was ``a well orchestrated press campaign'' aimed at
crippling the 9,500-member guild.
   The guild's negotiating committee and East and West Coast boards
last week recommended that members reject the producers' $71
million contract offer. They said the economic package on foreign
and one-hour residuals, or reruns, was unacceptable.
   Several of the industry's top ``hyphenates'' _ writer-producers
who hold union cards but also have become management by starting
their own production companies _ are among the dissidents.
   They include ``L.A. Law'' producer-writer Steve Bochco; Stephen
Cannell, who produces ``Hunter''; John Hughes, producer and writer
of such films as ``The Great Outdoors'' and ``Planes, Trains and
Automobiles;'' and ``Red Dawn'' writer John Milius.
   Hyams said the producers' current offer of a 14.7 percent
minimum increase for residuals was a victory for the union.
   Bochco said continuation of the strike would affect thousands of
jobs as production dates for the upcoming television season loom
during the next two weeks.
   ``The day is late and we are beginning to look at the calendar.
... If we begin to reduce the number of episodes we can make in a
season, that's when you begin to see tremendous economic loss _
irretrievable loss,'' Bochco said.
   All of the more than 20 writers who attended the news conference
insisted their personal interests were not at stake. Independent
writers who are trying to sell their scripts and have no other jobs
in the industry would be most harmed by a prolonged strike, they
said.
   Cannell, who belongs to both the guild and management's Alliance
of Motion Picture and Television Producers, cited the recent drop
in syndication sales of one-hour TV shows and said both sides must
realize ``this business is in fact in desperate trouble.''
   About 300 members of the dissenting Writers Coalition met Monday
night and agreed to back the producers' offer.
   The coalition claims about 600 members, which it claims are
among the guild's most frequently employed members, and therefore
the biggest contributors to its health, welfare and pension fund.
</TEXT>
