<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Callaghan     06-21 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Callaghan,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Callaghan Suffers Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister James Callaghan, now Lord
Callaghan, suffered a mild heart attack and was admitted to a
hospital Tuesday.
   Callaghan, 76, entered St. Thomas' Hospital in London for tests
after complaining of feeling unwell, the hospital said.
   It released no further information but Callaghan's former
parliamentary secretary, Roger Stott, said Callaghan ``suffered a
mild heart attack.''
   Stott said doctors at the hospital ``are hoping he may be out by
the end of the week, although he will have to take things very
easily.''
   Callaghan, a Labor Party leader and prime minister from
1976-979, had to cancel plans to attend an annual conference of
former heads of state or government in Colorado, said his daughter,
Margaret Jay.
   ``As I understand it, there is nothing to be alarmed about,''
she said. ``He seems very cheerful.''
   Callaghan succeeded Harold Wilson as prime minister and lost
power in 1979 to the Conservative Party under Margaret Thatcher.
   He is a member of the House of Lords, the unelected upper
chamber of Parliament.
</TEXT>
