<DOCNO> AP880621-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Grosz     06-21 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Grosz,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grosz Warns Against Challenging System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz said
Tuesday he expects Hungary's new leadership to be tested but he
warned against challenging the system.
   In a speech to the National Council of Trade Unions, Grosz spoke
about demonstrations, including one last Thursday commemorating the
30th anniversary of the execution of Imre Nagy, a leader of the
1956 revolt that was crushed by Soviet forces.
   According to witnesses, police broke up a demonstration by about
400 people who called for Nagy's official rehabilitation. Officals
said 15 people were detained for several hours.
   Grosz said ``hostile and opposition elements'' are exploiting
current debates in Hungary over how far to go in implementing
political reform.
   Grosz was chosen at the Communist Party conference last month to
replace Janos Kadar, who led Hungary for 32 years.
   Referring to the conference, Grosz said the new party leadership
is ``more sound politically, intellectually and organizationally.''
His comments were carried by the MTI news agency.
   It quoted him as saying the leadership respects ``everybody's
personal feelings'' but said he added: ``We firmly reject all kinds
of movement against the system ... and demonstrations against the
representatives of power.''
   The party's revamped Central Committee is to meet Thursday to
discuss greater opennesss in party affairs and economic change.
   Grosz indirectly criticized Kadar. MTI reported he said, ``We
want to rid our socialist system of the impediments it has had to
carry because of errors made by individuals.''
   He said one of the errors ``over the past 15 years is that we
did not accept political inconveniences and tried to evade serious
problems.''
</TEXT>
