<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2141EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WomenPriests     06-21 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women Priests,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglican Leader Says Dispute Over Women Priests Need Not Be
Divisive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ordination of women as priests and even
bishops in the Anglican Communion need not disrupt the worldwide
meeting of the church's bishops next month, Archbishop of
Canterbury Robert Runcie said Tuesday.
   ``I hope that we shall be able to consider living together with
this degree of impaired communion that exists and I hope we will
get some idea of how the question is viewed from different parts of
the communion,'' he said.
   Runcie, spiritual head of the state Church of England and leader
of the world's 70 million Anglicans, held a news conference at his
Lambeth Palace residence to discuss the Lambeth Conference that
meets every 10 years.
   He said the 12th conference since 1867 will be attended by more
than 500 bishops at Canterbury from July 17-Aug. 7.
   Only a minority of the 27 Anglican communions in the world have
ordained women to the priesthood. Most are in the U.S. Episcopalian
Church, which is considering consecrating the first woman bishop
but is expected to wait to see how the debate develops at the
Lambeth Conference.
   The Church of England appears to be moving toward the ordination
of women and could decide by the mid-1990s, according to some
church leaders. They noted such a move would have to be approved by
Parliament because it is the state church.
   Some English bishops have said they would consider accepting
women priests but not a woman bishop because bishops are regarded
as the heirs of Christ's apostles, who were men.
   Bishops at the Lambeth Conference in 1978 agreed to accept
churches that ordained women priests and those that did not, and
urged each side to respect the other's convictions.
   Runcie said he hoped next month's conference would ``go beyond''
that decision, but he did not spell out what he thought might be
decided.
   Other major issues to be considered at the conference are the
spread of the AIDS disease, relations with other churches and the
future of the conference.
   Runcie was asked if the Canterbury meeting might be the last
Lambeth Conference and he said he had an open mind on whether the
conference should continue in its present form.
   He said there were logistical problems in organizing such a
large gathering as well as the question of ``impaired communion''
because of the differences over women priests.
   ``It would not be impossible in the future for a looser
association of conferences to take place,'' he said.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome, or AIDS, is a disease in
which a virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers.
   AIDS is most often transmitted through sexual contact. Other
means of transmission include transfusions of tainted blood or
blood products, and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles
or syringes by drug abusers. AIDS can also be passed from mother to
child at or before birth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
