<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Kohl     06-21 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Kohl,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Leader Denies Summit Had Winners, Losers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Tuesday
he found general agreement and optimism among the summit leaders,
adding that it would be ``completely false'' to call President
Reagan or any other leader a loser over the issue of farm subsidies.
   ``There was broad agreement that the economic policy
coordination, particularly of recent months, has proven itself
particularly effective,'' Kohl told reporters.
   The coordinated reaction of the summit nations following the
stock market crash last October contributed greatly to keeping the
world economy from collapsing, he said. And, the leaders agreed
that the prospects for the economy are favorable and encouraging,
Kohl said.
   ``In short, we have well-grounded cause to look forward with
optimism and trust,'' he said.
   Kohl was asked whether Europeans had been victorious in fending
off the attempt by President Reagan and Canadian Prime Minister
Brian Mulroney to pledge to end agriculture subsidies by the year
2000.
   ``Some journalists love simple formulas, and some journalists
above all love pictures that there are victors and vanquished,'' he
said. ``That would be a completely false picture.''
   In the talks on farm policy, the leaders had to take account of
the different situations in each summit country, he said.
   However, he said, ``We are moving completely on a similar
track.''
   ``The long-term goal must be a strong market-orientation of
agriculture production,'' rather than heavy subsidies, Kohl said.
``For this, realism and perspective are necessary.''
   The leaders must take into account the different size of farming
operations and in particular protect small family farms, he said.
West Germany has a number of such small holdings, rather than large
agribusinesses.
   Of special significance during the summit was the attention paid
to the debt burden of the world's poorest countries, especially
those in Africa, Kohl said.
   West Germany already has forgiven 4.2 billion marks, or $2.5
billion, in poor countries' debt and plans to take further measures
to ease their burden by another 2.3 billion marks, or $1.39 billion
dollars, he said.
   Kohl said he particularly urged environmental protection during
the summit, including a promotion of international attempts to
reduce acid rain and protect water resources, particularly the
North Sea.
   He said he would continue to pursue his goal of seeking to tie
protection of tropical rain forests to helping debt-ridden
countries, adding that ``doubtless the World Bank has an important
role to play.''
   The bank has been criticized for funding projects that destroy
the forests and the valuable resources they provide. The bank's
projects sometimes have included conversions of the forests into
farms that soon fail and turn to desert.
   Improvement of the plight of poor countries is also closely tied
to the fight against trade protection, he said.
   ``Without open markets, the developing countries have no chance
to improve their situation for the long term,'' he said.
</TEXT>
