<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Anchor-CanalCase     06-21 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anchor-Canal Case,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Department Reaches Tentative Settlement in Oil Overcharge
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department said Tuesday it had
agreed on an unusual tentative settlement of one of its most
controversial oil price cases, a case in which an administration
official was determined by his boss to have given the appearance of
a conflict of interest.
   The department said Anchor Gasoline Corp., a Tulsa, Okla.,
refiner, and its subsidiary, Canal Refining Co. of Church Point,
La., had agreed to pay $9 million and possibly as much as $30
million, plus certain interest charges which were not spelled out
in the announcement, to settle charges that the two firms charged
too much for crude oil and refined products in 1973-1981, when
price controls were in effect.
   The department still has outstanding about 200 overcharge cases.
President Reagan ended controls shortly after he took office in
1981.
   The Anchor settlement will go above $9 million if Anchor's net
income, as defined in the settlement, is enough to trigger
specified shares for the government during the four fiscal years
beginning May 1.
   The agreement calls for the government to take 12.5 percent of
net income from $1.5 million to $2 million and a rising percentage
of amounts above that, reaching 50 percent of anything over $5
million.
   In 1982, Joseph Wright Jr., deputy director of the Office of
Management and Budget, called an official of the Energy
Department's Economic Regulatory Administration and asked him to
meet with Anchor officials to discuss a settlement. A meeting
occurred.
   Anchor is run by Wright's father. The family owned 20 percent of
the company, with Wright owning about 3 percent.
   Though a Senate committee explored the matter in 1985, the
Justice Department declined to pursue it.
   James Miller, director of the Office of Management and Budget,
wrote Wright in 1986 that his call ``created the appearance of a
conflict of interest,'' but kept him on the job.
   The settlement is open for public comment until July 18, when
the department's Economic Regulatory Administration will hold a
public hearing in Washington on the proposal.
</TEXT>
