<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CampaignSymposium     06-21 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Symposium,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Campaign Officials Discuss Election Process</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The managers of Michael Dukakis' and Jesse
Jackson's Democratic presidential campaigns got together Tuesday
but focused more on the election of 28 years ago than the
differences of their candidates today.
   Dukakis campaign manager Susan Estrich and her counterpart in
the Jackson camp, Gerald Austin, were among the participants in a
John F. Kennedy Library symposium that examined differences in the
presidential campaigns of 1960 and 1988 and the media's role in the
election process.
   Sponsored by Life magazine and moderated by ABC correspondent
Jeff Greenfield, the panel discussion dealt with three issues:
comparing the 1988 and 1960 presidential elections, assessing the
effect of television on the campaigns, and an analyzing how the
nation has changed in those 28 years.
   ``It was a lot of fun for me to sit and listen to the folks from
1960,'' said Estrich. ``I came away with both a renewed sense of
appreciation for that campaign and an appreciation of the new
rules.''
   One reason Estrich and Austin didn't spend too much time
discussing current conflicts was that their bosses were meeting
face-to-face across the country in Los Angeles.
   Veterans of the 1960 campaign who were present at the session
were 1960 Republican nominee Richard Nixon's press secretary,
Herbert Klein, and his 1960 campaign director, Robert Finch, along
with Kennedy's speech writer, Richard Goodwin.
   Among the topics of discussion was how much Kennedy's
Catholicism was an issue in the 1960 campaign, whereas religion is
not generally seen as a barrier to political office today.
   ``That suggests how far we have come in the past 28 years,''
Estrich said.
   Syndicated columnist Mary McGrory recalled how television played
a much smaller role in the 1960 campaign, which she covered, than
it does today, although the televised debates in 1960 were hailed
as a sign of television's first significant impact on presidential
politics.
   The panelists also discussed changes in rhetoric and
speech-making during campaigns _ changes they said were largely
dictated by the demands of television _ and the evolution of the
image of the presidency since 1960.
</TEXT>
