<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Politics     06-21 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Politics,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Candidate to Announce Cabinet in Advance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manuel J. Clouthier, presidential candidate
of the opposition National Action Party, said Tuesday he will name
the members of his intended Cabinet before the election so voters
will be better informed.
   ``I want the people to know beforehand who would form my
Cabinet,'' Clouthier told at a news conference at the Foreign
Correspondents Association.
   The president-elect usually announces his Cabinet on
inauguration day or just before. Clouthier, whose chances of
winning the July 6 election are considered nil, said he would
reveal his list next week.
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari is expected to be Mexico's next
president. He is the candidate of the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, known by its Spanish initials PRI, which was founded in 1929
and has governed the country since, never having lost a
presidential election.
   A poll called the ``most ambitious ever realized'' in Mexico
indicated 56 percent of registered voters favored Salinas.
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a leftist coalition candidate, was next in
the survey, obtaining 23 percent and Clouthier had 19. The Gallup
survey was conducted between May 12 and June 1 for ECO, Inc., a Los
Angeles-based affiliate of the private Televisa television network,
which has close ties to the government.
   Clouthier insisted he ha a chance, declaring Tuesday: ``There
hasn't been any government in the world that after three
consecutive years of more than 60 percent inflation still remains
in power. This July 6, Mexico won't be an exception.''
   National Action, popularly known by its Spanish initials PAN, is
the customary runnerup, but there had been speculation before the
poll that Cardenas would finish seocnd.
   Cardenas broke with the PRI last year after it rebuffed the
internal reform movement he called Democratic Current. His
coalition is called the National Democratic Front.
   National Action says many state and local election victories
have been stolen from it and Clouthier has called for civil
disobedience if ``alchemy,'' as vote fraud is known in Mexico,
occurs July 6.
   He is a business leader and rancher from the northwestern
coastal state of Sinaloa. His conservative party traditionally
fares best in northern Mexico.
</TEXT>
