delivered; No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis met privately with Jesse
Jackson Tuesday and discussed the Democratic vice presidential slot
but both refused to say whether Jackson asked for second billing on
the ticket.
   Jackson said they discussed the vice presidency ``to some
measure'' during the 40-minute meeting and he repeated his
assertion that ``our constituency deserves consideration.''
   Dukakis refused to give any hint of what they discussed.
   ``We talk about lots of things when we talk,'' Dukakis said at a
news conference following the session. ``I don't talk about private
conversations.''
   In a separate news conference, Jackson revealed few details.
   ``We talked about it more than we have talked about it (before)
person to person,'' Jackson said of the vice presidential question.
   Dukakis repeated earlier statements that he has begun looking at
vice presidential nominees but has made no decisions yet.
   ``The process has now begun. But it's open. There's no short
list, or medium list or long list,'' Dukakis said.
   ``There's no understanding (with Jackson),'' Dukakis continued.
``He himself has said it's up to the nominee to make that decision.
I agree with him.''
   Jackson reiterated his contention that he deserves consideration
as a potential running mate.
   ``This constituency we have organized in our party has earned
consideration,'' he said. ``Our constituency represents hope for
our party. It represents a commitment to make room for all
Democrats.''
   But asked if he told Dukakis that he wanted to be on the ticket,
Jackson said ``I'm not going to characterize exactly what we
discussed.''
   Dukakis, who now has more than enough to clinch the presidential
nomination at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta next
month, met with Jackson after addressing more than 3,500 members of
the American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees.
   Jackson is to address the same group on Wednesday.
   In his AFSCME address, Dukakis renewed his call for a national
health insurance program, saying that should be ``the birthright of
every family and every citizen of the United States of America.''
   ``Two months ago, ... I became the first governor in America to
sign a bill that will guarantee health insurance for every single
citizen in my state,'' Dukakis said. ``And I look forward to the
day I can sign the same kind of bill into law for all Americans _
as president of the United States.''
   Dukakis said he would support legislation to require all except
the smallest businesses to provide health insurance, which he
presented as a fairness issue between employers as well as a basic
right for employees.
   ``Responsible employers, who provide insurance for their
workers, must compete with employers who don't provide a dime's
worth of coverage for their employees and dependents. That's not
fair. That's not right. And with your help we're going to change it
beginning in January of 1989,'' he said.
   ``The simplest way and the fairest way and the most affordable
way to expand the circle of health care and health opportunity for
our citizens is to require every employer _ with some exceptions
for small businesses _ to provide insurance coverage for their
workers and dependents,'' he said, estimating that about 38 million
Americans would be affected by such a proposal.
</TEXT>
