<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AuctionRecords     06-21 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auction Records,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Sales At Sotheby's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three records were set Tuesday in the sale at
Sotheby's auction house of three manuscripts collected by William
Waldorf Astor.
   The three were among 20 medieval and Renaissance manuscripts
collected by Astor that sold for a total $8.3 million.
   At another Sotheby's sale, an American collector paid a record
$1.62 million for a work by the French romantic painter Eugene
Delacroix (1798-1863), providing French actor Alain Delon a huge
profit.
   Astor became the wealthiest American of the day when his father,
John Jacob Astor, died in 1890. The younger Astor moved to Britain,
bought the Cliveden mansion and Hever Castle and became a British
citizen in 1899. He died in 1919.
   Family trustees sold the manuscripts, most of which were bought
by dealers.
   The top price of 1.54 million pounds ($2.74 million) _ a record
for an English manuscript _ was paid by the London dealer Quaritch
for a prayer book made in about 1340 for Elizabeth de Bohun,
countess of Northampton. The previous high was 1.25 million pounds
(then $1.8 million) in June 1986 for a manuscript on the life of
St. Thomas Becket.
   Quaritch also paid the record for an Italian manuscript, 770,000
pounds ($1.37 million) for a 15th century prayer book made for
Galeazzo Maria Sforza, duke of Milan.
   The highest price for a Flemish manuscript, 1.21 million pounds
($2.15 million), was paid by the West German dealer Tenschert for a
16th century prayer book of Cardinal Albrecht of Brandenburg.
   Sotheby's said the American bid by telephone to acquire the
Delacroix painting of an Arab with drawn sword on a galloping
horse. The price paid, 913,000 pounds ($1.62 million), is more than
double the previous price for a work by the artist. The buyer was
not identified.
   Delon bought the painting in Paris in 1977 for 49,000 pounds
(then $124,000).
   Also at Sotheby's Tuesday, a fragment o a biblical manuscript
found in the sands of Egypt and kept in Boston since 1950 sold for
104,500 pounds ($186,000).
   The torn and stained scrap of vellum bearing Greek writing was
believed to date from the third century and is the earliest known
manuscript of part of St. Paul's letter to the Romans on the
concept of justification by faith.
   It was bought by Quaritch and the seller was not identified.
</TEXT>
