<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2056EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-ReaganFarewell 1stLd-Writethru a0803 06-21 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Reagan Farewell, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0803,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit Bids Farewell to Reagan, Their `Trusted Ally'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 8th graf bgng: Mulroney said ... to
UPDATE with Mitterrand remarks. Picks up 9th graf pvs bgng: British
Prime ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLE FELDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western leaders on Tuesday marked the end of
President Reagan's foray into economic summitry with a resounding
tribute to a ``gracious friend and trusted ally'' and a declaration
that Reagan's place in history had been secured.
   The Toronto summit was Reagan's eighth, and when the seven
summit nations meet next, in France in July 1989, the United States
will be represented by one of two likely successors _ Vice
President George Bush or Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Asked if he would miss the annual gatherings, Reagan told
reporters, ``In a way, yes.''
   Reagan's summit partners were quick to praise the president
throughout the three-day meeting. But when it came to the final
communique, they denied him what he had sought most _ an end to all
agricultural subsidies by the end of the century.
   Still, the president said he was satisfied with the results of
his final summit.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, speaking on behalf of
the Western leaders, used the occasion of the reading of the final
communique to deliver a formal thank you to the American president.
   ``His leadership has been strong, his accomplishments
substantial and his place in history secure,'' Mulroney declared.
``Ronald Reagan has been for all of us at this table a gracious
friend and a trusted ally. We shall all miss his warmth and his
wisdom.''
   Mulroney said Reagan was leaving Toronto with the respect and
affection of the summit leaders and ``our best wishes for good
health and every happiness for Nancy and himself.''
   French President Francois Mitterrand was a lot cooler.
   ``For someone who played a great role in contemporary history,
it's normal to salute him and wish that his retirement be happy and
long,'' Mitterrand said. ``It's a courtesy. It has nothing to do, I
suppose, with politics.''
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, the dean of the summit
leaders and a philosophical soulmate of the president's, told
reporters she had only ``kind words'' for Reagan.
   ``He's been marvelous,'' she said.
   At a news conference later, she said that Mulroney's tribute had
the support of ``each and every one of us _ the whole-hearted
support and affection for President Reagan and what he has done.''
   Mrs. Thatcher and Reagan will meet at least once again before he
leaves office. Reagan has invited her to visit him in Washington
after the November elections.
</TEXT>
