<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Reagan-Speech 1stLd-Writethru a0782 06-21 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Reagan-Speech, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0782,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Urges Summit Partners To Maintain Free Trade</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 3rd graf bgng: In a ... to UPDATE with speech delivered.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, in a summit farewell address,
urged his economic partners on Tuesday to expand free trade and
steer clear of ``the protection and isolation that are relics of
another age.''
   Winding up his eighth and final session with the leaders of
Britain, Canada, France, Italy, Japan and West Germany, the
77-year-old president left them also with a message of faith in the
technological revolution.
   In a speech to a group of Canadian businessmen prior to his
departure from Canada, Reagan noted a tiny silicon chip has the
power of the biggest computers of the 1960s. ``Do we dare stop
climbing?'' he asked.
   Reagan is credited with persuading his summit partners through
the years to encourage free-market trends and to eschew
protectionism. At his final summit, however, he was unable to rally
them behind his appeal for an end to agricultural subsidies by the
year 2000.
   Still, in the final communique, the seven leaders offered a
vague promise to consider the problems of farm subsidies, and the
White House found a victory in that decision.
   ``The U.S. is happy with the final product,'' said Marlin
Fitzwater, the president's spokesman.
   Reagan, in his speech, warned that ``protectionist storms'' were
brewing around the world. The choice, he said, was ``between moving
toward freer trade, or backward toward the protection and isolation
that are relics of another age.''
   He said the industrialized democracies could not stand still,
and in a special reference to Canada, he said ``we North Americans
never have. We have always risen to meet a challenge. Our hearts
quicken to the call, our eyes brighten, our pace picks up.''
   Looking back before his two-term presidency, Reagan said
``inflation, stagnation, decline and despair characterized, in one
measure or another, the economies of nearly all the summit nations.
Today, we live in a time of hope.''
   Reagan also gave the businessmen a glowing report of his summit
meeting in Moscow three weeks ago with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   He called the general secretary ``a serious man seeking serious
reform'' and said their talks focused on freedom of choice and
other individual freedoms.
   ``I know I speak for all of us in saying our prayers go with the
Soviet peoples,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
