<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-BBC     06-21 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-BBC,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BBC Says Government Drops Ban on Spy Series</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said Tuesday that
the government has agreed to lift a six-month-old ban on a BBC
radio series about Britain's security services.
   It said it planned to broadcast its Radio 4 series, ``My
Country: Right or Wrong,'' next week. The three-part series
features interviews with nine former or serving intelligence
officials.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's administration won a court
order last Dec. 4 to prevent the series from being broadcast. It
claimed the nine officials might have broken their oaths of secrecy
and said the series could harm national security.
   BBC initially refused to turn over the transcripts of the series
to government officials, saying that would amount to
pre-censorship, but later relented.
   Publicly funded BBC issued a statement Tuesday saying the
government's treasury solicitor ``has informed the BBC that he will
cease his action against the Radio 4 series.''
   ``The BBC and the treasury solicitor will apply to the court
this week to have the injunction lifted, and the BBC hopes to
transmit the series next week across three successive days,'' it
said.
   BBC deputy director general John Birt criticized the
government's attempt to block the series and said the action had
``prevented a serious discussion of matters of public concern when
interest in them was most ripe.''
</TEXT>
