<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Thatcher     06-21 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Thatcher,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Leader Hails Summit Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on
Tuesday hailed the Toronto summit as a success despite the absence
of agreement on farm subsidies, and said the free-market policies
pushed there ``make for a better world.''
   ``We've made a start,'' said Mrs. Thatcher, defending the vague
language in the summit communique on farm subsidies and its
effective rejection of a U.S. proposal to eliminate the subsidies
by the year 2000.
   ``There is a specific commitment to try first to freeze and then
to roll back the subsidies and various other kinds of support for
agriculture in an ordered and substantial way,'' she told a news
conference at the conclusion of the three-day summit.
   ``It means not just having a higgledy-piggledy, haphazard
reduction, but really trying to stick to some principles ... We
need to set long-term objectives and each have some short-term
objective going toward the long term.''
   She said the sustained economic growth enjoyed by the world's
richest countries stemmed from ``the cooperation and common sense
of purpose between the summit countries during the 1980s in
applying sound economic policies, containing inflation, promoting
efficiency, enterprise and competition.''
   Praising the free-market policies pushed at the summit, Mrs.
Thatcher said, ``Success, however hard to come by, may not make
news, but it does make for a better world.''
   Mrs. Thatcher, who has been President Reagan's staunchest
foreign ally, said ``each and every one of us'' felt
``whole-hearted support and affection for President Reagan and what
he has done.''
   Asked whether she would carry the torch with Reagan's departure,
Mrs. Thatcher said, ``I just see myself as carrying on, believing
the things that I have believed and trying to translate them into
action.''
   ``This final summit (for Reagan) underlines the success of the
economic policies we have pursued in this second (seven-year) cycle
of summit meetings in which he played such an important part.''
   She said the summit also ``sharpened the attack on terrorism''
by endorsing International Civil Aviation Organization call that
countries should agree not to allow hijacked aircraft to take off.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who apologized during the summit to West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl for the hooliganism in Europe of British
soccer spectators, said she had suggested during the summit that
discipline was a tougher problem now than adapting to technological
change.
   ``What we are faced with now are some of the really tricky
problems _ some of the behavioral problems,'' said Mrs. Thatcher.
``These are the problems that really go to the root of the quality
of life.''
</TEXT>
