<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberating In Newman Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 1st to UPDATE with deliberations over
for the day.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury on Tuesday began deliberating
whether Paul Newman reneged on a promise to give a delicatessen
owner a share of the actor's food business.
   The jury, which interrupted about five hours of deliberations
twice to ask questions and have testimony re-read, was to resume
deliberations Wednesday.
   Julius Gold of Westport contends in the Superior Court lawsuit
that he helped develop and market Newman's Own salad dressing and
that he was assured orally that he would receive 8 percent of the
stock in return.
   Gold said he contributed 30 months' effort to Newman's company
and believed his ``judgment and perserverance ... led to the
success of this corporation.''
   Newman, president and founder of Newman's Own Inc., testified
that Gold had never received such a commitment and that the idea
for the dressing, its recipe and packaging were his own.
   Newman's Own, whose products include spaghetti sauce, lemonade
and popcorn, has donated $15 million to charity since 1982 and
helped create a camp for seriously ill children in Connecticut.
   Lawyers have given no estimate of what an 8 percent stake would
be worth.
   Named in the suit besides Newman are his food companies,
Newman's Own Inc. and Salad King Inc.; Newman's partner and
longtime friend, author A.E. Hotchner, and food distributor David
Kalman.
</TEXT>
