<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Takeshita,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Prime Minister Reported Very Pleased With Summit Results</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita viewed
the economic summit with a ``sense of fulfillment'' and won praise
from the Western leaders for his country's success in narrowing its
trade surpluses, an aide said Tuesday.
   Michihiko Kunihiro, chief cabinet councillor for external
affairs, told reporters that Japan's three priorities for the
Toronto summit produced results.
   He listed them as strengthening policy coordination among the
seven largest industrial democracies and the European Community,
resisting protectionism and addressing the problem of Third World
debt.
   ``I am finishing this summit meeting with a sense of
fulfillment,'' the official quoted Takeshita as saying.
   ``The prime minister was gratified to confirm the importance
every summiteer attaches to policy coordination. He finds that
sustained growth without inflation has now taken root in the minds
of every summiteer.''
   Takeshita found it reassuring that other leaders strongly resist
protectionism, while special Japanese farming considerations were
taken into account in calling for reduced farm subsidies, Kunihiro
said.
   On debt, Takeshita was ``particularly pleased'' that a great
deal of attention was paid to poor developing countries and
understood the lack of specific action for middle-income debtors
such as Brazil, where the problem is more complex and requires a
``menu approach.''
   Kunihiro said Takeshita won ``complimentary remarks'' from
several summit partners for Japan's recent success in boosting
imports and narrowing its trade surpluses.
   Kunihiro said this may have accounted for the absence of any
Japan-bashing in Toronto, in contrast to summits in past years.
   ``Statistics talked on our behalf,'' he said.
</TEXT>
