<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeSillers     06-21 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DeSillers,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Fine Against Maria DeSillers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hearing officer on Tuesday
dismissed a $1,000 fine imposed against a woman for allegedly
violating the state's charity law by misusing funds donated for her
late son's liver transplants.
   Administrative Hearing Officer Donald Alexander in Tallahassee
said in his decision that all the money donated for Ronnie
DeSillers' transplants became part of his estate after his death,
exempting the funds from the state charity law.
   ``As such, the Circuit Court has `exclusive jurisdiction' to
ensure that the donated funds, which are now a part of Ronnie's
estate, are used for legitimate purposes,'' Alexander wrote.
   Alexander emphasized that his ruling applied only to whether the
boy's mother, Maria DeSillers, was required to register as a
charity. He said he was not ruling on whether Ms. DeSillers
received or used the money legitimately.
   The decision noted that other court remedies are available for
those who want to challenge her use of the money.
   The 7-year-old Miami boy died at Children's Hospital of
Pittsburgh in April 1987 while awaiting a fourth liver transplant
after a fund-raising drive that brought in $660,000, including a
$1,000 donation from President Reagan.
   The Dade County state attorney's office is investigating
allegations that Ms. DeSillers made personal use of $47,000 of
donations to her son.
   An official appointed by the state attorney's office reported
last month that Ms. DeSillers spent some $200,000 of donations on
herself, relatives and friends. The spending included payments of
$10,850 to a jewelry store and $23,700 to Ms. DeSillers'
ex-boyfriend, the report said.
   Ms. DeSillers hailed Tuesday's decision.
   ``People should realize I never did anything wrong. Everything I
did was for Ronnie,'' she said at a news conference.
   ``The state has nothing to show my side of it. I will be
vindicated in the end.''
   Ms. DeSillers' lawyer, Harry Robbins, said the ruling showed Ms.
DeSillers violated no laws and that the money remaining in the
estate should belong to her.
   ``We believe that this is the beginning of a vindication
process,'' said Robbins. ``Maria only wanted to do good. She only
wants to help people.''
   Robbins acknowledged Ms. DeSillers still faces legal problems
that are likely to continue for years, but he said she will
continue working to increase organ donor awareness.
   Court documents show $509,912 of donations was in Ronnie's
account when he died. About $239,288 remained in a custodial
account on Feb. 18.
</TEXT>
