<HEAD>Host Prime Minister Says Toronto Got Back To Spirit of First
Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney put a
positive spin on the economic summit's refusal Tuesday to abolish
agricultural subsidies by the year 2000, saying, ``We have come a
long way'' since the issue was placed on the agenda two years ago.
   Mulroney, host of the 14th annual meeting of the world's largest
industrialized democracies, had hoped that his summit colleagues
would take firm action to end the subsidy war, an issue pushed by
President Reagan.
   Although the final communique called only for reductions in
subsidies, not their elimination as the United States proposed,
Mulroney declared himself ``well pleased.''
   ``We have come a long way'' since the issue was placed on the
summit agenda in Tokyo two years ago, he said.
   He termed the declaration ``a strong signal of continued
political support for reform'' in advance of the December meeting
in Montreal, which will complete a mid-term review of the current
trade talks.
   ``It is not a perfect statement but it represents some
progress,'' Mulroney said.
   The Conservative leader said he was gratified that the summit
``strongly welcomed'' the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement _ which
has run into heated opposition within Canada.
   ``It's pretty hard to do better than that,'' he said of the
communique's language.
   Most of all, Mulroney said, he was pleased with the success of
the two additional negotiating sessions he introduced into economic
summitry, including a relaxed talk about educational needs of the
future.
   ``The summit as a forum has been strengthened,'' he said.
</TEXT>
