<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Sajak, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0736,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Hoping Sajak Will Be Letter Perfect As Late Night Talk Show
Host</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf ``Sajak, 41'' to CORRECT by deleting erroneous
statement that Sajak never was host of a talk show. Picks up 6th
graf: ``But CBS ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Game show host Pat Sajak, hoping to send
CBS's late-night ratings wheels spinning with a new talk show, says
the program is still in the formative stages, with the biggest
decision so far being a name.
   It's going to be called ``The Pat Sajak Show.''
   ``I guess it isn't the most creative thing in the world, but it
says what it is,'' said Sajak, the low-key host of ``Wheel of
Fortune,'' the most successful television series in syndication
history.
   ``Of course, I had a different idea,'' said Sajak. ``I looked up
and down the CBS schedule and saw `Kate & Allie,' `Cagney & Lacey,'
`Eisenhower & Lutz,' `Jake and The Fatman.' So I thought a good
name would be `Pat and His Desk.'''
   Sajak, 41, will be the latest to go up against the mighty Johnny
Carson in the late-night slot, a time when Joan Rivers and Alan
Thicke have failed.
   But CBS, last in prime-time and late-night ratings, is betting
Sajak's popularity from ``Wheel of Fortune'' will translate to
viewers when the show starts in January.
   The network has given ``The Pat Sajak Show'' a two-year
commitment and is building a studio for it in Hollywood.
   ``I mean, obviously, that's what I'm doing is competing in the
same time slot with Carson,'' said Sajak. ``All I can say is I'm
going to do a good show and let the pieces fall where they may.''
</TEXT>
