<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HoppeTrial     06-21 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hoppe Trial,0438</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Jury Selected In Ex-Football Star's Trial For 31-Year-Old Slaying
^By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former college football star went on
trial on first-degree murder charges Tuesday, nearly 31 years after
the man he is accused of slaying was shot to death.
   Bobby Hoppe, 53, is charged with the 1957 shotgun death of Don
Hudson, a 24-year-old moonshine runner who had dated Hoppe's sister.
   Prosecutor Tom Evans and defense attorneys Bobby Lee Cook and
Leroy Phillips spent more than six hours Tuesday in Hamilton County
Criminal Court selecting a jury. Opening arguments are scheduled
Wednesday before Judge Joe DiRisio.
   Hudson, an ex-convict who had several scrapes with the law, was
shot in the early morning hours of July 20, 1957, as he drove his
car on a street in North Chattanooga, not far from his home.
   Hoppe, a star running back who went on to help lead a 10-0
Auburn University team to the 1957 national football championship,
was questioned at the time of the slaying.
   However, no one was arrested in connection with Hudson's death
until Hoppe was indicted last March, after police reopened the case
at the request of Hudson's mother, Georgia.
   Key prosecution witnesses in the case are expected to be the
Rev. Joseph Godwin, a Baptist minister who is mayor of Mars Hill,
N.C., and Odene Neal of Red Bank, Tenn., who was an acquaintance of
Hoppe in 1957.
   During a pretrial hearing earlier this month, Godwin testified
that he was taking a summer class at Auburn in a957 when Hoppe came
to him and said he had killed a man.
   Defense attorneys argued then that Godwin's testimony shouldn't
be allowed because of a 1959 law prohibiting the courtroom use of
conversations with ministers. DiRisio ruled that Godwin and Hoppe
did not have a pastoral relationship.
   Mrs. Neal testified during another pretrial hearing that seven
hours before Hudson was slain Hoppe had threatened to kill him. She
said Hoppe made the statement after Mrs. Neal told him that Hudson
had ``smacked around on'' Hoppe's sister, Joan, whom Hudson had
dated.
   In a successful defense motion Monday to get a list of the
state's witnesses, Cook and Phillips described Godwin's and Neal's
testimony as false and manufactured.
   Hoppe is on an unpaid leave from his job as athletic director at
Chattanooga State Technical Community College. If convicted, he
faces a sentence of 20 years to life in prison.
   Tennessee has a death penalty, but Hoppe is being tried under
the law as it existed in 1957.
</TEXT>
