<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2257EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Haiti     06-21 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Haiti,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Coup Won't Stop Haiti's Pursuit of Duvalier Millions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRASSE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military coup in Haiti will not
interrupt Haiti's efforts to regain millions of dollars allegedly
taken by dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier when he fled to France,
attorneys representing Haiti said Tuesday.
   A judge was to be selected Monday in this southern French city
to hear the case against Duvalier, accused of misappropriating $120
million in public funds.
   In Haiti's capital of Port-au-Prince on Monday, Lt. Gen. Henri
Namphy re-established military rule by decree and named his own
government a few hours after ousting President Leslie Manigat's
civilian government.
   The coup crushed hopes for the democracy promised two years ago
after Duvalier was toppled, ending his family's 29-year
dictatorship.
   ``We are not lawyers for the government but for the Haitian
state,'' said attorney Yann Colin, who represents Haiti in its
French legal proceedings.
   In April a French court ruled it had jurisdiction in the case
against Duvalier.
   The Haitian national lottery, office of vehicle insurance,
gaming commission and Port-au-Prince Bank are demanding that
Duvalier and members of his entourage reimburse the government.
   Colin claimed the $120 million requested represents only part of
what Duvalier diverted.
   Since arriving in France Feb. 7, 1986, Duvalier has lived with
his wife, Michelle, and other family members in a luxurious mansion
in southern France rented from Saudi millionaire Adnan Kashoggi.
   Duvalier has declined to comment on political developments in
Haiti since his downfall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
