<DOCNO> AP880621-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2258EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-USBusiness     06-21 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-US Business,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Businessmen Told of Difficulties Operating in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China is both a land of opportunity and a
quagmire of bureaucracy, delay and high costs, American businessmen
were told Tuesday at a major trade and business conference.
   ``I think China is a super place to do business if you realize
there's no free lunch,'' William Kinch, head of Grace China
Limited, said during panel discussions at the U.S.-China Joint
Session on Industry, Trade and Economic Development.
   The conference has brought nearly 1,000 American businessmen to
the Great Hall of the People for discussions on doing business in
China.
   It is the largest business conference ever held in China and
reflects China's hopes that American money will play a major role
in its modernization drive.
   U.S.-Sino trade topped $10 billion last year.
   Kinch's company in Shanghai produces sealing compounds for cans
and was one of the first enterprises in China wholly owned by
foreigners.
   He said it took nearly three years of negotiations to establish
the company because of foreign exchange problems and the need to
receive approval from several ministries and offices, both in
Shanghai and Beijing.
   Attorney Jerome Cohen, a specialist on Chinese law, told
potential investors they must be certain they are negotiating with
people who have the business licenses and authority to sign
contracts.
   He said approval from a ministry for a joint venture does not
mean that the tax or customs offices will go along with the project.
   Roy King of H.J. Heinz Co., which produces baby food in southern
China, said inflation accompanying China's switch to
market-determined prices is becoming a serious problem, and any
equipment ``invented in the last 30 years will have to be
imported.''
   He said permits and licenses can take months to obtain because
of the ``very well developed bureaucracy,'' and joint ventures must
bring in people at great cost in the early stages because of the
lack of skilled Chinese personnel.
   American panelists also said low labor costs are offset by low
productivity and there is an absence of market-research skills.
   Chinese speakers emphasized the progress China is making. Yuan
Zhenmin, director of treaties and law in the Foreign Economic
Relations and Trade Ministry, said the government has moved
aggressively to pass laws governing foreign investments.
   Yuan said income tax, patent, joint-venture and trademark laws
passed in recent years have assured foreign businessmen of fair
treatment. China now has more than 10,000 joint ventures or wholly
foreign-owned enterprises.
   It is the first visit to China for about 95 percent of the
American businessmen.
   Ivy Joseph Breaux, operator of a centrifugal foundry in Temple,
Texas, said the Chinese ``are really trying to move very fast. I
really trust them.''
   ``The Chinese are very sincere,'' said Alberto Barrocas, a shoe
manufacturer from Miami. ``They are very conscious of the great
need they have for expanding their horizons in trade. They want to
make it happen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
