<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0721,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospitals Say 36 Treated in Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf ``The youngsters'' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
two more hospitalized, quotes about brief fire. Picks up 6th graf
pvs ``The driver...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOWE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus carrying members of a Michigan drum and
bugle corps was hit Tuesday from the rear by a semi-trailer truck,
injuring 36 people, authorities said.
   The bus, with 40 people aboard, had stopped for mechanical
problems on the Indiana Toll Road and was struck when it pulled
back onto the road around 3:30 a.m., said State Police Cpl. Ron
Johnston.
   The Northern Aurora Drum and Bugle Corps was returning to
Saginaw, Mich., from a competition in Mishawaka. The members range
in age from 14 to 21.
   ``Many of them aren't really sure what happened,'' said Steve
Stigall, an instructor who was riding on another bus. ``They were
asleep at the time.''
   A brief fire scorched the front of the truck cab on impact, said
Jackie Waskoviak, the wife of corps commander Robert Waskoviak.
   ``He looked in his rear-view mirror, and he did see flames, a
ball of fire is what he called it,'' she said in a telephone
interview from Saginaw after talking with her husband. ``It was out
very quickly.''
   Two young men were hospitalized, one for a concussion and
bruises and the other for a said broken wrist, hospital officials
said. Three other youngsters were treated at hospitals and released.
   The driver of the truck, Larry A. Noble, 46, of Clinton, Iowa,
was in stable condition at Parkview Memorial Hospital in Fort Wayne
suffering from a back injury and cuts, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   The bus driver, Frank Davila, 56, of Freeland, Mich., was
treated at Sturgis Hospital and released, a spokeswoman said.
   Neither driver has been cited, said state police Lt. Ken
Hollingsworth.
</TEXT>
