<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Venezuela-Haiti     06-21 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela-Haiti,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuela Cancels Aid; Talks Of Action To Re-establish Haitian
Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday canceled aid
to Haiti and said it is talking with other Latin American nations
about collective action to re-establish democracy in that Caribbean
nation.
   President Jaime Lusinchi denounced the ouster of elected
President Leslie Manigat in Sunday's military coup. He said he was
pulling out Venezuelan aid workers sent to Haiti after the fall of
dictator Jean Claude Duvalier in February 1986.
   ``The ouster of President Manigat by Gen. (Henri) Namphy is
unacceptable for Venezuela and we are making all the necessary
consultations to promote collective action by Latin America to
correct this abnormal situation,'' Lusinchi told reporters at the
presidential palace.
   ``While Manigat will always be welcome in Venezuela, it is not a
question of hospitality but of re-establishing the democratic
system in this fellow nation,'' he said.
   Lusinchi said a corps of Venezuelan officials and soldiers sent
to Haiti in 1986 to help build roads and housing was recalled
Tuesday ``as a show of protest.'' He did not disclose the extent of
the Venezuelan assistance.
   Manigat was granted political asylum in the Dominican Republic
Tuesday. He had lived in exile in Venezuela in the 1970's.
   Foreign Minister German Nava is expected to discuss Haiti with
his Argentine colleague Dante Caputo, scheduled to meet with
Lusinchi in Caracas on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
