<2ND_LINE>AM-Car-Train Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0804,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Killed in Kansas Collision; Eighth Person Dies in Rescue
Effort</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to specify adults were women, INSERTS 3 grafs
after 8th graf ``The car'' to UPDATE with quotes from sheriff, adds
final graf with names and hometown.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHEROKEE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven people were killed Tuesday afternoon
when their station wagon was struck by a freight train at a rural
crossing, and an eighth person collapsed and died trying to
resuscitate one of the victims.
   Two women and five children were killed when their car burst
into flames after the collision about eight miles west of Pittsburg
in southeast Kansas.
   Five of the accident victims were dead at the scene. One child
was pronounced dead at Mount Carmel Medical Center in Pittsburg,
120 miles south of Kansas City, and another died en route. Names of
the victims were not released.
   Joe Cobb, director of the Crawford County ambulance service,
collapsed and died of an apparent heart attack at the hospital
while trying to resuscitate one of the children, hospital spokesman
Collin Hermreck said.
   Cobb, 48, apparently went to the accident scene, where the
temperature was in the mid-90s, and returned to the hospital with
one of the victims, Hermreck said.
   ``Shortly after the victims arrived, he was helping resuscitate
one of the children. He collapsed and died,'' he said.
   Crawford County Sheriff Lynn Fields said the car was struck in
the passenger side door by a Burlington Northern freight train made
up of an engine and seven cars.
   The car was crossing the tracks about two miles northeast of
Cherokee. The crossing was not protected with lights or safety
gates.
   ``What we've found out so far is that the driver didn't even
look up,'' Fields said. ``So, apparently she didn't even see the
train.
   ``Other witnesses say the engine did blow its whistle and that
apparently the train did everything it could do to avoid the
accident. But the car was right on the middle of the tracks when
the train struck it.''
   Fields said the intersection has a clear view but that other
car-train collisions have been reported there.
   Lennie Westervelt, chief of the Rural Cherokee Fire Department,
said the car's gasoline tank exploded and the car was engulfed in
flames when firefighters arrived. The wooden railroad ties also
were on fire.
   Westervelt said there was nothing firefighters could do to help
the victims. All victims but one were thrown from the car.
   The rail cars remained upright and on the tracks. Officers at
the scene said there was a small fire in electrical wiring on the
train.
   The Kansas Highway Patrol identified victims as the driver,
Kathy Hastings, 31; her children, Erik Hastings, 5; Reuben
Hastings, 3; and Kara Hastings, 8; Lisa Maxwell, 26; her children,
Joel Maxwell, 5; and Avery Maxwell, 2. All were from Iola, the
patrol said.
</TEXT>
