<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Bofors     06-21 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Bofors,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Former Bofors Executives Charged With Arms Smuggling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday filed arms
smuggling charges against four former directors of the country's
largest weapons manufacturer.
   The Bofors AB executives were accused of selling 300
anti-aircraft missiles to Bahrain and Dubai in 1979 and 1980 in
violation of Swedish export regulations barring arms sales to
volatile regions.
   Folke Ljungvall, chief prosecutor of the city of Karlstad, said
he expected the case to come to trial later this year. If
convicted, the defendants could face prison terms ranging from six
months to six years, he told The Associated Press.
   Those charged after a four-year investigation were former
managing directors Claes-Ulrik Winberg and Martin Ardbo, former
sales director Lennart Palsson and Hans Ekblom who had headed the
export division.
   ``It's not the company that's being prosecuted,'' said Bofors
spokesman Per Mossberg. ``In today's Bofors there have been some
major changes, and the company is now stronger than it was before.''
   Critics have said the allegations of misconduct in arms exports
have undermined the credibility of Swedish neutrality and the
leadership role that it claims in advocating world disarmament.
   Ekblom said through his lawyer that the deal in which he was
accused of illegal practices had been approved by the director of
the War Materials Inspectorate, Rear Adm. Carl-Fredrik Algernon.
   Algernon was crushed to death by a subway train at Stockholm's
central station in January 1987, a week before he was to be
questioned in the case. Police said they suspected suicide.
   ``The war materials inspector (Algernon) was informed about all
steps I took,'' Ardbo said in a Swedish Radio interview.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
