<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday June 22</NOTE>
<HEAD>Business Challenge: How To Keep the Good Times Rolling</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires. John Cunniff is on vacation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When your company's sales and earnings are
soaring, what's the problem? How to make the good times last.
   That is the textbook situation right now confronting Micron
Technology of Boise, Idaho, a manufacturer of computer memory chips.
   In the past few years, most American producers of so-called
dynamic random access memory chips, or D-RAMs, were driven out of
the business by intense competition from large Japanese
manufacturers.
   Joseph Parkinson, Micron's chairman, has described what happened
then as ``a hailstorm of illegal selling of products here in the
U.S. at below their foreign-made cost to produce.''
   When the United States and Japan reached an agreement covering
international trade in the chips, however, Micron, as one of the
few independent survivors, was suddenly in the right place at the
right time.
   With supplies of chips reduced and demand getting stronger all
the time, prices spiraled upward.
   After posting large losses in its 1986 and 1987 fiscal years,
Micron recently reported a $54.65 million profit for the first nine
months of its fiscal 1988, through June 2, on revenues of $187.09
million.
   In the last five fiscal quarters, Micron's revenues have climbed
from $22.8 million to $29.5 million to $43.2 million to $53.3
million to $85.6 million.
   You can't turn things around so drastically without attracting
the attention of Wall Street analysts and investors.
   Micron's stock, with its ticker symbol DRAM, has made regular
appearances lately among the most active issues in the
over-the-counter market's National Market System. From a low of $4
last year, the stock has jumped to as high as $26 this month.
   The question facing Micron's management, customers and its
followers on Wall Street is what happens to chip prices from here
on. Will the shortage persist even as Micron adds a new plant next
year and other, bigger companies size up the profits to be made?
   Expert opinion runs the full range from yes to no. One analyst
queried by the New York Times maintained that ``the shortage will
last well into 1989 and I think it's going to get worse.''
   Said an industry official: ``It will ease toward the end of the
third quarter and will end in the fourth quarter'' of this year.
   In this kind of volatile, uncertain environment Micron has just
disclosed a strategy aimed at increasing the stability of its
business and enhancing its once-shaky standing.
   Parkinson, the chief executive, announced that the company would
offer to sell chips to customers under long-term contracts that
couldn't be canceled, rather than the short-term contracts that
cover most of its sales now.
   The move isn't, he asserted, an attempt to grab the brass ring
of higher prices while they last, but rather an effort to assure
``reasonable prices on the assumption it's a long-term
relationship.''
   Actually, Wall Street analysts who follow the company say,
Micron has more on its mind than prices.
   In offering contracts to the big names of the high-technology
world, they say, it is trying to improve its position with those
manufacturers, and is turning away to a significant extent from the
distributors to which it sold most of its chips in the past.
   Richard Whittington and Elizabeth Dorsey, analysts at
Prudential-Bache Securities, called the decision a ``prudent step''
for what Ms. Dorsey described as ``basically a one-product
company.''
   ``It lessens some of the volatility in their business and
enhances the likelihood of their long-term success,'' they said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed June 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
