<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 24,0846</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday AMs, June 24, or Tthereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Limelight Is A Mixed Blessing, Hunthausen Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Being punished by the Vatican was not the kind of
notice wanted by Seattle's Roman Catholic Archbishop Raymond
Hunthausen, but he says it hasn't curbed his message.
   And listeners crowd around now to hear it more than before.
   ``Probably what I say will attract more attention,'' he said in
one of his rare interviews since his run-in with the Vatican,
adding that this makes him somewhat uncomfortable.
   At the same time, he said he feels that speaking out on
important issues such as poverty and peace ``is a responsibility
that is genuine in my life.''
   But he said he wants the spotlight on issues, not personalities.
``I want people to try to catch what I'm really saying and not
misinterpret,'' he said.
   Hunthausen, 66, whose full authority was restored a year ago
after it was curtailed by the Vatican for the previous year and a
half, has not backed away from his keen social concerns as a result.
   In his responsibilities as a bishop, he said, ``I don't feel any
constraints in what I think I should do and how I should do it. If
I'm at peace with the direction I feel I ought to pursue, I will
pursue it.''
   He has kept pushing causes he champions _ a higher state minimum
wage, low-income housing and nuclear disarmament. He continues to
withhold a portion of his federal income tax to protest the arms
race.
   He has appeared at protests at the Bangor nuclear submarine base
west of Seattle, chided state legislators that the $2.50 hourly
state minimum wage is ``an embarassment'' and criticized Seattle
city leaders for rampant downtown development at the expense of
low-income housing.
   Whenever Hunthausen appears at a public event, the news media
are there. Tourists flock to St. James Cathedral to hear his
soft-spoken but outspoken sermons.
   In disciplining him, Rome claimed he was too flexible about
granting annulments, general absolution for sins, intercommunion
with Protestants and letting gay Catholics meet in Catholic
churches.
   During the time his authority was limited, Vatican appointee
Bishop Donald Wuerl had charge of many diocesan functions.
   While the clampdown on Hunthausen pleased some conservatives, it
also sparked an outcry throughout the United States from priests,
nuns and lay Catholics.
   On May 26, 1987, a special commission of three U.S. bishops
assessing the situation announced that the Vatican had restored
Hunthausen's full authority, and a coadjutor bishop was being named
to assist him.
   The Vatican also transferred Wuerl, who has since been made head
of the Diocese of Pittsburgh.
   Hunthausen has described the shared powers relationship as
painful, humiliating and confusing, but said that he now is at
peace and believes he and the church are stronger for the
experience.
   Since the restoration of his powers, Hunthausen and his
coadjutor, Archbishop Thomas Murphy, have divided up some tasks,
but Hunthausen has final authority in all archdiocesan matters.
   Hunthausen describes himself as ``a rather shy, retiring
individual.'' He is still clearly reluctant to talk about the past
situation which he called ``very painful, extremely painful.''
   While it hasn't shackled his words or actions, he said , ``Being
human, I suppose that I will never be totally unaware of that
experience. You just can't.''
   At the same time, he said, ``I don't have any regrets'' about
statements or actions than led to the controversy. He added that he
does not feel he is being watched by Rome.
   He has to meet with the three-bishop panel one more time, ``and
then hopefully within a few more months we will see the end of
that.''
   He emphasized that any speculation that a deal was made in which
he would retire soon and Murphy would take over is wrong.
   ``There's nothing at all (to that), absolutely nothing,'' he
said. There was ``just no deal, never any conversation on it. It
never even arose.''
   Hunthausen said he's now in better health than he was a few
years ago when he suffered a heart attack. He also has had prostate
surgery.
   Since then, he's taken pains to eat better and exercise daily,
including taking hikes in his beloved Montana whenever he goes home
to visit relatives.
   ``I wish I had been doing that all my life, because my energy
level is certainly better on the ski hill than it was,'' he said.
   Also, archdiocesan programs that got started under Hunthausen,
such as a reorganization of priests and lay deacons to provide
adequate service with a diminishing number of priests had to be put
on hold for a while.
   ``We're going to move on now to implement that,'' Hunthausen
said. ``It's something we would like to have done many many months
ago but we were in such a state of flux.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs, June 24</NOTE>
