<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRoundup Adv24   06-21 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Roundup, Adv 24,0594</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday AMs, June 24, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's health care system could go
bankrupt unless physicians start refusing treatment to patients who
are terminally ill, says a Jesuit priest who is an authority on
medical ethics.
   The Rev. John J. Paris, professor of social ethics at Holy Cross
Hospital in Worcester, Mass. says medical experts estimate 270,000
Americans will develop symptoms of AIDS within the next three years.
   He told an audience of medical professionals that if the
projections prove accurate, the only way to avoid draining health
care resources will be for hospitals to give ``maximum medical
intervention'' only to patients for whom there is a ``realistic
expectation of benefit.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint international committee of Lutheran and
Anglican theologians says the time has come for ``immediate
establishment of full communion'' between the two traditions.
   The scholars say the chief remaining obstacle involves
differences over the historic succession of bishops, but this can
be resolved by mutual steps gradually converging the episcopal
lines.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NYACK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Christian and Missionary Alliance has
decided to move its international headquarters to Colorado Springs,
Colo., and expects the move to occur in the summer of 1989.
   Headquarters property in Nyack, 20 miles northwest of New York
City, is to be sold. The denomination, with 2.3 million members in
53 nations, emphasizes evangelism, and fields 1,245 missionaries in
40 countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOUTHPORT, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Reformed Church here has
overwhelmingly approved a proposal that the church unite with the
Congregational Union of Scotland, which is to vote on the proposal
in September.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Roman Catholic scholars _ four priests
and a woman Bible specialist _ have been named to serve for the
next four years on the Faith and Order Commission of the National
Council of Churches.
   Although Roman Catholicism does not belong to the council, which
includes most major Protestant and Eastern Orthodox denominations,
Catholics have served for more than 20 years on the commission,
which deals with doctrine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Silber, president of Methodist-related
Boston University, has assailed social activism by the United
Methodist Church.
   He says it is becoming an ``institution in which theology is
distorted and degraded by the trends of politics and intellectual
fashion.''
   He told the church's annual Oklahoma conference that ``too many
bishops, clergy and politically motivated laity ... appear to
arrive at passionately held political beliefs without benefit of
Scripture or serious reflection.''
   Acknowledging his own right-of-center beliefs, Silber denounced
the church's recent criticism of U.S. politices of nuclear
deterrence and opposition to aiding Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENEVA, Switz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Lutheran World Federation
have termed the recent summit meeting between President Reagan and
Soviet leader Gorbachev a ``sign of hope'' and urged further steps
to eliminate the ``threat of nuclear annihilation.''
   The Rev. Gunnar Stalsett, executive secretary of the
organization of 50 million Lutherans, and Bishop Johannes
Hanselmann, president, urged leaders of the two countries ``to move
ahead decisively in pursuit of their stated goal to eliminate all
weapons of mass destruction.
   ``We again urge both governments to honor the letter and spirit
of existing treaties and to keep outer space free from the testing
and deployment of offensive and defensive weapons systems.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs, June 24</NOTE>
