<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-21 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0533</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl C. Icahn conceded he lost the battle for
five seats on Texaco Inc.'s board after a New York investment firm
revealed it voted its key stake in favor of the oil giant's
management.
   Icahn had said he considered the 12 million votes cast by
Kohlberg, Kravis Roberts & Co. to be the key block in the critical
proxy contest at the Texaco stockholder meeting on Friday.
   Icahn had no comment Monday on whether he would continue to
pursue his takeover bid for Texaco or sell out. Analysts estimated
he could make a profit of nearly half a billion dollars by selling
his stake.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. says it plans to sell its
transportation businesses for more than $500 million to a joint
venture it is forming with Blackstone Capital Partners and managers
of the rail and water subsidiaries.
   The deal disclosed Monday would raise the total of USX asset
sales to $5.5 billion since David Roderick became chairman in 1979.
It also would pare USX's wholly-owned transportation businesses to
the petroleum pipelines and ocean-going tankers of its Marathon Oil
and Texas Oil & Gas subsidiaries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Japan have reached a trade
agreement that could double U.S. exports of beef and oranges to
more than $1 billion a year, according to U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton Yeutter.
   The agreement announced Monday calls on Japan to nearly double
its imports of beef by 1991. Japan also agreed to expand market
access for fresh oranges by 22,000 tons annually, to 192,000 tons
in 1990.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought withering crops in parts of the
nation won't mean hunger if it continues, but could mean disaster
for farmers and spiraling costs for consumers, Agriculture
Secretary Richard E. Lyng says.
   Lyng said Monday the worst threat to the agricultural economy is
in the Corn Belt, the Midwestern region where corn and corn-fed
livestock are raised. But problems also are looming for Southern
soybean growers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mississippi River's record low-water
levels caused by the drought in the Midwest and Plains have thrown
more roadblocks in the way of river barge shipping.
   Authorities warned Monday that sandbars exposed by the dropping
water are dangerous and claimed three lives over the weekend.
   ``A little rain at St. Louis is not what is needed,'' said Coast
Guard Lt. Phil Rhoades. ``A drenching of the entire Mississippi
drainage basin is needed, lots of water.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southland Corp. has agreed to pay
nearly $10 million to settle charges that a former division
conspired with other producers to fix prices of milk sold to
Florida schoolchildren, the state said.
   Past and present officials of Velda Farms Dairy of Miami,
formerly owned by Dallas-based Southland, acknowledged the company
participated in illicit price fixing, Florida Attorney General Bob
Butterworth said Monday.
   Southland, parent of 7-Eleven convenience stores, will help
Butterworth litigate cases against six other milk producers as part
of the agreement.
</TEXT>
