<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   06-21 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0507</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest dealers of Suzuki Samurais say their sales
slowly are beginning to recover from the damage done by allegations
that the sporty vehicles roll over too easily.
   The top 10 dealers say their June sales will be off from as
little as a tenth to more than half because of the critical June 2
report by Consumers Union, according to a survey by The Associated
Press.
   Separately, Consumers Union said Monday that it received a June
11 letter from American Suzuki Motor Corp. demanding a retraction
of its report, but rejected it, writing back that its report was
``wholly fair and accurate, and based upon properly conducted
tests.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has cleared former Attorney General
Griffin B. Bell in a civil suit alleging he libeled a former E.F.
Hutton brokerage manager in a 1985 report about the company's
check-kiting practices.
   The U.S. District Court panel found Monday that Bell, who had
been hired by Hutton to investigate the scheme after the company
pleaded guilty to mail and wire fraud charges, had not defamed John
Pearce.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has
unveiled a program that will allow people to trade in older IBM
personal computers for credit on its new Personal System-2
computers.
   IBM's announcement Monday came as Houston-based Compaq Computer
Corp., its archrival in PCs, announced a pair of personal computers
using the speedy 80386 microprocessor from Intel Corp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. has announced the resignation
of J. Jeffrey Campbell, who headed its restaurant business for more
than a year.
   Pillsbury also announced a series of other organizational
changes Monday that it said were designed to streamline its
structure of senior management.
   The company did not provide an explanation for the departure of
Campbell, who had responsibility since May 1987 for all of
Pillsbury's restaurant operations. He could not be reached for
comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 U.S. businessmen showed up for the
opening session of China's largest trade conference, seeking to
exchange economic know-how with their Chinese counterparts.
   The four-day U.S.-China Joint Session on Industry, Trade and
Economic Development in Beijing's Great Hall of the People began
Monday. It includes 1,000 Chinese from 22 provinces, who are
looking for U.S. capital and technology to fuel their drive for
economic modernization.
   The Americans mostly are businessmen from small or medium-sized
companies on their first trip to China to meet representatives of
Chinese industries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell Monday in the second-slowest session of
the year. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 20.09 to
2,083.93.
   Bond prices were narowly mixed.
   The dollar finished higher against most major currencies in
foreign exchange.
   Grain and soybean prices rose sharply, but livestock and meat
futures prices were mixed and oil and precious metals prices fell.
</TEXT>
