<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-21 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Skid as Post-OPEC Pessimism Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pessimism in the wake of last week's OPEC
meeting continued to wash over the energy futures market, sending
oil prices skidding lower.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate oil, the benchmark U.S. crude, fell 45 cents
Monday to close at $16 a barrel.
   John Azarow, a trader with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said WTI
had not traded at such low levels since the end of March.
   The July contract was due to expire Tuesday, and this
contributed to the sharpness of the decline, said Jim Fiedler, a
trader with E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc. The August
contract slipped 30 cents and the September contract fell 24 cents.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, home heating oil
fell 0.46 cent a gallon to 43.18 cents and unleaded regular
gasoline slipped 0.50 cent to 49.47 cents a gallon.
   ``There was no new news'' to drive prices lower, Fiedler said.
``It's just a continuation of pessimism in the
   Fiedler said the market was pressured by liquidation of long
positions _ contracts bought in speculation of a price rise _ taken
ahead of last week's meeting of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
   The OPEC ministers, unable to reach a new agreement that would
have limited production and raised the price of oil, extended their
current accord for another six months. This was bad news for the
oil market because the cartel already exceeds the self-imposed
quotas contained in the agreement.
   Reports that Saudi Arabia was discounting the price of its crude
deepened the market's pessimism on Monday, Azarow said.
</TEXT>
