<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     06-21 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields Up on Short-Term Treasury Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in the government's latest auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 6.51 percent on Monday, up from 6.44
percent last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 6.83 percent, up from 6.67 percent
last week.
   The three-month bill rate was the highest since May 31, when
they sold for 6.53 percent. The six-month rate was the highest
since Oct. 19, when the bills averaged 7.21 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 6.71 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,835.40 and 7.17 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,654.70.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate mortgages, dropped to 7.40 percent last
week from 7.46 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
