<DOCNO> AP880621-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco-Icahn Bjt   06-21 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn, Bjt,0732</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn Evaluating Options After Conceding Defeat in Texaco Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major defeat in his battle to force a buyout
of Texaco Inc. won't necessarily cost Carl C. Icahn a profitable
campaign, should he decide to sell his stake in the oil giant.
   Icahn, Texaco's biggest shareholder, is mulling whether to
continue his attempts to force a buyout of Texaco in the wake of
his defeat in a critical proxy battle for five seats on the
company's board of directors.
   Whatever his strategy, the corporate raider won't walk away
crying: analysts estimate Icahn could reap upwards of $450 million
in profit if he sells his 14.9 percent stake in Texaco to a third
party.
   Icahn conceded Monday that he lost the proxy battle after the
New York investment firm Kohlberg, Kravis Roberts & Co. revealed it
voted its 12 million shares _ a 4.9 percent stake _ in favor of
Texaco management.
   Saying he considered the Kohlberg Kravis stake the crucial
``swing vote'' in the contest, Icahn said: ``The closeness of the
race was indeed gratifying. I am, of course, sorry that I did not
win, but so be it.''
   Several large institutional investors had said previously that
they also voted in favor of management.
   It will take several weeks to actually sort out and count the
votes cast in the proxy fight.
   A Texaco spokesman said only that the company was ``gratified
that Kohlberg Kravis has voted ... in favor of management.''
   Icahn, Texaco's largest shareholder, sought the board seats as a
lever to pressure Texaco management into letting shareholders vote
on his proposal to buy the company for $60 a share, a bid that
values the company at $14.6 billion.
   Spokesman Neil Call said Icahn now is mulling ``whether to hold
the shares, sell, go for a hostile offer or look for a partner.''
   Icahn previously had said he would sell his shares if he lost
the proxy battle, but in the days before the annual meeting hinted
he might launch a hostile tender offer for Texaco.
   ``The ball's in Texaco's court _ if they want a discussion,''
Call said.
   Analysts said a third-party sale would be a logical scenario.
   ``He'll make at least $450 million in profits (by selling the
stock), so don't feel sorry for Mr. Icahn,'' said Bruce Lazier, an
analyst at Prescott, Ball & Turben Inc. He based his calculations
on Icahn's having paid about $35 a share for his stake and a
theoretical sale at about $50 a share.
   When considering Icahn's rate of return, ``he didn't do badly at
all,'' said Paul Ting, an analyst at Oppenheimer & Co. ``The stock
would have to fall very, very low before he starts losing money.''
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Texaco fell
$1.12{ a share to close at $46.87{, following Friday's drop of
$1.50 a share. It was the most actively traded issue, with more
than 2.6 million shares changing hands.
   Analysts believe Icahn was unable to muster enough institutional
support because of widespread skepticism about his ability to
finance the deal. Furthermore, investors typically resist voting
against management, particularly when a major reorganization is in
progress.
   Texaco management also skillfully drove home its restructuring
efforts by announcing on the eve of its annual meeting a $1.28
billion deal to sell 50 percent of its refining and marketing
operations in 23 states to Saudi Arabia.
   Kohlberg Kravis said in a statement that it backed Texaco
because it was impressed by the restructuring so far.
   The keystone of Texaco's restructuring plan was a $3 billion
payment to Pennzoil Co. to settle a lawsuit resulting from Texaco's
1984 acquisition of Getty Oil Co. after Pennzoil had made earlier
moves to acquire Getty.
   In addition, Texaco has begun selling off up to $5 billion worth
of marginally profitable assets, and a $1.7 billion distribution to
shareholders also is planned.
   Kohlberg Kravis sold its 4.9 percent stake in Texaco before the
meeting but retained its voting rights because it owned its shares
on record date for the shareholder vote.
   A spokesman said the firm remained ``interested in (Texaco's)
progress and hopes to maintain an ongoing dialogue with Texaco.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
