<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ClioAwards     06-21 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Clio Awards,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BBDO Takes Six Television Clios, Chiat-Day Wins Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The advertising agency BBDO has won six Clio
awards for television commercials, including two for a Diet Pepsi
ad starring actor Michael J. Fox and two for commercials for Apple
Computer products.
   BBDO, which also won Clios for a corporate ad for DuPont and a
retail services ad for PIP Printing, won more television awards
than any other agency in the U.S. television advertising segment of
the Clio competition.
   The award-winning work came from BBDO offices in New York and
Los Angeles.
   Awards were announced Monday.
   Chiat-Day Advertising, with offices in New York and Los Angeles,
won five television Clios, including two each for ads for Arrow
shirts and the regional telephone company Nynex. The fifth was an
ad for Foster Farms Chicken.
   The television Clio for the best national advertising campaign
went to the agency Cliff Freeman & Partners, based in New York, for
a series of ads for Philips Light Bulbs that show what can go wrong
when a bulb burns out.
   One of the ads showed a matronly woman wondering where the magic
has gone in her marriage as her husband slurps his soup at the
dinner table. After the light goes out, a snore, then a splash and
finally a gurgle can be heard as the old man apparently dozes off
into his soup.
   Two production houses, Pytka of Venice, Calif., and Rick Levine
Productions of New York, each won four Clios for television ads.
   Pytka won for its work with BBDO on the Apple computer ads in
the home entertainment and office equipment categories, for a
commercial for Bartles & Jaymes wine cooler and for an ad for
Perrier water.
   Levine won three Clios for its work with BBDO on the Diet Pepsi
ad called ``Apartment 10G'' that showed Fox scrambling out his
apartment window and across traffic in a driving rain to get a soft
drink for a pretty neighbor.
   Levine's fourth Clio was for its work with BBDO on the DuPont ad
called ``Bill Demby'' that showed a man who had lost his legs in
Vietnam playing basketball with his friends with the aid of
protheses, or artificial legs.
   Clio Awards, a private concern based in New York, had been
administering the Clio presentations for 29 years.
</TEXT>
