<DOCNO> AP880621-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-Citrus     06-21 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Citrus,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Pact Opens Up Japanese Markets to Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The easing of Japanese import restrictions
on citrus provides the Florida industry with virtually a new market
for fresh oranges and orange juice shipments, officials say.
   ``We have the potential for similar growth in orange and orange
juice that we have had with grapefruit,'' said Lee Bouldin,
international marketing director for the Florida Department of
Citrus.
   Florida grapefruit exports to Japan doubled in the past two
years following the removal of import quotas on that fruit. And
Bouldin foresees the possibility of equally good results with fresh
oranges and orange juice once the quotas are eliminated for those
two products.
   The trade agreement announced Monday in Tokyo by U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter calls for a phasing out of import
quotas for oranges by 1991 and for orange juice by 1992. Tariffs on
fresh grapefruit will be reduced over the next two years.
   ``It's clearly beneficial...a positive step forward for the
Florida industry,'' said Robert Behr, director of economic research
for the citrus department.
   If Florida's share of the Japanese market remains the same, ``we
can expect almost a five-fold increase in sales of orange juice to
the Japanese,'' said Behr.
   Florida's biggest competitor on the world market is Brazil.
   Japan is Florida's largest export market for fresh grapefruit,
and lowering tariffs will help any potential oversupply, Behr said.
   Florida has a bumper grapefruit crop this year and expects
record harvests into the 1990s.
   The U.S. Agriculture Department said total American citrus sales
to Japan could increase from $50 million to $150 a million a year
when the quotas are lifted. Yeutter said the agreement could double
U.S. exports of beef and oranges to more than $1 billion annually.
   American exports of fresh grapefruit to Japan totaled almost $90
million from January through November 1987, with most of that
coming from Florida, Behr said. This compared with $74 million for
all of 1986.
   For the current season, Florida growers have shipped 11,390,000
cartons equalling about 42 pounds each of fresh grapefruit to
Japan, Bouldin said. This compared with just under 9 million
cartons in the 1986-87 season and 6 million in the 1985-86 season.
   Executive Vice President Bobby F. McKown of Florida Citrus
Mutual said the agreement is beneficial ``in the short-term and the
long-term.''
   Florida Citrus Mutual, which is the state's largest grower
cooperative, and other state citrus groups helped pressure Japan by
filing a complaint with the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
charging Japanese orange and orange juice quotas were illegal under
the international trading system.
   McKown estimated that because of the agreement frozen
concentrate orange juice sales to Japan could go as high as 80
million gallons a year. Florida's total annual juice shipments,
domestic and foreign, now are about 210 million gallons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
