<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Summit-FarmSubsidies 1stLd-Writethru f02Press 06-21
0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Farm Subsidies, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0288,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deadlock Between U.S. Ambitions and European Caution</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 4 grafs new to UPDATE with talks continuing. Picks up 3rd
graf pvs bgng: The declaration ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economic summit, torn between U.S. ambitions
and the caution of the West Europeans and Japan, bogged down Monday
over President Reagan's call for an end to agriculture subsidies by
the year 2000.
   ``The situation is delicate. The discussions are very intense,''
a senior Canadian official said as negotiators searched late into
the night for a compromise between what he termed ``extreme
positions.''
   ``There may be the possibility of movement, and there may not,''
the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Negotiators for the seven industrialized democracies and the
European Community sought a formula to accommodate conflicting
stances in advance of crucial General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade (GATT) talks in December in Montreal.
   The declaration on farm subsidies, which ranked with Third World
debt as a major economic issue at the three-day gathering, was
expected to be included in the final communique that will be
released Tuesday afternoon.
   West German sources said the communique would contain no
reference to the United States plan for the elimnation of all
subsidies by the year 2000.
   A Canadian official said the officials faced ``a long night''
working on the farm subsidy draft after the Europeans stuck to
their position that the subsidies must be curtailed, but cannot be
eliminated.
   ``It is totally unrealistic,'' British Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson said of the U.S. plan.
   ``I think that it scares farmers in most parts of the world
unnecessarily if you do talk in terms of abolishing all government
support, all subsidies, by the year 2000,'' Lawson added in a
television interview.
   ``On the other hand, we have got to have some form of
multilateral disarmament on this issue.''
   British officials said Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, during
an hour-long closed session on the subsidy issue, urged the United
States and Canada to give the 12-nation European Economic Community
credit for its moves since 1984 to cut subsidies.
   At a special meeting last spring, the EEC instituted a system of
automatic subsidy cutoffs if farmers exceeded their production
quotas.
   But the West European agriculture remains heavily subsidized.
The farm program consumes two-thirds of the EEC's budget.
   EEC President Jacques Delors urged the leaders during Monday's
session to implement past pledges to curtail subsidies rather than
endorse the U.S. plan.
   ``There is a limit to what you can ask farmers to do,'' Delors'
spokeswoman, Francoise Le Bail, said Monday evening.
   According to figures produced by the 24-nation Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development, Japan provided a 75 percent
subsidy for its agriculture in 1986, compared with 54 percent in
1980. European Economic Community subsidies totaled 49 percent in
1986, up from from 36 percent in 1980. U.S. subsidies were 35
percent in 1986, up from 15 percent in 1980.
   Britain, France, Italy and West Germany, the four European
nations taking part in the summit, are all members of the EEC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
