<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Federated,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federated Lost $129 Million In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc. posted a $129
million net loss in its first quarter, largely due to costs
stemming from its unsuccessful battle to prevent a takeover by
Campeau Corp.
   Federated, which was acquired by Campeau last month following a
months-long battle, indicated its results during the quarter ended
April 30 included charges of $88.7 million related to tender offers
for Federated stock and of about $167 million before taxes for
stock option settlements, ``golden parachute'' severance agreements
and other payments stemming from the change in control.
   The figures were included in a financial statement Federated
submitted Monday to the Securities and Exchange Commission, the New
York Times reported.
   Cincinnati-based Federated had posted a profit of $50.1 million
in its first quarter of 1987.
   Excluding the takeover costs, Federated's profit declined to
$21.5 million during the latest first quarter. Sales fell to $2.45
billion from $2.46 billion in the year-earlier quarter.
   Quarterly results included the sale of four Federated store
divisions following the change in control, but did not include a
charge for a $60 million ``breakup fee'' provided for rival bidder
R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. when it agreed to withdraw in favor of Campeau.
</TEXT>
