<2ND_LINE>PM-Allegheny International,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Management Takes Lumps From Shareholders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc.'s dissident
shareholders say they are confident of winning a crucial proxy
battle for control of the troubled company's board of directors.
   The group, led by the New York investment firm Spear, Leeds &
Kellogg, is seeking seven seats on Allegheny International's
13-member board in order to oust Chairman Oliver S. Travers and
push an alternate Chapter 11 reorganization plan.
   Results of Monday's vote are expected to be released July 5,
Allegheny International said.
   The dissident group complained Monday that the management's
proposed reorganization plan could dilute their holdings by 75
percent.
   Martin Whitman, a New York adviser to Spear, Leeds & Kellogg,
said his preliminary plan would infuse $50 million from outside
sources, pay holders of the company's public debt more than market
value on their investments and exceed management's plan for
shareholder equity.
   But management defended its reorganization plan, which was filed
Monday in U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   ``When you look at companies that go through the reorganization
process, dilution is almost always a factor,'' Travers said.
   Management of the consumer products company recently told
shareholders that Bennett LeBow, the investor Spear, Leeds &
Kellogg recruited to help produce a competing plan, diluted
shareholders' equity by 80 percent in his reorganization of Western
Union Co.
   The management plan would leave current common shareholders with
a 25 percent interest in the company. If approved by shareholders
and the court, full payment would go to unsecured creditors in the
Sunbeam Corp., Sunbeam Holdings Inc., and Almet-Lawnlite
subsidiaries.
   The parent company's secured bank creditors, led by Mellon Bank,
would received full payment in cash. Other creditors would get
cash, notes based on contingent asset sales and common stock.
   Among current shareholders, those with common shares would end
up with 9 percent of the company, holders of $2.19 preference
shares would have 5 percent and holders of $11.25 preferred shares
would have 11 percent.
   Travers, meamwhile, told the shareholders the company plans
legal action if necessary to recover $32 million in loans made at 2
percent interest during the early 1980s.
   He said the investment bankers at Smith Barney appraised
Allegheny International at $663 million.
</TEXT>
