<2ND_LINE>PM-GM-Concept Cars,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM to Produce Two Concept Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. says it plans to market two
of its flashiest concept cars _ the Pontiac Banshee and Chevrolet
Venture _ by the early 1990s.
   The cars are on display at the automaker's Teamwork and
Technology exhibit, which ends today in Warren.
   The exhibit kicked off a national tour in New York in January
and has traveled to Chicago, Los Angeles, Dallas and Atlanta. Its
last scheduled stop will be in Toronto later this month.
   A senior GM official, who asked not to be identified, told the
Detroit Free Press in today's editions that the concept car
announcement is unusual because most of those cars never go beyond
the prototype stage.
   ``Our goal when we went into this was not to build a car that
was so far-fetched that we wouldn't be able to actually build
one,'' said Marietta Kerney, GM senior creative designer. ``We're
looking now at building a car that's very, very close to what
you're seeing right out here.''
   The concept cars were developed last year in an effort to dispel
criticism that many GM cars look alike and establish distinct
differences in the automaker's marketing divisions, said Stan
Wilen, executive designer for GM's Chevrolet-Pontiac Canada Group
and the Saturn Corp.
