<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   06-21 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commodities Still Higher; Japan-U.S. in Trade Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: leads with 6 grafs with consumer price report, picks up 3rd
graf, Wheat futures</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices, led by large increases for gasoline and
automobiles, climbed a moderate 0.3 percent in May, the Labor
Department said today.
   The increase followed gains of 0.5 percent in March and 0.4
percent in April and would amount to an annual inflation rate of
4.2 percent if prices climbed at the same pace for 12 months, the
government said.
   For the first five months of 1988, retail prices were rising at
an annual rate of 4.4 percent, the same pace as in 1987.
   There was no evidence that effects of the Midwestern drought
reached consumers in May. Grocery prices rose just 0.4 percent,
compared with a 0.6 percent increase in April.
   But on Monday, commodities prices were pressured still higher by
the merciless drought.
   Grain and soybean futures prices jumped sharply higher on the
Chicago Board of Trade. Except for wheat, all grain and soybean
futures shot up their daily allowable limits at the opening bell.
   Wheat futures were influenced less by the drought than were
corn, oats and soybeans because the winter wheat crop, which
accounts for 75 percent of U.S. production, is nearly finished
growing and is being harvested.
   After the close of trading, the National Weather Service issued
a six-to-10-day forecast predicting above-normal temperatures and
below-normal rainfall for the Grain Belt in the first five days of
next week.
   The stock market followed its busiest day of the year Friday
with one of its slowest, amid fears of higher inflation due to the
drought and of rising interest rates.
   Stock prices weakened as volume on the New York Stock Exchange
dropped to 116.75 million shares, the slowest since May 23. It was
about one-third the volume of the year's record high of 343.92
million shares traded Friday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials finished at 2,083.93,
down 20.09. Broader market indicators also fell.
   Elsewhere, bond prices were nearly unchanged from Friday; the
dollar strengthened against most currenices and gold prices fell
slightly.
   In Tokyo, the United States and Japan announced a trade
agreement that could double U.S. exports of beef and oranges to
more than $1 billion a year.
   ``My judgment is that this will turn out to be a landmark
agreement in U.S.-Japan economic relations,'' U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter said Monday following marathon talks
with Japanese leaders.
   The agreement calls for Japan to nearly double its imports of
beef by 1991, and phase out involvement by the Livestock Industry
Promotion Corp., which currently controls most beef imports. Japan
would be allowed to set tariffs of 70 percent in 1991, 60 percent
in 1992 and 50 percent in 1993 to allow Japanese farmers time to
adjust.
   Japan agreed to expand market access for fresh oranges by 22,000
tons annually, to 192,000 tons in 1990. After that, fresh oranges
from the United States would be permitted in unlimited quantities,
at the current tariff rates of 40 percent in season and 20 percent
off season. Quotas on orange juice also will be phased out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
