<HEAD>London Share Prices Head Higher After Weak Opening</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: will be led with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices headed higher Tuesday on the London
Stock Exchange despite a weak opening, with traders shrugging off
losses in Tokyo and New York.
   Traders described the turnaround from a slight retreat at the
opening as evidence of the market's underlying bullishness.
   ``We aren't just following New York and Tokyo,'' said one
trader. ``The tone here actually looks quite good.''
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 8
points, or 0.4 percent, at 1,852.0 at about noon local time, its
high for the day.
   Volume was 211.9 million shares, up from 155.2 million shares at
the same time on Monday.
   The market's turnaround came amid news that the Deutsche
Bundesbank, as expected, raised the interest rate on securities
repurchase agreements to 3.5 percent from 3.25 percent.
   Many London traders said the rise in West German rate means that
a hike in the British commercial banks' base lending rate can't be
far behind.
   Despite the jitters felt last week over the prospect of higher
interest rates, traders said Tuesday that the market appears well
prepared for such a move.
   ``We might even move higher (after a rate hike) as people heave
a sigh of relief and get on with it,'' said one trader.
</TEXT>
