<2ND_LINE>BC-Belgium-Boeing,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belgian Airline Sabena Orders 16 Boeings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgium's national airline, Sabena,
announced Tuesday that ordered 16 Boeing 737s as part of a plan to
renew and expand its fleet.
   Sabena Chairman Carlos Van Rafelghem declined to disclose the
value of the deal at a news conference, and company officials said
financing had not yet been worked out.
   In a statement, the state-controlled company said it would have
``a completely renewed'' short and medium-haul fleet by 1992, the
year the European Economic Community is due to create a single
market with freedom of movement for persons, goods, services and
capital.
   The order is for four 144-seat Boeing 737-400s and 12 111-seat
Boeing 737-500s. The aircraft will be delivered at the beginning of
the 1990s.
   The latest order plus previously placed orders for seven
126-seat Boeing 737-300s will bring Sabena's short and medium-haul
fleet of Boeing aircraft to a total 23 aircraft by the early 1990s,
the company said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
