<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Aviation     06-21 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Aviation,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ministers Adopt Safety Measures For Summer Rush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation ministers of the 12-nation
European Economic Community have adopted emergency measures aimed
at improving air safety before the summer travel rush, officials
said Tuesday.
   The ministers agreed to set up a ``red alert'' telephone link
among Europe's five busiest airports: London, Frankfurt, Paris,
Rome and Madrid.
   In addition, a crisis center coordinating all West European air
traffic during the four or five busiest weekends of the summer is
to be established.
   The ministers were told during their meeting Monday that several
potentially serious air mishaps were narrowly averted in Britain,
Spain and Greece over the past few months because of overcrowded
skies.
   Proposals for more radical safety measures are to be considered
in October when the EEC transportation ministers meet again.
   The ministers' decisions were based on a report by civil
aviation directors in the 12 EEC countries that said air control
services were understaffed and ill-equipped.
   The report also called for linking the data banks of all of
Europe's air control centers, harmonizing computers and radars and
opening more of Europe's military air space to civil aviation.
   It also estimated that by the year 2000, the number of flights
throughout Europe will have doubled from present levels.
</TEXT>
