<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 0916EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Honda     06-21 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honda,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honda To Build Car Exclusively For U.S. Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda Motor Co. says it intends to develop a car
that would be sold exclusively in the United States.
   Nobuhiko Kawamoto, president of Honda R&D Co., the company's
research division, said such plans represent a departure from the
company's worldwide philosophy.
   In the past, Honda cars have been designed in Japan and sold
throughout the world with few modifications.
   Kawamoto also said during a news conference Monday that Honda
will remain in the subcompact car market despite shrinking profits
and increased competition from developing nations, such as South
Korea, Taiwan and Brazil.
   To remain competitive in this market, Honda will experiment with
several cost-saving measures, including increasing automation at
its new assembly plant at Marysville, Ohio, Kawamoto said.
   The appreciation of the Japanese yen, which has doubled in value
against the dollar over the last three years, is resulting in an
expansion of research and engineering facilities in the United
States, Kawamoto said.
   While Honda has no timetable for production of the totally
American car, Kawamoto said it would begin in the near future.
   ``As far as complete development, I think it will take time,''
he added.
</TEXT>
