<2ND_LINE>BC-Societe Generale,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rival Shareholders Try To Forge Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival shareholders in Societe Generale
de Belgique, Belgium's largest holding company, have begun
negotiations to try to reach an agreement on the future management
of the company.
   A dramatic and lengthy battle for control of Societe Generale
ended in April with a narrow victory for a group led by the French
company Cie. Financiere de Suez over Italian financier Carlo De
Benedetti, who had started the fight.
   At the special meeting two months ago, shareholders spurned De
Benedetti's bid to win board seats for himself and two allies,
dealing him a severe blow in his attempt to take over Societe
Generale, which controls a third of the Belgian economy.
   On Tuesday, Suez and its allies said they had started
negotiations with a group of shareholders led by de Benedetti with
the aim to ``permit the efficient management and development'' of
Societe Generale.
   In a joint statement issued after a shareholder meeting on
Tuesday, the two groups said that any final agreement, if forged,
would be announced Friday.
   De Benedetti and his allies control more than 40 percent of
Societe Generale. Suez, the Belgian insurer Groupe AG and their
allies hold a slim majority.
   Despite their apparent willingness to hold talks, the two groups
still appear to be at odds over who will manage the company. The
statement said that Suez, Groupe AG and their allies will vote in
favor of the nomination of Herve de Carmoy, a French banker, to
Societe Generale's board, while De Benedetti and his allies will
abstain.
   It is expected that De Carmoy will be asked to take over a large
part of Societe Generale's management.
   De Benedetti's group said in the statement that it will respond
to the appointment of a managing director ``at the proper time.''
   Societe Generale Governor Rene Lamy Tuesday predicted a ``solid
recovery'' in the company's 1988 net income. He further forecast
that Societe Generale's current earnings should double in the
period between 1987 and 1990.
   Societe Generale's net profit fell 43 percent in 1987 to 3.61
billion francs, or $100 million, from 6.33 billion francs, or $176
million the previous year.
</TEXT>
