<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn Opens Limit-Up; Soybeans Soar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of corn and soybeans opened
sharply higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with corn
futures soaring the limit for daily trading for the sixth
consecutive session.
   Wheat futures retreated on profit-taking as the winter wheat
harvest advanced.
   The drought in the Farm Belt showed no sign of easing and
futures traders continued to bet on lower corn and soybean yields.
   ``The real damage is being done in corn,'' said Richard Loewy,
senior grain and oilseed analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York.
   ``I'm looking at at least a 10-to-13 bushels-per-acre decline''
in corn yields, or about a 12 percent drop from last year, Loewy
said.
   Skyrocketing soybean prices triggered an increase in the Board
of Trade's daily price limit on soybean futures from 30 cents to 45
cents a bushel for three days beginning today. Limits on corn
futures dropped back to 10 cents a bushel today after three days at
15 cents.
   The Agriculture Department's weekly crop progress report issued
Monday found most of the U.S. corn crop in fair condition and most
soybeans in fair to good shape as of Sunday. The survey found the
winter wheat harvest more than 20 percent complete.
   In early trading, wheat was 3{ cents to 5{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.97 a bushel; corn was 10 cents
higher across the board with July at $3.34{ a bushel; oats were 5
cents to 10 cents higher with March at $2.96 a bushel; soybeans
were 10{ cents to 45 cents higher with July at $10.46{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher and pork futures were sharply higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .40 cent higher with August at
64.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent to 1 cent higher
with August at 70.70 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent to 1.50
cents higher with July at 46.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were 1.18 cents to 2 cents higher with July at 43.15 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mixed on Monday.
</TEXT>
