<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0330</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced this morning on news
of lower-than-expected consumer price increases, easing anxiety
over inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 10.66 points
to 2,094.59 as of noon EDT on Wall Street.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues rose 0.44 to 152.40. The
American Stock Exchange market value index rose 0.82 to 305.94.
   Gaining issues outnumbered losers by about a 7-to-5 ratio on the
NYSE, with 719 up, 502 down and 550 unchanged. Volume totaled 65.58
million shares in the morning, vs. 54.74 million shares Monday
morning.
   Brokers said stocks benefited somewhat from a relatively mild
rise of 0.3 percent in May consumer prices reported by the Labor
Department this morning.
   There was no evidence that a prolonged Midwest drought and other
inflation signals worrying the financial markets played a role in
the May increase, which translates into an annual inflation rate of
4.2 percent.
   ``I think this figure was better than expected, which gave the
market a little lift,'' said Hank Streifler, senior vice president
on the trading floor at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Texaco led the NYSE's most-active list, up \ to 47[ on volume
exceeding 1 million shares. Carl Icahn conceded defeat Monday in a
shareholder proxy battle with management of the oil company, but
the takeover strategist's next move remains unclear.
   IBM rose 1\ to 118]. The company unveiled a new group of
computers.
   Murray Ohio fell 2| to 55[. The company said it will be acquired
in a $56-a-share deal with Britain's Tomkins PLC, topping a hostile
$52-a-share offer from AB Electrolux of Sweden.
   Airline stocks were widely higher, reflecting a fare increase
for business travelers. UAL rose 1{ to 87\, NWA rose ] to 43{ and
AMR rose \ to 46|.
