<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks turned lower today in dull trading after
a brief boost that brokers attributed to news of a
lower-than-expected consumer price increase.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, up about 11
points by midday to the 2,094 level, backtracked to 2,081.61 by 2
p.m. EDT, down 2.32.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 0.39 to 151.57. On the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 0.35 to 305.47.
   Losing issues outnumbered gains by about a 7-to-6 ratio on the
NYSE, with 712 down, 607 up and 558 unchanged. Volume totaled
102.04 million shares with two hours of trading left.
   Brokers said stocks benefited somewhat in the morning from a
relatively mild rise of 0.3 percent in May consumer prices reported
by the Labor Department. But an afternoon selloff by
inflation-sensitive bondholders spilled over into Wall Street,
depressing prices.
   ``The stock market has been tracking the bond market,'' said
Gordon L. Smith, head of institutional trading at Alex. Brown &
Sons Inc. in Baltimore. Texaco led the NYSE's most-active list, up
\ to 47[ on volume exceeding 2.6 million shares. Carl Icahn
conceded defeat Monday in a shareholder proxy battle with
management of the oil company, but the takeover strategist's next
move remained unclear.
   IBM rose ~ to 118. The company unveiled a new group of computers.
   Among other actively traded blue-chip stocks, Bethlehem Steel
fell ~ to 20{, General Electric fell } to 42] and Exxon fell { to
45}.
