<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Dow-ExxonPlant     06-21 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dow-Exxon Plant,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joint Venture Will Build Plastics Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow U.S.A. and Exxon Chemical Co. said
Tuesday they have formed a joint venture to manufacture material
for adhesives and sealants.
   The group will build a $20 million plant in Plaquemine, La.,
where Dow has a manufacturing facility.
   The companies will share equally in the capital investment and
expenses of building the plant and in profits from marketing the
styrenic thermoplastic elastomers it will produce, said L. Dennis
McKeever, Dow vice president for polyolefins and elastomers.
   McKeever said some current Dow employees at Plaquemine will be
involved in operating the plant, but it has not been determined how
many new jobs will be created.
   Applications for the materials include pressure-sensitive
adhesive tapes and hot-melt adhesives, said McKeever, who made the
announcement jointly with Jean Pierre L'Hermitte, Exxon Chemical
vice president for adhesion products.
   Potential future uses include the manufacture of roofing and
road construction materials, elastomeric rubber for footwear and
other specialty applications, McKeever said.
   The plant, scheduled to begin production in 1990, would make 70
million pounds a year of the styrenic TPEs, about 10 percent of
worldwide production. The Dow-Exxon venture would be the
second-largest producer after Shell Chemical Co., McKeever said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880621-0317 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1448EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-GermanRateHike     06-21 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-German Rate Hike,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Bank Raises Key Interest Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's central bank
Tuesday announced an increase in a key interest rate, sparking
criticism that the move could worsen unemployment.
   The securities repurchase rate, known as the ``repo rate,'' was
increased from 3.25 percent to 3.5 percent.
   A daily West German newspaper had reported last week that the
Bundesbank decided to increase the rate, which it pays to trade
securities in the open market. The rate had been unchanged since
November.
   Analysts said the central bank's move didn't constitute a sharp
policy reversal. They said it was a reaction to several new
economic trends, such as better global economic growth prospects,
rising inflation, and the strong dollar.
   ``It was an adjustment to a changed environment,'' said Hermann
Remsperger, chief economist at the Berliner Handels and Frankfurter
Bank.
   ``The (3.25 percent) rate was created at a time when the world
looked very differently from what it looks today,'' he said.
   But an increase in borrowing costs can often lead to slower
economic growth, some observers said. A leading member of West
Germany's Employees' Union said the decision ``endangers economic
growth and expansion of employment opportunities'' when joblessness
is already about 8.4 percent.
   ``Since the government up to now has failed in developing a
program for fighting unemployment, the responsibility for low
economic growth must be tied to the monetary polities of the
central bank,'' said Employees Union board member Ursula Konitzer.
   In a news release, the Alliance of West German Labor Unions
(DGB) also blasted the rate increase, saying the Bundesbank was
using the higher dollar as an excuse to hike interest rates.
   ``Using this as justification to stop the danger of inflation is
not convincing, because current price increases have been 1 percent
for months,'' the DGB statement said.
   The dollar was hardly affected by the news, remaining steady
just below 1.7600 Deutsche marks, and West German bond prices
firmed during Tuesday morning.
   It isn't clear yet whether the rate hike was a one-time move or
the beginning of a string of interest rate hikes, said Remsperger.
``It will depend on the market reaction,'' he said.
   But Ute Geipel, chief economist at Citibank AG, Citicorp's
Frankfurt subsidiary, said a further interest rate hike is only
likely if the U.S. Federal Reserve pushes up its own rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880621-0318 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1450EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-McKesson-Alco     06-21 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-McKesson-Alco,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McKesson To Acquire Alco Health Services For $500 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McKesson Corp. announced Tuesday it will
expand its wholesale drug distribution business by acquiring Alco
Health Services for $500 million.
   McKesson has agreed to purchase Alco, a drug and health care
products distributor based in Valley Forge, Penn., for $30 a share
in cash. A tender offer is set to begin June 27.
   ``The acquisition of Alco Health Services reflects our strategy
of focusing our resources on the distribution of prescription
drugs, health and beauty aids and general merchandise to drug
stores, supermarkets and mass merchandizers,'' said Thomas W. Field
Jr., president and chief executive officer of San Francisco-based
McKesson Corp.
   The company's businesses include McKesson Drug Co., one of the
largest wholesale drug distributors in the nation; Armor All
Products, automotive appearance products; and the McKesson Water
Division, bottlers of Alhambra Water in Northern California and
Sparkletts Water in Southern California.
   With the acquisition of Alco, McKesson's wholesale drug business
will total 80 percent of overall sales, said company spokesman
Marvin L. Krasnansky.
   ``McKesson used to be a conglomerate, but now we are focusing on
what we know best,'' he said.
   Alco Standard Corp. owns 50 percent of Alco Health Services' 13
million outstanding shares. Under the agreement, McKesson, which at
present owns no Alco stock, will purchase Alco Standard's shares
for $30 a piece following the tender offer to the public
shareholders, Krasnansky said.
   McKesson had $7.3 billion in revenues and net income of $95
million during the fiscal year ended March 31, Krasnansky said.
   Alco's revenues totaled $1.7 billion for the fiscal year ending
Dec. 30. Net income totaled $18 million, he said.
</TEXT>
