<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0358</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks bounced around in a directionless pattern
today, buffeted by conflicting economic signals and futures-linked
computerized trading strategies.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks seesawed in a
narrow range, largely mirroring movements in the bond market. By 3
p.m. EDT the indicator was up 12.26 points to 2,096.19.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues rose 0.56 to 152.52. On the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 0.99 to 306.11.
   Gaining issues outnumbered losers by about 4-to-3 on the NYSE,
with 808 up, 601 down and 496 unchanged. Volume totaled 126.38
million shares with an hour of trading left.
   Brokers said stocks and bonds benefited somewhat in the morning
from a relatively mild rise of 0.3 percent in May consumer prices
reported by the Labor Department.
   But a selloff by inflation-sensitive bondholders, worried about
credit-tightening moves by the Federal Reserve, spilled over into
Wall Street and depressed prices by early afternoon.
   ``The market's been up and down,'' said Thomas Ianiro, partner
on the trading desk at William Blair & Co. in Chicago. ``We had a
pretty good report on the morning consumer-price figures. But I
believe the bond market gave us a false impression, then turned
around and slam-dunked us.''
   By late afternoon stocks were moving higher again as bonds
recovered. There also was a spate of demand triggered by
computerized trading programs that profit from price differences
between stock-index futures and stocks.
   Texaco led the NYSE's most-active list, up 1 to 47~ on volume
exceeding 3.3 million shares. Carl Icahn conceded defeat Monday in
a shareholder proxy battle with management of the oil company, but
the takeover strategist's next move remained unclear.
   IBM rose 1] to 118{. The company unveiled a new group of
computers. IBM's main rival Digital Equipment fell 1 to 109{.
   Among other blue-chip stocks, Bethlehem Steel fell } to 20|,
Boeing rose 1\ to 55~, General Electric fell \ to 42~ and McDonalds
rose { to 44{.
