<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2209EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Beef     06-21 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Beef,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Move To Bolster Agriculture After Market-Opening Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government leaders Tuesday moved to shore up
Japanese farming after acceding to American demands to lower
barriers on imported beef and oranges.
   Key Cabinet ministers and officials in the governing Liberal
Democratic Party emerged from a hastily called meeting Tuesday
morning with a broad outline of steps to ease the transition for
the nation's farmers.
   They included trimming production costs, subsidizing farmers,
buying up farmland and encouraging tangerine growers to convert
their plots to other uses, according to a statement released by the
government.
   The measures were announced one day after Agriculture Minister
Takashi Sato and U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter signed
an agreement that could double the imports of American beef and
oranges by 1991 to $1 billion a year.
   The agreement came after months of negotiations and complaints
by the United States against Japan's restrictive import quotas.
   Also Tuesday, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and
Fisheries announced Sato would head for Australia on Wednesday to
work out a new beef import pact with officials in Canberra.
Australia provides about 60 percent of Japan's beef imports, while
American beef accounts for about a third.
   The government statement called for ``drastic measures'' to
stabilize the price of Japanese beef calves, said to cost about 10
times as much as their American equivalents. Many Japanese beef
producers rely on calves sold by breeders.
   The news release also called for developing new markets to boost
demand for Japanese citrus but gave no details on any of the
proposals.
   While American cattlemen and citrus growers welcomed the new
accord, Japan Agriculture Ministry officials said they were still
trying to assess the effect Monday's agreement would have on
Japan's farmers. The Asahi Evening News said the price of Japanese
beef could plunge to half the current level, but gave no time frame
and quoted no sources.
   One hundred grams, or about 3.5 ounces of Japanese bee,f now
sells for about 450 yen, or $3.56 _ double the local price for
American beef.
   An official at a major trading house said the trade pact, which
calls for Japan to nearly double its imports of beef in three years
and erase its quotas on imported oranges after two years, was
already worrying fishermen, suppliers of a chief protein source
that is still cheaper than home-grown beef.
   ``This is just part of the iceberg,'' said Hiroshi Kawakubo of
Nissho Iwai's Feed and Livestock Department. ``When we see below
sea level, we see a very serious impact to the entire agricultural
system.''
   Ryokichi Morishita of Daiei, Japan's largest supermarket chain,
said it was ``thinkable'' that more trading firms and meat
producers would try their hand at raising beef cattle overseas,
much as automakers have done to avoid steep production costs at
home.
   Nissho Iwai's Kawakubo said a handful of corporations are
already producing beef bound for Japan in Australia, where land and
calf prices are cheaper than in Japan and the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
