<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-21 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Soar; Wheat Retreats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought fears drove futures prices of corn, oats
and soybeans up their limits for daily trading Tuesday while wheat
futures retreated on profit-taking.
   The National Weather Service's latest six-to-10 day forecast for
hot, dry weather in the Midwest through the end of the month
underpinned the rally and threatened further damage to the corn,
oat and soybean crops, analysts said.
   ``With the corn crop, each week that goes by without rain means
another 10 percent is lost,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst with
Research Department Inc. in Chicago. Some experts estimate anywhere
from 10 percent to 30 percent of the U.S. corn crop has already
been ruined by lack of rain.
   Still, the Agriculture Department's weekly weather and crop
bulletin rated most U.S. corn in fair condition.
   Karlin said the soybean crop could hold out a little longer than
corn, but ``you're rapidly running out of this grace period before
rains are desperately needed. I think it'll be around the July 4th
weekend before yield losses occur.''
   Wheat futures dropped on profit-taking linked to the ongoing
winter wheat harvest, which is more than 20 percent complete,
according to the USDA.
   Skyrocketing soybean prices triggered an increase in the Board
of Trade's daily price limit on soybean futures from 30 cents to 45
cents a bushel for three days beginning Tuesday. Limits on corn
futures dropped back to 10 cents a bushel today after three days at
15 cents.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 13{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.89 a bushel; corn was 2} cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $3.34{ a bushel; oats were 9 cents
to 10 cents higher with July at $3.18 a bushel; soybeans were 10
cents to 45 cents higher with July at $10.46{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
