<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Gillette-Coniston     06-21 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gillette-Coniston,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Discuss Potential Buyers of Gillette</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two New York investment firms once offered to buy
large stakes in Gillette Co. to help the company fight a takeover
attempt by Coniston Partners, lawyers charged in opening arguments
in U.S. District Court.
   The investment companies were identified as Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co. and Forstmann Little & Co.
   They were named during opening arguments Monday in disctict
court where Coniston is trying to overturn last April's proxy vote
for four seats on Gillette's board. Gillette won the contest by a
52-to-48 percent margin.
   Gillette attorney Patrick F. McCartan said the investment firms
made their offers to help Gillette fight a takeover attempt by New
York-based Coniston and that the offers show Coniston is wrong in
arguing that Gillette misled shareholders by claiming there were no
buyers for the company.
   McCartan said Kohlberg Kravis proposed buying preferred stock
that could be converted into 40 percent of all shares outstanding,
and that Forstmann Little made a similar proposal.
   But Richard Ziegler, who is representing Coniston, said Gillette
lied when it told its stockholders there were no bidders for the
company during the proxy fight.
   Both sides claim the other ran an unfair campaign.
   McCartan said Gillette's financial adviser, Morgan Stanley &
Co., recommended against selling large interests in the company to
either firm.
   McCartan and Zeigler also disagreed over a chart that Gillette
ran as a newspaper advertisement two days before the proxy election.
   Coniston said the chart unfairly depicted the company's
relationship with Tito Tettamanti, a Swiss financier. Coniston said
Tettamanti is an investor but does not control Coniston investment
strategy.
   Gillette claimed Tettamanti controls companies connected with
Coniston behind the scenes and that Coniston violated federal
securities law by trying to conceal his involvement in the Gillette
takeover attempt. Coniston lawyers denied the allegations.
</TEXT>
