<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Belgium-Boeing 1stLd-Writethru f0192 06-21 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Belgium-Boeing, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0192,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belgian Airline Orders 16 Boeing Jets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 2nd graf to add price range; subs two
grafs for 5th graf to give jet prices and previously unannounced
orders; adds two final grafs after 9th graf to give 737 order
totals.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgium's national airline Sabena said
it has ordered 16 Boeing 737s as part of a plan to renew and expand
its fleet.
   Sabena Chairman Carlos Van Rafelghem declined Tuesday to
disclose the value of the transaction at a news conference, and
company officials said that it had not been decided yet how Sabena
will pay for the planes.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes also would not give a value for the
Sabena order, but a company spokesman in Seattle said a price range
for the twinjet planes was $380 million to $444 million.
   The state-controlled company said that it would have ``a
completely renewed'' short- and medium-haul fleet by 1992, the year
that the European Economic Community is due to create a single
market with total freedom of movement for persons, goods, services
and capital.
   Sabena and its charter subsidiary, Sobelair, ordered four
144-seat Boeing 737-400s and 12 111-seat Boeing 737-500s, to be
delivered at the beginning of the 1990s.
   Boeing spokesman Tom Cole said the price range per jet is $29
million to $33 million for the 737-400 and $22 million to $26
million for the 737-500, depending on options.
   In addition, Sabena holds two previously unannounced orders for
737-300s that will be delivered in April and May 1989. It already
operates five model-300s, which sell for an average price of $28
million.
   For its long-haul fleet, Sabena last year ordered five A340-300
long-distance jetliners from Airbus Industrie to be delivered in
1993.
   Van Rafelghem also said Sabena is seeking to associate with
several other European airlines to create a European airline.
Sabena would become the nucleus of such a plan, he said.
   The executive said Sabena has had contacts with KLM, SAS, Air
France, Swissair and Luxair.
   Van Rafelghem added that the company was also holding talks with
American Airlines on some sort of commercial agreement on the North
Atlantic route.
   Boeing now has 988 announced orders for advanced versions of the
737, including 754 model-300s, 111 of the -400 model, and 123 of
the 737-500s.
   The 737-400 made its first flight earlier this year, while the
737-500 is still in development.
</TEXT>
