<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Pillsbury-Spoor     06-21 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury-Spoor,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Chief Says Record Year Will Follow Disappointing 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. had a disappointing year in its
recently-completed fiscal 1988, but may have record results this
year because of the benefits of a major restructuring, Chairman
William Spoor said Tuesday.
   ``We over-promised and we under-performed,'' Spoor said of
fiscal 1988. ``It's simple and it's pretty clear. But that's all
behind us.''
   He told a gathering of food industry analysts that the company's
financial results for the year ending in May, expected to be
released in a week, will show earnings fell to between 80 cents and
85 cents a share from $2.10 a share a year ago, mostly because of
restructuring costs.
   Without those costs, Spoor said profits in fiscal 1988 would
have been $2.40 to $2.50 a share.
   He said sales amounted to about $6.2 billion compared with $6.13
billion a year ago.
   Pillsbury reported earnings of $181.9 million in fiscal 1987.
   Spoor, who retired as chairman in 1985 but returned in March
after Chairman John Stafford resigned, said his interim rule will
end by September when a new leader is chosen from outside the
company in time for the annual board of directors' meeting.
   ``It will be his responsibility to lead Pillsbury back to
premiership,'' Spoor said. ``We've got a marvelous group of young
giants (within the company), but they're just not there yet.''
   The restructuring, which included a write-off of $141 million in
the third quarter, ``cleared the decks of a great deal of dead wood
and debris from failures of past decisions,'' he said.
   The company in fiscal 1988 closed 30 of its Steak and Ale and
Bennigan's restaurants, decided to remodel 200 Burger King
restaurants and dropped its four other restaurant chains.
   Spoor said 1989 will bring record earnings despite plans to
invest $80 million in restaurant remodeling and $50 million in
marketing and improvements to restaurant operations, mostly for
Burger King.
   Even though Burger King sales increased with the addition of 400
new locations in fiscal 1988, individual store sales remained flat,
said Roger Headrick, Pillsbury's chief financial officer, who spoke
in place of former reaturant group head J. Jeffrey Campbell, whose
resignation was announced Monday.
   ``Our most critical current issue is the lack of growth in top
line sales,'' said Headrick, who noted that a 1 percent unit sales
growth at the company's 5,600 Burger King restaurants would
increase earnings per share by 3.5 cents. ``We need to bring the
customer back.''
   Spoor said the restructuring in 1988 included a ``flattening''
of the corporate chain of command. For example, Headrick said 100
positions have been cut at restaurant headquarters.
   Spoor repeated earlier statements that Burger King is not for
sale and Pillsbury is not a corporate takeover target ``to the best
of our knowledge.''
   ``Some of you in this room have speculated on potential and
likely acquirers and even friendly merger suggestions,'' Spoor
said. ``But you are badly off base.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
