<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NYSE-Profits     06-21 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NYSE-Profits,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYSE Says Firms' Profits Rebound From Record Loss At End Of 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Stock Exchange member firms that do
business with the public, slammed by the stock market crash last
October, rebounded in the first quarter of 1988 to post after-tax
profits of $745 million, the NYSE said Tuesday.
   The companies lost $1.48 billion after taxes in the fourth
quarter of 1987, a period that included the Oct. 19 crash, the
exchange said. The loss had originally been stated as $2.35
billion, but was restated to reflect tax credits arising from
unprofitable results.
   The exchange said 68 percent of the 393 firms reporting for the
quarter were profitable.
   Revenue in the first quarter totaled $13.0 billion, up 30.5
percent from $9.97 billion in the fourth quarter of 1987.
   Member firms' capital rose 2.1 percent to $36.3 billion from
$35.5 billion in the fourth quarter, the exchange said.
</TEXT>
