<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2108EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Kodak-Judge     06-21 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kodak-Judge,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Withdraws From Polaroid-Kodak Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal judge who ruled in Polaroid Corp.'s
landmark $5.7 billion patent infringement suit against Eastman
Kodak Co. withdrew from the case Tuesday because her late
mother-in-law owned $100,000 in Kodak stock.
   It was the second time in as many weeks that U.S. District Court
Judge Rya Zobel pulled out of a case because of an alleged conflict
of interest.
   In a statement tracing her involvement in the Polaroid-Kodak
case, Zobel said neither side objected to her mother-in-law's
holdings at the outset of proceedings in 1981.
   ``The court informed all parties (of the holdings) before
opening statements and the taking of any evidence,'' Zobel wrote.
``Throughout the 75 days of trial, Kodak's silence continued.''
   Zobel stated Kodak remained silent even after she ruled in 1985
that the Rochester, N.Y.-based camera company had violated nine
Polaroid patents when it entered the instant camera market. She
said Kodak also did not raise the issue during a lengthy appeal
process.
   Shortly after her mother-in-law died, Zobel on May 9 told
attorneys from both sides she intended to recuse herself from the
case because she and her husband had become the beneficiaries of
her mother-in-law's estate.
   The judge acquiesced after both sides encouraged her to continue
in the case and asked her for time to research the situation.
   But in a motion filed June 15 in U.S. District Court, Kodak
called for Zobel's immediate disqualification and dismissal of all
of her rulings in the case since October 1981, including the 1985
patent ruling.
   Kodak also recommended an award of less than $200 million to
Polaroid for any profits lost to Kodak's line of instant cameras
and film, which ceased production under a court order on Jan. 9,
1986.
   Noting the delay in Kodak's action, Zobel wrote:
   ``To date, neither party has submitted any authority even
suggesting the incorrectness of the court's stated postion. Indeed,
for the first time since October 5, 1981, Kodak asks for recusal.''
   Kodak spokesman Henry Kaska refused to comment on why the firm
waited seven years before objecting to Zobel's holdings, but said
there may have been some misunderstanding at the May 9 meeting.
   ``Our counsel had not understood the judge to have made final
determination to withdraw,'' he said. ``Our counsel understood the
judge asked the parties for their views on the subject and our
motion was in response to that request.''
   Harry Johnson, a spokesman for Cambridge-based Polaroid, said
the case was reassigned to Judge A. David Mazzone. He said Polaroid
believed Zobel's rulings would stand.
   The damages portion of the case is to begin in January 1989.
   Last week, Zobel withdrew from a proxy suit involving Gillette
Co. and Coniston Group case after learning that Gillette chairman
Colman M. Mockler was a fellow of Harvard College and a member of
the Harvard Corporation. Zobel is a member of the Board of
Overseers of Harvard College.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
