<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Pennwalt-Centaur     06-21 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pennwalt-Centaur,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennwalt Chairman Vows To Fight Takeover Attempt By Centaur</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Pennwalt Co. said Tuesday
the company would fight an buyout offer by Centaur Partners, and
rejecting a meeting with the investor group.
   ``We will strenuously fight any takeover attempt which we
believe not to be in the best interests of our shareholders,''
Pennwalt Chairman Edwin E. Tuttle said in a letter to shareholders.
   In a separate letter to Centaur, Tuttle rejected a meeting
requested by the group, saying management was in the best position
to restructure the company.
   In a news release, Centaur said the management's ``actions
reflect their concern with entrenching themselves in their jobs
rather than benefitting the shareholders who own the other 98.7
percent of the company.''
   Pennwalt's stock closed Tuesday up $1 at $80.75 a share on the
New York Stock Exchange. Based on its nearly 11.5 million
outstanding shares common sharse, the company would have a market
value of about $928.6 million.
   Centaur, which holds 7.6 percent of Pennwalt's outstanding
shares, had proposed a friendly takeover that it said would be ``at
a significant premium to the market price.''
   ``Our offer to negotiate with Pennwalt our possible purchase of
all shares at a premium in a friendly transaction still stands, but
in light of Pennwalt's reply, we are examining our other options,''
Centaur stated.
   The options include purchasing shares on the open market,
private negotiations with shareholders and merger, said Centaur
spokesman Mark Greenberg.
   In a related development, spokesman Peter McCarthy denied that
Pennwalt's efforts to sell its pharmaceutical division represented
an effort to thwart a takeover by enhancing the company's cash
position.
   ``We might not have announced our intention without the Centaur
Partners' move. But the decision to do so (consider selling the
division) was made several months ago,'' he said.
   Pennwalt's pharmaceuticals division accounted for about 11
percent of sales and 14 percent of operating earnings last year.
Pennwalt, which employs 9,000, had profit of $53.8 million last
year.
   Centaur comprises Melvyn J. Estrin of Washington, D.C., a
financier and real estate investor and former chairman of American
Health Services; Abbey J. Butler, president of C.B. Equities with
assets in excess of $500 million, and former chairman of Financial
World magazine; and Robert Nederlander, a lawyer and president of
Nederlander Organization Corp., which owns Broadway theaters, and
also part owner of the New York Yankees baseball team.
   The 138-year-old Pennwalt started as a salt manufacturer and now
makes products ranging from cough syrup to chemicals and smelting
precious metals for dentists and dental laboratories.
</TEXT>
