<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Drought-Streamflow 1stLd-Writethru f0146womanVeraAmesandVinceTrivelli
06-21 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Streamflow, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0146,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>May Streamflow Below Normal Over Half the Nation</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 14th graf bgng, `Month-end contents,' to CORRECT that
drought in 1986 was in southeastern states, sted western states</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Heat Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought has reduced many of the nation's
rivers and streams to record lows as it threatens navigation,
reduces electrical generation and makes beaches unusable,
government agencies said Tuesday.
   The U.S. Geological Survey reported that May had ``the lowest
percentage of (river) stations with flow in the normal to
above-normal range, not only for May, but also for any month in the
last six years.''
   The agency said 54 percent of 191 river measuring stations were
normal or better, down from 66 percent in April.
   ``In our South Atlantic Division we had a 33 percent deficiency
in power generation last week and 96 percent of the public beaches
at the division's reservoirs are not usable,'' said Bob Page,
assistant secretary of the Army for civil works.
   The Corps of Engineers has dredges at work trying to keep the
Ohio and Mississippi rivers open to navigation, Page added at a
news briefing.
   ``Normally we would expect conditions such as we have now to
occur in late August,'' added Maj. Gen. Thomas Sands, acting
director for civil works.
   And, said Page, ``We don't see any signs of its getting better
in the short term.''
   Page said low water has also affected electrical generating
capacity in the Pacific Northwest but that no electrical shortages
are anticipated because power is available for transfer from other
regions.
   The Geological Survey said the low flows reported at nearly half
the nation's streams and rivers included several record lows.
   The Saline River at Rye, Ark., dropped to only 10 percent of
normal flow, and there was only 15 percent of normal water in the
Tombigbee River at Coatopa, Ala.
   The Geological Survey reported streamflows of only 21 percent of
normal in the Peace River at Arcadia, Fla., and the Buffalo River
near St. Joe, Ark. The French Broad River at Asheville, N.C., at 40
percent of normal, also set a record low flow for the month.
   The survey said the combined flow of the nation's three largest
rivers _ the Mississippi, St. Lawrence and Columbia _ averaged 617
billion gallons per day during the month, 37 percent below normal
and the second lowest combined flow in 60 years. These three rivers
drain about half of the contiguous 48 states.
   Regionally, streamflows were lowest in California in May at 42
percent below average for the month. Flows were down 40 percent in
the Great Basin of Nevada and Utah, 29 percent in the Pacific
Northwest and 18 percent in the Southeast.
   Month-end contents of many reservoirs were lower than those of
May in previous drought years, 1987 for the West and 1986 for the
southeastern states.
   Reservoir levels were in the below-normal range in North Dakota,
Montana, Idaho, Wyoming, California and Nevada.
   Below-average levels were also reported at all five sites in the
Tennessee Valley, Clark Hill Reservoir in South Carolina and
Georgia and Lake Sidney Lanier in Georgia.
   The Great Lakes were in the normal range except for Lake
Superior, where the monthly mean fell below normal for the first
time since 1982.
   As for underground water supplies measured in wells, water
levels fell in the Southeast and Southwest. New lows for the month
were recorded for the sand aquifer near Memphis, Tenn.; the Eutaw
Formation at Montgomery, Ala,. and the Hueco bolson near El Paso,
Texas, and in a key well at Jackson, La.
   On the other hand, three record high flows were also recorded in
May _ on the Potomac River at Paw Paw, W.Va., on May 7; on the
Potomac downstream at Washington, D.C., on May 20; and on Seneca
Creek at Dawsonville, Md., on May 19.
</TEXT>
