<1ST_LINE>d f BC-TimesMirror     06-21 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Times Mirror,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Executive Moves in Times Mirror Organization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Times Mirror Co. has announced that senior
vice president Donald F. Wright will take over supervision of three
of its Eastern newspaper companies.
   Robert F. Erburu, chairman and chief executive officer, also
announced Tuesday that Edward E. Johnson, vice president of
planning and development, will become a group vice president
responsible for the consumer publishing group.
   Wright, who assumes his new duties immediately, will continue to
be responsible for Times Mirror Broadcasting and Times Mirror Cable
Television.
   Reporting to him under his new duties will be the publishers of
the Hartford Courant, the (Allentown, Pa.) Morning Call, and the
Southern Connecticut newspapers, the (Stamford) Advocate, and the
Greenwich Time.
   Johnson, who assumes the consumer publishing duties July 1, will
retain responsibility for Jeppesen Sanderson Inc. and certain
corporate development duties.
   Wright replaces Peter C. Goldmark, a senior vice president who
left Times Mirror on June 3 to become president of the Rockefeller
Foundation. Johnson will replace Herbert K. Schnall, who is
retiring.
   Times Mirror is a media and information company that publishes
the Los Angeles Times, Newsday, New York Newsday and the Baltimore
Sun newspapers, among others. The company also has interests in
broadcast and cable television, as well as book, magazine and other
publishing.
</TEXT>
