<FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 2327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Drought-HeatRdp 2ndLd-Writethru f0315 06-21 1172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Heat Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, f0315,1196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Doesn't Abate Drought, and The Heat Goes On</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-7, `Records for ... Colleen Reilly,' with 6
grafs to UPDATE with new record highs, cooler weather due in 4
northern states, fires in South Dakota, power outage in Lincoln;
picks up 8th graf pvs, `At the Blank ...' SUBS 19th graf pvs, `The
Coast ...' to UPDATE with river closed; picks up 20th graf pvs,
`Coast Guard ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos KOK1, APP1, JX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain fell Tuesday on part of the drought-ravaged northern
Plains, but the road-buckling heat wave around 100 degrees gave it
little chance of soaking in, and farmers with withered pastures
turned to ``hay hot lines'' to find cattle feed.
   On the lower Mississippi River, shrunken by months of low rain
in the Plains and Midwest, barges escaped from one low-water
bottleneck but faced at least one more.
   Temperatures hit record highs Monday on the last day of spring
across the central and eastern United States and repeated that
Tuesday for the first day of summer at more than 40 cities from the
Dakotas to the East Coast, the National Weather Service said.
   Thermometers didn't have far to rise to hit records Tuesday,
with Bismarck, N.D., cooling down overnight only to a low of 77, a
record. A few minutes after noon the city tied its record of 99 and
later warmed to 103 degrees.
   Records for high temperatures started toppling well before the
sun was even directly overhead. Milwaukee tied its record of 93 at
10:34 a.m., then broke it six minutes later and continued on to
101. Other records soon began falling across Michigan, Iowa,
Illinois, South Dakota, North Dakota and Indiana.
   The official highest reading in the contiguous 48 states was 114
degrees at Phoenix, Ariz., while Hill City, Kan., hit 111 and Sioux
Falls, S.D., reached 110. Twenty-three states reported at least one
city in triple-digit heat.
   A cool front is expected to sweep from Canada into North Dakota,
Minnesota, upper Wisconsin and upper Michigan Wednesday, dropping
temperatures into the 80s and giving some relief from the humidity,
the weather service said.
   Lightning ignited dry timber and grass in northwestern South
Dakota. Firefighters were trying to control one fire that burned an
estimated 5,000 acres, while another scorched at least 1,500 acres,
state and U.S. Forest Service officials said.
   Many utilities hit record peak loads and asked customers to cut
back their use of electricity. Iowa Electric offers price breaks if
industrial customers shut off electricity during peak demand, and
those who went for the price break included Kirkwood Community
College in Cedar Rapids and that city's public library, said
spokeswoman Colleen Reilly.
   An overload caused a brief power outage in Lincoln, Neb.,
Tuesday afternoon that darkened the state Capitol and parts of the
University of Nebraska-Lincoln. The outage halted a meeting of the
Legislature's Executive Board and prompted Sen. Bernice Labedz to
wonder aloud if the state paid its electric bill.
   At the Blank Park Zoo at Des Moines, Iowa, the staff was busy
keeping animals cool. ``We're also freezing fish in chunks of ice
and giving them to the seals. They're having fun with that,'' said
zoo keeper Kevin Drees.
   The heat actually kept swimmers and sunbathers away from
Chicago's beaches along Lake Michigan during the hottest part of
the day, said pool supervisor Joe Pecoraro said.
   Thunderstorms over northwestern Minnesota and eastern North
Dakota dumped as much as 1.7 inches of rain in spots Tuesday, not
enough to overcome the rain deficit. Wind up to 50 mph cut power to
10,000 customers in Brainerd, Minn., for several hours.
   ``We're really thrilled to death to see that rain. We needed it
bad,'' said Dale Johnson, who farms 4,000 acres of wheat, barley,
beans, corn and sugar beats near Mayville, N.D., with his father
and brothers. Mayville got 1.7 inches. ``We've been on our knees
praying asking the good Lord for rain,'' he said.
   Parts of Ohio got up to a half-inch of rain in a surprise
thunderstorm during the night. But it didn't rain at Clyde, where
florist Cliff Doebels paid $2,000 to bring in Sioux Indian Leonard
Crow Dog to perform a rain ritual. Crow Dog promised rain by
Thursday.
   Agricultural experts said the heat worsens the drought by
evaporating what little moisture remains in the soil.
   ``These real hot days _ 95 to 100 degrees _ are using more
moisture than we can stand to lose,'' said Harold Hunzicker,
agricultural adviser in Marion County, Ill. ``We're still hanging
in there, but that is not to say we couldn't have a disaster.''
   The effect of continuing heat and no rain shows in Montana,
where the state Agricultural Statistics Service reported Monday
that 71 percent of the state's spring wheat crop was in ``poor'' or
``very poor'' condition, compared with 62 percent a week earlier.
   At Dayton, Ohio, a hay hot line was started Tuesday for farmers
seeking fodder from as far away as Kansas to feed their cattle
because their own pastures are dried out.
   ``A lot of people haven't felt the need yet,'' said Agriculture
Department spokeswoman Alice Walters. ``But if this situation
worsens, we want to have everything in place.''
   The Coast Guard closed the shrinking Mississippi River to
commercial traffic Tuesday evening at Memphis, Tenn., so a dredge
could widen and deepen a 1,000-foot section of the river north of
the city.
   Coast Guard Cmdr. Michael Donohoe said the river, at a record
low level, would stay closed for up to three days, halting up to
1,800 barges.
   That section of the river has shrunk from 500 feet wide and 15
feet deep to 170 feet wide and nine feet deep, he said. The dredge
was to dig it out to 12 feet to 14 feet deep and widen it to 300
feet.
   The freeing of a 26-barge tow that ran aground near Rosedale,
Miss., reopened the 730 miles of the Mississippi downstream from
Memphis to the Gulf of Mexico, the Corps of Engineers said Tuesday.
   ``Once they got the grounded tow cleared out there was a
nine-foot channel,'' said Bob Anderson, a Corps of Engineers
spokesman in Memphis. ``But the channel is not very wide, and
there's a pretty wicked Z-style dog-leg, so traffic is moving very
gingerly right now.''
   The Ohio River at Mound City, Ill., was closed again while
tugboats worked to refloat a barge that ran aground late Monday,
said Coast Guard spokesman Rick Johnson at Paducah, Ky. That same
section was closed last week for dredging.
   Heat distorted railroad tracks in Mobridge, S.D., during the
weekend, derailing five cars of a Burlington Northern train, said
spokesman Al Wiegold in St. Paul, Minn.
   At Sioux Falls, S.D., the heat buckled 25 roads, about the usual
damage for the entire summer, said Delmer Van Ekern of the state
Transportation Department. In Des Moines, Iowa, pavement buckled
Sunday and slowed traffic on U.S. 6 and Interstate 235.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
